abstract: Meeting in Wall-street, New-York; at McClellan Meeting in Wallstreet
snippet: Meeting in Wall-street, New-York; at McClellan Meeting in Wallstreet
lead_paragraph: A meeting was held in Wall-street yesterday, of men styling themselves merchants and bankers, in favor of electing G.B. MCCLELLAN to the Presidency. The call for the meeting and the appearance of a stand erected on the corner of Broad and Wall streets, decorated with burning, streamers, &c., attracted only about 1,000 persons to that locality in the course of the afternoon. If the audience was composed of the merchants and bankers of this city, our reporter's preconceived notions as to the personal appearance of that class of people have been erroneous.

abstract: A couple of letters from our California correspondent ("Podgers,") mailed in July last, have come to hand. They have been through various adventures during the past four months, or during the time that the overland mails across the plains were interrupted by the hostile Indians. Probably the red men tried to read and comprehend them; but failing to do so, at last concluded to forward them to us. Most of the news, speculations and gossip that our correspondent then wrote is entirely out of date, and we give but a couple of characteristic paragraphs.

abstract: at Union Meeting, New-York
snippet: at Union Meeting, New-York
lead_paragraph: Another Union mass meeting was held at Cooper Institute last evening. The hall was crowded. Mr. CHAS. S. SPENCER, presiding, opened the meeting by presenting to the audience the vote of the soldiers deposited in his care, to be placed in the ballot-box. He said that the soldiers were fighting the enemy with the bullet and the ballot. Since the previous meeting of the club there had been another star added to the galaxy of our Union -- Nevada. [Applause.] She came without the curse of slavery upon her. [Applause.]

abstract: ARRIVAL OF THE FIRST MASSACHUSETTS CAVALRY. -- The First Regiment Massachusetts Cavalry, direct from GREGG's division, of Gen. GRANT's army, passed through this city on Sunday on their way home, their term of enlistment having expired. They numbered two hundred and fifty-eight men, and were under command of Lieuts. BRIGHAM and RUSSEL. This regiment has passed through very many hard battles, and has earned for itself a glorious reputation. At one battle alone, the battle of Aldee, Virginia, June 17, 1863, it lost 154 men and six officers. A vote was taken in this regiment to ascertain their feeling on the Presidential question, and when the votes were counted up it was found that of the entire command Gen. MCCLELLAN had received only EIGHT VOTES.

abstract: Dispatches from the Army of the Potomac say that since the return of the army to its old quarters all is quiet. Our entire loss in the late movement will reach about 1,500. We took 828 prisoners and four battle flags. The highest praise is given by all to the officers and men of the Second and Third Divisions of the Second Corps for their behaviour during the day. Gens. EGAN and MOTT, who commanded them, and Gen. SMITH and Col. MCALLISTER, commanding brigades, are particularly praised for the very able manner in which they handled their men. The charge made by the New-Jersey Brigade, under Col. MCALLISTER on the enemy, who had got in the rear of our forces, was one of the finest ever witnessed, and resulted in saving the entire position.

abstract: President Lincoln's Reelection a Quietus
snippet: President Lincoln's Reelection a Quietus
lead_paragraph: Shall rebellion be allowed to triumph in its last throes? Are we, who bore down upon it so effectively in its towering might, no[???] [???]o give way before it when it staggers in [???]kness? We do not need the evidence in JEFF. DAVIS' late speeches, or the testimony of the fugitives who are coming into our lines in constantly increasing numbers, to know that the tremendous drain of the last three years upon the resources of the Southern people is at last near its uttermost limit. In the nature of things it could not be otherwise. The census returns of 1860 presented the exact extent of these resources, particularly in respect to able-bodied population, the main element in war. They show that at that time there were only about a million and a quarter of white men between sixteen and fifty in all the eleven States which went into the "Confederacy." Not more than two-thirds of these, at the very most, could have been physically able to stand effective military service. We have lost by disease and battle about half a million since the war began. They, in the want of sanitary commissions, and of medical necessities, and by being oftener worsted in fight than we have been, have lost at least as many. There are then but about three hundred thousand left fit for military duty, in all these eleven States. But at least half of the area of these States has been so much reduced to our control as to be unavailable to the rebel government for conscription. Considering this, in connection with the fact that we have between sixty and seventy thousand of the rebel army in our hands as prisoners of war, it is mathematically certain that the rebellion is fast finding it an absolute impossibility to keep up its armies to the strength indispensable for its making any effective stand against us.

abstract: Proclaimed a Free State
snippet: Proclaimed a Free State
lead_paragraph: -- The highest courts of Maryland have overruled all the technicalities raised by the rebels and copperheads for an injunction upon Gov. BRADFORD, and he has issued his proclamation declaring that the free Constitution has received a majority of the votes cast, and will go into operation on the 1st of November. Thus the final act is consummated, and Maryland this day begins her life as a free State. It will hereafter rank as the most glorious day in her calendar. Right gladly do her loyal sisters welcome her to the long career of prosperity and power now before her.

abstract: The Registers for the various polling districts in each ward of the city meet this day, and continue their sittings to-day and to-morrow. It is the duty of every loyal citizen to personally attend to the registry of his own name. If he was registered at the last State election, his name will appear upon the poll-books, and registry is not necessary. But every loyal voter should see that his right to vote is fully set forth, and even if certain of his registry last year, let it be rendered doubly certain this year, for it will at this election, in this city, be more than ever necessary that every loyal vote be polled. We have positive information that in several of the Wards of this city attempts will be made by the Copperheads to put on the poll lists, by proxy, thousands of names of absent electors, to be duly represented and voted on election day! Let honorable citizens look sharply to this matter to-day.

abstract: A German Vote for the Union; Vote for the Union; Staats Zeitung on
snippet: A German Vote for the Union; Vote for the Union; Staats Zeitung on
lead_paragraph: The Staats Zeitung, in a labored editorial replying to our recent call upon the Germans for greater activity in this election, admits the truth of our assertion that the intelligent Germans are on the side of the Union party. It seeks to explain this interesting fact by the charge of "self-conceit" against this class, and by the allegation that they are beguiled through the humanitarian cry of "Anti-Slavery." As they are often gentlemen of much culture, who know from long reading the fearful effects of the system of human slavery in all lands where it has been tried, and as personally they have sacrificed fortune and country for liberty, we think the last point of the accusation is probably true. They undoubtedly can appreciate what liberty means, better than many of our native Americans, and they do unquestionably hate slavery, as men should, who have suffered under oppression all their lives. They were too intelligent to be deceived by the word "Democrat," as some of their ignorant countrymen, and they naturally joined the progressive and truly Republican party of this country. Their support of the Union party is all the more acceptable, because, as the Zeitung truly observes, many of them personally preferred Gen. FREMONT for President; but, uninfluenced by their personal prejudices, they feel now that their first duty to their country is to defeat MCCLELLAN and the Peace Faction. They are acting a truly patriotic part.

abstract: A grand Union demonstration took place at Elizabeth, N.J., on Saturday afternoon and evening. In the afternoon able and eloquent addresses were made to a large assemblage by Gen. F.S. CAREY and Hon. J.M. SCOVILLE, and in the early evening an immense procession marched through the streets of the town, bearing innumerable transparencies and making a brilliant display with torches. Newark, Somerville, Rahway, Plainfield and Bound Brook were well represented in the procession, and the houses and stores along the line of march were so generally illuminated as to give the impression that there were very few Copperheads in Elizabeth. In the evening Ex-Gov. WRIGHT of Indiana addressed as large an audience as Library Hall would hold. The demonstration throughout was one of the most successful and enthusiastic which has been made in New-Jersey during the present campaign.

abstract: at Young Men's Republican lican Union, New-York
snippet: at Young Men's Republican lican Union, New-York
lead_paragraph: The headquarters of the Young Men's Republican Union, on the corner of Broadway and Fourteenth-street, were thronged last evening with enthusiastic Republicans, who assembled to listen to WM. CURTIS NOYES, Esq., and Prof. CHAS. MANSFIELD, of Nyack. DEXTER A. HAWKINS, Esq., called the meeting to order, and, after a couple of songs from the McDonald Glee Club, introduced to the audience Prof. MANSFIELD, of Nyack, Rockland County, who gave the most flattering account of the prospects of the Union candidates in that Democratic stronghold. He said that, since the adoption of the Chicago platform, scores of old Democrats, who had voted nothing but the Democratic ticket for thirty years past, were coming over to the Union party. So great was the change that he did not consider it of the slightest importance what majority the Peace party got in this city; MCCLELLAN would be beaten out of sight in the State, whatever might be his majority on leaving New-York and Kings County. Prof. MANSFIELD spoke at considerable length upon the issues involved in the present contest, and was frequently applauded

abstract: The Territory of Nevada, which has just been admitted to the Union as a State, by proclamation of President LINCOLN, was organized in March, 1861. For this purpose about ten thousand square miles were appropriated from the northern extremity of California, and about seventy thousand from Western Utah. At the time of its organization the Territory possessed a population of very nearly seven thousand white settlers. The development of her mineral resources was rapid and almost without parallel, and attracted a constant stream of immigration to the Territory. As the population has not been subject to the fluctuations from which other Territories have suffered, the growth of Nevada has been rapid and steady. At the general convention election of 1863 nearly eleven thousand votes were cast; during the present year great accessions to the population have been made.

abstract: By the arrival of the steamer Hibernian yesterday at Father Point, we have one day's later intelligence from Europe. Additional failures are reported in Liverpool and Manchester. Letters from Brazil confirm the magnitude of the financial crisis in that country. So great was the popular excitement that the military were called out to preserve order, and the leading Rio de Janeiro were occupied by troops. The Emperor and Empress of Russia are on a visit to the South of France. The settlement of the Danish question is still delayed by the consideration of main points. American securities have experienced a slight decline.

abstract: Admiral PORTER reports that on the morning of the 28th Lieut. CUSHING, in command of Picketboat No. 1, blew up the celebrated rebel ram Albemarle, which was undergoing repairs in Albemarle Sound. After Lieut. CUSHING had performed his daring feat, a shot from a rebel battery on shore struck his little boat and destroyed it. He and one of the crew escaped. The rest were captured.

abstract: Estimate of Political Standing; Magazines for November
snippet: Estimate of Political Standing; Magazines for November
lead_paragraph: -- Harper's New Monthly Magazine (New-York: HARPER & BROTHERS) for November, opens with ROSS BROWNE's second paper on Arizona, and his adventures in the arid regions watered by the River Gila. It is profusely illustrated with clear sketches, and forms an article of great interest on a part of the world on which there is scarcely anything "in print" at present. "A Cruise on the Sassacus" describes vividly the excitements of chasing blockade-runners, and overhauling the "assorted cargoes" intended to minister to the wants of the Confederates, but transformed by the fortunes of war into prizes of no ordinary value. "Exploring the Magalloway," is a pleasant account of border rambles on the confines of Maine and Canada. "Ups and Downs" contains some curious episodes of family history, founded on the very questionable authority of BURKE, the Peerage Editor, a most blundering and incompetent successor to the DUGDALES and CAMDENE of old, who once dignified the study of genealogy. "An Unfortunate Princess," epitomises WREXALL'S lately published memoir of CAROLINE MATILDA, the ill-fated sister of GEORGE III., and Queen of Denmark. "The Decline of Tragedy " and "Woman's Profession Dishonored," complete the list of miscellaneous prose articles. Fiction is headed, of course, by DICKENS' Story, "Our Mutual Friend," now in its fifth month. Two or three new characters are added to the already crowded canvas. One of them, "Mr. Headstone," the official schoolmaster, testifies strongly to the author's impatience of the line and rule systems that would reduce all nature to the monotony of a "cut and dry" plan; the other, "Miss Jenny," the doll's dressmaker, is a slightly fantastic creature, redeemed from unreality by the author's genial humor, which is not incompatible with touches of genuine pathos. "My Refugees," is a story of the Southern War. "The Crow Child," "My Silver Spoon," and "On the Way to the Diamond Mines," are of a mere imaginative complexion. The "Monthly Record," "Literary Notices," "Editor's Table," &c., are prepared with the usual care that has always been conspicuous in the various departments of Harper's Monthly.

abstract: Triumph and Progress of the War; London Times on Impregnability of the South
snippet: Triumph and Progress of the War; London Times on Impregnability of the South
lead_paragraph: After every success of the rebels, great or trivial -- after every repulse of our arms at any point of the compass -- during every temporary surcease of active operations, the cry is sounded through the country that the war is a failure. At the present moment, this cry is very loud. The rebel army of the Southwest has moved from the point to which it was driven by Gen. SHERMAN, and has struck northward for Tennessee -- which nullifies, we are told, the magnificent conquests of the last three years in the Mississippi Valley. The rebel army of Virginia has just prevented GRANT from seizing the Southside Railroad -- which shows conclusively that Richmond can never be captured.

abstract: Hon J R; Speech at War Democrats' Meeting, New-York; Speech at War Democratic Meeting, New-York; Address to Democracy of the Union
snippet: Hon J R; Speech at War Democrats' Meeting, New-York; Speech at War Democratic Meeting, New-York; Address to Democracy of the Union
lead_paragraph: Vast as are the dimensions of the hall at Cooper Institute, it failed completely to accommodate the crowd of Union-loving, loyal Democrats that assembled last evening, and large numbers were unable to gain admittance. The body of the house, as well as the platform, was every where filled by men whom we have long been accustomed to see in the front ranks of the Democratic party -- the men whose ability and eloquence gave to that par[???]its great influence and hold upon the people. A reference to the list of Vice-Presidents shows names of those who, as Mr. CUTTING remarked, have "wintered and summered" in Democracy, and whose opinions must have so small effect upon the country. They represented every State in the Union. MOSES TAYLOR, Esq., called the meeting to order, and nominated for chairman FRANCIS B. CUTTING, whose appearance was greeted with a storm of applause.

abstract: We have a neat dispatch from Rear-Admiral PORTER, informing us of the destruction of the great rebel ram Albemarle, in the waters of North Carolina, on Friday last. The Albemarle will be remembered as the ruffianly secession ram which ran down the Roanoke River a half-year ago, and played such an important part in the capture of Plymouth and its garrison, and also as the insolent ram which received such a drubbing from the double-ender Sassacus, in one of the most gallant and remarkable naval fights of the present war. Even after this, she threatened terrible things, and tried to make herself the terror of the inland waters of North Carolina.

abstract: Savannah, Instruction Ship, Officers of; Kankakee, Cutter, Trial and Description
snippet: Savannah, Instruction Ship, Officers of; Kankakee, Cutter, Trial and Description
lead_paragraph: REVENUE MARINE -- TRIAL TRIP OF THE REVENUE CUTTER KANKAKEE. -- The United States steam revenue cutter Kankakee, built by WESTERVELT & SON, made her engineer's trial trip yesterday, and the results obtained proved her to be the fastest of the [???] of six new cutters recently built by order of the Treasury Department. The vessel left Mr. WESTERVELT's yard about 10 A.M., and proceeded down the river, "heaving-to" off the Battery to receive on board T.B. STILLMAN, Esq., Superintendent of Repairs and Supplies; Captains CONSTABLE, MERRIAM and MARSELLS. United States Revenue Marine; Mr. HOPPER WHITE and others. After 11 o'clock the Kankakee steamed down the bay, gradually increasing her speed until it reached about 12 knots per hour, the engines making as high as 36 revolutions per minute, and the screw turning 108 times per minute. Steam was at 22 pounds pressure, vacuum 27 1/2 inches, the cut-off following 12 inches out of 30 inches, or working steam expansively 18 inches. She has one tubular boiler. Her engines are oscillating, geared three one on the shaft; the cylinders are 36 inches in diameter, with 30 inches stroke, and were built by J. & R.J. GRAY, at the Phoenix Iron Works, in this city. The screw is 8 feet in diameter, with 12 feet pitch. The hull was built by WESTERVELT & SON, and is of the following dimensions: Length, 130 feet; beam, 26 feet; depth, 11 feet 6 inches. She is brig rigged and makes a very fine appearance upon the water. She steers beautifully, turning around in a very short space. She carries an armament of six guns, two of them being pivots. The after one is a 30-pounder Parrott, while all of the other guns are of the Dahlgren pattern. About 4 o'clock, after returning from a trip down the bay, Collector DRAPER came on board, and the Kankakee again steamed down the bay. The Collector was very much pleased with the vessel, and all the inspecting officers pronounced unqualifiedly in favor of this new craft. She will no doubt prove a valuable acquisition to the revenue-cutter service.

abstract: Roanoke, the; Capture of
snippet: Roanoke, the; Capture of
lead_paragraph: The officers of the captured steamer Roanoke arrived here yesterday, and the statement of the purser is possibly the most satisfactory account we are likely to get, although that is far from clear on certain most essential points. How many pirates came on board? How was it that they were picked up as ordinary passengers, boarding the Roanoke, as they did half way down the harbor of Havana? "On getting half way out the harbor," says the purser, "the steamer was hailed by three boats containing passengers, among them Lieut. BRAINE." We seek for information. Is it usual for the Havana steamers thus to make good their complement of passengers? Is it usual, especially, for merchant steamers flying the flag of the United States, and crossing the ordinary track of the pirates, thus to fill up with boats' loads of passengers wherever they are hailed? It seems to us that this statement of the extraordinary manner in which the pirates got on board the Roanoke ought to lead to an examination of the truth of the report current at the time of the capture -- that it was talked about, and anticipated in Havana, before the Roanoke weighed anchor.

abstract: The Confederate iron-clad ram Albemarle, reported to have been destroyed on the 28th ult. by the  United States picket boat No. 1, was built in the Roanoke River, for the purpose of clearing the waters of North Carolina of our naval vessels, and driving off the United States troops who were located at various posts.
lead_paragraph: The Confederate iron-clad ram Albemarle, reported to have been destroyed on the 28th ult. by the United States picket boat No. 1, was built in the Roanoke River, for the purpose of clearing the waters of North Carolina of our naval vessels, and driving off the United States troops who were located at various posts. On several occasions she has spread terror throughout that department, and has caused serious annoyance to our forces, both naval and military. On the 5th of May last the United States naval forces, consisting of the wooden gunboats Mattabesselt, Sassacus, Wualusing, Miami, Whitehead, Ceres and Commodore Hull, engaged the Albemarle and her consorts, Cotton Plant and Bombshell, and after a terrible conflict the Albemarle was forced to retreat, having been seriously damaged by she fire of our gunboats, but principally by the Sassacus.

abstract: -There are certainly some very remarkable campaigns being carried on at this date by the rebels. They have a novel political character attached to them. When HOOD was setting forth on his present campaign to the northward, JEFF. DAVIS delivered a speech at Augusta in which he said HOOD's object was to "help the Peace party of the North to elect their candidate." The Richmond Examiner, in like manner, told us a short time ago, that JUBAL EARLY, in the Shenandoah Valley, was "electioneering for the Peace candidate." Gen. PRICE, too, has been operating upon the same line in Missouri, for, beside his ravages and butcheries, he has had leisure and opportunity, during his travels, to mount the stump and deliver speeches for Little MCCLELLAN. These are surely very curious things.

abstract: The depression in financial and commercial circles showed little or no improvement. Failures were daily announced, and it is well known that the announcements would be far more numerous than they are but for the circumstance that in a large number of cases private arrangements were being made between struggling firms and their creditors. The new failures publicly announced include: GALBRAITH, BIGLAND & Co., merchants, London, for about £130,000; MANNING & COLLYER, hemp brokers, &c., London, for £100,000; SIMPSON & Co., of London, in the Brazilian trade, &c. The weekly returns of the Bank of England showed a decrease in the bullion of only £[???],805, and in the reserve of notes of £51,835. These figures were so much more favorable than had been anticipated -- as also were the returns of the Bank of France -- that they produced a very favorable effect on the Stock Exchange, and a more favorable turn prevailed than had been the case for many days. Consols advanced 1/2, closing at 88 [???]@7/8 for money; and miscellaneous securities participated in the improvement.

abstract: and the Late Battle
snippet: and the Late Battle
lead_paragraph: --Those who would understand the movement made by the Army of the Potomac on Thursday last, will find on the second page of to-day's TIMES a succint and comprehensive account of the entire operation, its plan, inception, execution and final issue. The Copperheads are, of course, already basely trying to use this movement of our troops for political effect. They are attempting to prove that GRANT made a final and fatal failure; to show by it that GRANT can never capture Richmond, and that the great rebellion can never be subdued. The Copperheads have rushed to these conclusions with the greatest haste and the utmost delight. But the fact is they are altogether overdoing this thing. The malignancy with which they seize on every incident to belittle and misrepresent the deeds of our armies, and to show the hopelessness of the Union cause, is producing disgust among all decent white men. They have neither pride in their country, pride in the achievement of its armies, nor self-respect. When they cannot daily find grounds ready at hand for maligning our soldiers, they invent false grounds.

abstract: Coburn, Jo; Letter on Recent "Sham Fight" With Mace
snippet: Coburn, Jo; Letter on Recent "Sham Fight" With Mace
lead_paragraph: COBURN, in a letter published in Bell's Life, thus refers to the "Great Sham Fights: "If MACE intended fighting, why did he stay in Dublin until Monday afternoon, and parade himself about the city, when he should have been secreted near the battle-ground, ready to enter the ring? And as I made the match to fight in Ireland on Oct. 4, how could he fight when he left Ireland the night before with his tall between his legs? Furthermore the stakeholder did not send the ropes and slakes belonging to the association, although the expenses were to have been borne alike. As for my not training, that would have been all in his favor; but I can assure MACE that I was trained enough to have met him, had he the courage to face me, and I have no doubt as to the battle resulting in my favor. I offered to give MACE £200 to fight me on British ground in America, but he had'nt the pluck to accept; and, to stop his bouncing challenges to the world, I agreed to take £100 and fight him in Ireland. He now backs out of his own proposition, and wants to gull me into fighting in England by the promise of an additional £100, to which I do not see fit to agree; but, providing I get the stakes, to which I consider myself justly entitled according to the rules of the ring, as MACE never showed on the ground, or even in the county, I will make a fresh match with MACE, and give him £300 to fight me in any part of the Queen's dominions in America, for £1,000 a side. To show how earnest I was in my intentions, I remained up to the end of the week in Ireland, and offered to give him the choice of ground there, but my friends and the public must be quite satisfied that he never meant to fight me at all, unless he could have the battle come off in England. To stop this letter-writing, I wish him and all his school to understand that I shall not fight in England under any circumstances. Had MACE been at the ringside and I not there, it requires no foresight to tell who would have got the money; and I therefore claim the stakes to which I am entitled." MACE says that he he will accept COBURN's challenge to fight him in Canada.

abstract: The Persia, which arrived at this port yesterday, brings two days later intelligence from Europe. The United States steamer Sacramento had been refused the privilege of coaling in England. No improvement was visible in financial and commercial circles, and failures were daily ...
lead_paragraph: The Persia, which arrived at this port yesterday, brings two days later intelligence from Europe. The United States steamer Sacramento had been refused the privilege of coaling in England. No improvement was visible in financial and commercial circles, and failures were daily announced. It is stated that the trial of FRANZ MULLER had been definitely fixed for the 27th of October. An alarming strike was in progress among the colliers of South Staffordshire. The Italian navy is to be reduced. The peace negotiations at Vienna had not terminated, owing to a disagreement on the financial question. The barracks of the gendarmes in Sollemoergo and Venetia, have been attacked and plundered by a band of insurgent Tyrolese.

abstract: Sacramento Pirate; Coal Refused in British Ports; Sacramento and Tallahassee
snippet: Sacramento Pirate; Coal Refused in British Ports; Sacramento and Tallahassee
lead_paragraph: THE SACRAMENTO AND THE TALLAHASSEE. -- The news from Europe which we publish to-day, relative to the refusal of a supply of coals for the Sacramento at British ports, will not be regarded as unsatisfactory if it is followed by the same rigid application of the British neutrality laws to the rebel pirates. The Tallahassee, the Florida and their companions can only become really formidable at this end of the great Atlantic highway by getting frequent supplies of coal at the various British Colonial ports, from Halifax to Nassau, or by the collusive aid of British merchantmen acting as tenders to the privateers. Lord RUSSELL might, with advantage, direct his attention to the British North American coaling stations.

abstract: Cortina's Surrender and the Chicago Surrender
snippet: Cortina's Surrender and the Chicago Surrender
lead_paragraph: We publish this morning CORTINAS' declaration of surrender to the French commander at Matamoras. It will strike every intelligent Copperhead at once, how remarkable is the coincidence in spirit and in terms between this offer of surrender by CORTINAS, and the proposed Chicago surrender to JEFF. DAVIS. CORTINAS, like MCCLELLAN's supporters, considers the struggle of Mexico for nationality "a failure," and certainly, we must admit that, though his action in this respect is not of the heroic order, he has infinitely more reason for it than our Copperheads. He relies upon the statements, official and unofficial, of the French invaders, that they only mean kindness and good-will to the Mexican people, just as the Chicago Cessationists rely upon JEFF. DAVIS, that, after all, he only means Union. CORTINAS looks to the Commander of the French for "magnanimity." VALLANDIGHAM and the Chicago Copperheads look to the Richmond conspirators for brotherly devotion. Both take the high ground of "unconditional surrender." CORTINAS hopes that the French Emperor's agent will make him a Brigadier-General. The Chicago man hopes that JEFF. DAVIS will permit him to become President of a portion of the United States.

abstract: and the Albemarle
snippet: and the Albemarle
lead_paragraph: -- The graphic description of the destruction of the Albemarle, which we publish this morning, forms one of the most romantic tales of the war. The gallantry, presence of mind, coolness and daring of Lieut. CUSHING have had few parallels in our own or any other time. His craft was little better than a ship's launch. His crew consisted of but a dozen men. The obstacles which presented themselves in ascending the Roanoke were of a kind only to be overcome by exertions of an almost superhuman nature. But the task was accomplished, as our readers will see, in a way which must command the admiration of the whole country, although at some sacrifice; only two of the party -- Lieut. CUSHING and one of his men -- escaping either death or capture. We question if the record of any navy can produce a case of more noble and indomitable daring than is to be found in this recital. Certainly we know of none attributed to one so young, Lieut. CUSHING not being more than 22 years of age.

abstract: and Sixth Congressional District
snippet: and Sixth Congressional District
lead_paragraph: In another column we publish an extended statement of the attempt made to harmonize the differences in regard to the Congressional nomination in the Sixth District. It seems that Mr. H.J. RAYMOND and Col. HAWKINS were nominated on the same evening by their respective conventions, and that various attempts have been made to secure some amicable and disinterested decision as to which of the two should withdraw. Mr. RAYMOND proposed to submit the matter to the judgment of three persons -- one to be chosen by each of the candidates, and the other by those two. All attempts, however, to agree upon the third man failed. The State Central Committee then took the matter in hand, but failed to secure the assent of Col. HAWKINS or his friends to any one of the numerous propositions which were made.

abstract: -It is expected that the great iron-clad Dictator will go down the bay to-day. She will probably go to the Compess Buoys, near Sandy Hook, where she will adjust her engines, experiment with ERICSSON's new gun-carriage, and test a number of so-called improvements. Lying at the dock of the Navy-yard her screw works up the mud, which seriously affects the boilers, &c. After the trip to adjust her machinery, she will return to the Navy-yard, be put into commission, when she will make a trip to Hampton Roads. Orders have been issued that until "further orders," they must not be allowed to drive her to exceed eight (8) knots. Very little information can be gleaned while on board from any one; all seem to have been pledged to keep her movements as secret as possible.

snippet: Charleston Mercury on Yankee Flunkies and Chicago Platform; Chicago Platform; Estimate of; and Failure of War; Charleston Mercury
lead_paragraph: Shortly after the "chivalry" compelled the hauling down of the old flag on Fort Sumter, their organ, the Charleston Mercury, discoursed thus: "Flunkey is a genuine Yankee word. It is only found in a Yankee dictionary, and is there defined by a periphrasis. The great WEBSTER, who understood Yankeedom thoroughly, calls it 'A term of contempt for one who is mean and low-spirited, perhaps from the Scottish flunkie, a livery-servant.' The word could only have its origin in a land where the thing itself had an existence. The animal flunkey, is an unadultered Yankee product. Recent events go to prove that it is not merely the exclusive, but universal growth of that region."

abstract: A Few Words to; And Hopes of the Rebels
snippet: A Few Words to; And Hopes of the Rebels
lead_paragraph: We believe there are considerable numbers of Democrats who have come to the conclusion that Mr. LINCOLN must and ought to be elected, but who will vote for Gen. MCCLELLAN because they wish to retain their hold of the party organization and the local nominations. If the choice rested with them, whether they would incur all the risks of MCCLELLAN's administration under his present influences, they would hesitate, and the most would vote for the Union candidate. But they see the tide of popular opinion. They are morally certain Mr. LINCOLN must be President, and as, in their view, one vote is of little importance, they prefer to remain with their old friends in the Democracy, and preserve their influence in the elections for the ward, town and county offices. They hope and believe one way, and vote another.

abstract: at Meeting of Marylanders in New-York

lead_paragraph: Tuesday being the day on which the new Constitution of Maryland went into effect, whereby the slaves of that State were made immediately and unconditionally free, a meeting of Marylanders residing in New-York and vicinity, was convened la the evening at the Club Rooms, No. 710 Broadway, to exchange congratulations over the glorious event. Although there was no public notice given of the meeting, a considerable number of Marylanders came together, in obedience to a most natural instinct, as it were, and gave vent to their jubilant feelings in speeches and resolutions, which will be found primed below.

abstract: SUBSTANTIAL RECOGNITION OF POLICE SERVICES. -- Of the fund of $60,000 which was raised soon after the great July riot, for disbursement among members of the police force and others who should receive injuries in suppressing riots, some $35,000 is left in the hands of the committee. They have decided to give Patrolman ROBERT B. DENNISON $200, and Patrolman FRANCIS F. MANN $150, on account of injuries sustained by them in putting down a riot in the Twelfth Ward (Thirtieth Precinct) at the last November election. Accordingly a check for the sums stated was yesterday placed in the hands of THOS. C. ACTON, President of the Board of Police.

abstract: The undersigned, counsel of Mr. JOHN B. MANNING, in view of the delay which has occurred in completing his examination, and the further postponement of the matter until Thursday, the 10th of November, which was occasioned by the imperative demands of the judicial business upon the time of Justice DOWLING, feel that it is due to him and to his friends to give to the public a brief statement of their own conviction of his entire innocence of the charge brought against him. The testimony in his behalf, in part already presented, will establish conclusively that he was in this city on the day upon which the robbery of the 7 3-10 Treasury notes is charged to have been committed, and that, on the evening upon which it is alleged that about 8 to 9 o'clock he passed two of the stolen notes in the neighborhood of Washington market, he was not out of his own dwelling in Allen-street a single minute after entering it at 5 o'clock. Adding to this the very highest testimony as to the character for integrity and honest industry of Mr. MANNING, and the fact that a member of one of the largest clothing houses in the City of New-York, has testified that on the same evening, in this city, one of the stolen notes was passed on him by a man who, he says, resembles Mr. MANNING, and yet positively swears, MANNING being present, that he is not the man, we consider that the whole question resolves itself into one of unfortunate mistake as to identity.

abstract: Collector DRAPER has allowed the use [???] [???] of the public stores to receive the packages of turkies and other good things for the soldiers and sailors on the James. All articles sent must be cooked, the turkies wrapped in white paper, and packed in straw, in boxes or barrels, marked "Our Defenders, City Point," and sent to GETTY's store, in the rear of Trinity Church, Trinity-place, from the 17th to the 20th, no later. What with our standing up for our brave boys at the polls, and remembering them on Thanksgiving, I think they will hit the rebels a harder lick than ever. Will the loyal newspapers please keep this before the people until the 20th, if Johnny Nook did try beef why should I not try turkey? G.W.B.

abstract: Meeting in New-York an Utter Failure
snippet: Meeting in New-York an Utter Failure
lead_paragraph: A remarkably small specimen of a McClellan mass meeting was held last evening at Union-square. Four stands were erected and decorated with flags and colored lanterns; bands of music were stationed on each stand, and every attempt made to attract a crowd, but it was useless; the affair was a perfect fizzle. Probably, at no one time during the evening there were more than two thousand persons present, and very many of these were passers-by, who stopped for a moment to hear the music, or to find out what the affair was about. There was no enthusiasm, no excitement, and the speakers were listened to by the boys (for they composed the greater part of the audience) with a sort of listless patience that was really amusing.

abstract: Rate of Disappearance of
snippet: Rate of Disappearance of
lead_paragraph: The rebellion has been deprived, by three years of war, of two-thirds of its original area. That, in itself, shows great progress toward its complete extinction; yet it but inadequately measures the real progress. The fact is, that, as the war proceeds, the resisting powers of the rebellion diminish in a constantly accelerated ratio; and there is every reason to believe that it will not take the same proportionate time to overcome the last stage of the rebellion that it did to prevail over the first.

abstract: ACADEMY OF MUSIC. -- The opera of "Rigo[???]etto" was given here very acceptably last evening. It had evidently been rehearsed with much care, and the result was a general and very agreeable air of completeness in the representation. Signor MASSI[???]ILIANI's Duke is certainly the best effort he has yet made. From the opening cabalotta to the jaunty air of the last scene, he was thoroughly admirable. We have never heard the quality and strength of his remarkable voice to greater advantage. Signor BELLINI was good as the Court jester, acting and singing (a little hoarsely, however,) with equal spirit. The smaller parts were well distributed, and the chorus and orchestra, under Mr. MARETZEK's direction, were thoroughly efficient. Mme. MORENSI's Magdalena was a very capital rendering of that small but important part.

abstract: Degenerate Sons
snippet: Degenerate Sons
lead_paragraph: There is coming a day, centuries hence, when all these tremendous events through which we are now passing, will stand forth in the broad light of history. Then, when as we may confidently believe, one Republican Empire shall hold the whole continent from the Arctic to the Isthmus, with almost unnumbered human beings in the enjoyment of such liberty and such prosperity as the world had never seen, with South as well as North, filled with free and happy communities, and all classes and races equal before the law, the youth of the country will study this grand revolution with even more interest than we now read the records of the war of Independence or study the history of the great French revolution.

abstract: Speech at Wall-street, New-York; Speech at Wall-street, New-York
snippet: Speech at Wall-street, New-York; Speech at Wall-street, New-York
lead_paragraph: The bankers, brokers and merchants of this city representatives of the capital, the enterprise and that enormous business interests of the Great Metropolis, met in mass in Wall-street yesterday afternoon, and took their stand on the side of the Union. This meeting, called under the auspices of the Lincoln and Johnson Central Campaign Club, brought out the solid men of New-York to a greater extent than any assemblage of the kind that has been seen during the campaign. It was estimated by good judges that three quarters of the capital of this city was represented there. The entire street was blocked up, from Hanover-street to far above William-street, by such an audience as is seldom seen collected together at one time, in one place, all actuated by the same motive -- a desire for the salvation and unity of their country. Men of all parties and creeds fraternized on that stand. Old Democrats like PETER COOPER, HIRAM WALBRIDGE and A.W. SPIES joining hands with MOSES H. GRINNELL, A.A. Low and GEORGE OPDYKE.

abstract: Democracy; Copperhead Assault on
snippet: Democracy; Copperhead Assault on
lead_paragraph: -- The great demonstration of the patriotic War Democracy on Tuesday night is producing a powerful effect among the Democrats of this city. The movement was in the hands of men who were of the highest repute, and their position in the Democratic party in other and better days was such as to give them, now as well as then, a large popular control. The Copperheads have undertaken to abuse these men personally and malignantly. They vituperate them as they vituperate all who are not on the side of JEFF. DAVIS. They attack them as ferociously as they assail the President and Generals of the Union. But it has little effect on the intelligent men who were members of the old Democratic party. They see the absurdity of the foul assaults, in the name of Democracy, upon men like CUTTING, DIX, WEBB, STEWART, ROOSEVELT, TAYLOR, WHITING and CODDINGTON, by Copperhead malignants and factious fag-ends. But let them assail and malign, and they will find out on election day how much they have gained by it.

abstract: Every mail strengthens the opinion I have so often expressed that Peru can only relieve herself from the embarrassment in which the Spanish seizure of the Chincha Islands has placed her, by complete submission to the Spanish ultimatum. The entire ministry of Peru have again sent in their resignations to President PEZET, on the plea of "Inability to conduct the public business in the face of so much unreasonable opposition to every measure they bring forward, and for constant calls for them in Congress to indicate a policy." The ministry asked for extraordinary powers from Congress to carry out their measures, and it was on the refusal to accede to this proposition that the ministry resigned.

abstract: - A grand Union demonstration and torchlight procession of the friends of LINCOLN and JOHNSON took place on Thursday night in Jersey City, and proved an entire success, there being many thousands of people out, both as participants and lookers-on. Beside, the Central Union and various ward clubs, bearing variegated lanterns, torches and banners, there was a large number of butchers and citizens on horses, veteran soldiers, the Jersey City Locomotive Works Association, trucks, wagons and carriages in great number. A delegation of several hundred was present from Paterson. The dwellings throughout the entire line were quite generally illuminated, and as the procession moved along fireworks were set off in profusion. Some attempt were made to creates disturbances, but in almost every instance the riotously disposed were punished on the spot, and six or eight were arrested by the police. The affair did not close until a late hour.

abstract: -- There is, we hear, an odd mixture of fury and consternation among the leading partisans of Peace-Secesh-Vallandigham Democracy, in Brooklyn, at the prospect of dangerous defection from their ranks. The War Democracy there, too, cannot swallow Chicago and surrender, and boldly say so. They hold a meeting tonight at the Brooklyn Academy of Music; and if it is anything like the Cooper Institute meeting on Tuesday last, it will be well worth attending. SICKLES and PIERREPONT will doubtless say something worth hearing. The leaders of the Peace Democracy in Brooklyn are already much frightened, and have lost their temper. They are engaged in personally abusing and berating their elder brethren who go for Union and for the war to sustain it, but the peace men do not vouchsafe a word in answer to their arguments.

abstract: Chickamauga and Olustee Escape from Wilmington

Hall, from Cardenas for New-York, all burned by the Confederate steamship Chickamauga, Lieut. WILKINSON, which left Wilmington on the 27th Oct. The M.L. Potter was burned Oct. 30; the E.L. abstract: Intelligence was received yesterday of further depredations upon our commerce by two new  rebel pirates, one of which, named the Chicka- mauga, and commanded by Lieut. WILKINSON, of the rebel navy, is believed to have run out of Wilmington on the night of Oct. 27. The other is called the Olustee, is commanded by a Lieut. WARD, and escaped from Wilmington on the night of the 30th ult.
lead_paragraph: Intelligence was received yesterday of further depredations upon our commerce by two new rebel pirates, one of which, named the Chicka- mauga, and commanded by Lieut. WILKINSON, of the rebel navy, is believed to have run out of Wilmington on the night of Oct. 27. The other is called the Olustee, is commanded by a Lieut. WARD, and escaped from Wilmington on the night of the 30th ult. The Chickamauga destroyed three vessels and bonded a fourth; the Olustee also burned three. Their crews were all sent into this port, and the scene of their depredations is chiefly on the track of vessels bound down the coast. Neither of the pirates are formidably manned, carrying only three guns each. A number of gunboats have already left in quest of them.

snippet: Nominated for First Congressional District, New-York
lead_paragraph: -- The Union Convention, held at Jamaica yesterday, nominated by acclamation Hon. HENRY G. STEBBINS for the short term vacancy, occasioned by Mr. STEBBINS' resignation. The bold and independent course of Mr. STEBBINS, and the reasons which induced him to cut loose from the peace-at-any-price influences of the Chicago Platform, should now receive a hearty indorsement from the War Democracy and all other Union men of that District. With proper effort, he may be returned to finish the term which he has so honorably begun.

abstract: Candidate 9th Assembly District, New-York
snippet: Candidate 9th Assembly District, New-York
lead_paragraph: -- In the Ninth District (Sixteenth Ward) SAMUEL C. REED is the regular Union and Citizen [???] candidate for the Assembly. He is a gentleman of ability and character, and has already served the district ably and acceptably for one term, and deserves the vote of every Union man. His nomination was indorsed by the German Republican organization on Thursday night. Mr. LAMONT, who is also a candidate, was put in nomination by the so-called Draper organization, but at a subsequent meeting his nomination was withdrawn and that of Mr. REED was confirmed. There ought to be no doubt as to the regularity of Mr. REED'S nomination, and no hesitation about supporting him.

abstract: Vote Conspiracy, the Projected
snippet: Vote Conspiracy, the Projected
lead_paragraph: The great reliance of the Democratic leaders is still upon the fraudulent vote. Even yet they hope to be able to use it to a large extent. This they expect to do mainly in the large cities of the North. Notwithstanding the exposure of the gigantic and outrageous army fraud, and notwithstanding the startling effect it has had upon the country, the more reckless and unscrupulous Copperheads are still determined that they shall not be baulked in their nefarious scheme of thwarting the popular will by fraudulent votes. Their scheme, as the evidence before the court-military has shown, was carefully planned, adroitly managed, and came very near to a successful consummation at the first effort. It went so far that it is feared it will even yet be difficult to prevent thousands of manufactured votes from getting into the ballot-boxes of this and other cities. This State, at all events, they are determined to carry by any means, however infamous -- though the shrewder of them have now given up all hope of carrying the country and electing their Presidential candidate. It was the State of New-York for which the army frauds were originally manufactured; and nowhere that there is yet the shadow of a chance to use them will they fail to make every possible effort to do so.

abstract: It is not believed by the Commissioners of Police that any serious disturbances will take place on the day of the coming election, but unusual precaution will be taken by President ACTON and Superintendent KENNEDY to preserve order and prevent disorderly conduct. The entire available force of the Metropolitan Police will be on duty. Extra men will be stationed at the polls in each district. Reserves will be held in readiness at every station-honse with conveyances to transport the men to any point with great rapidity. In all dangerous districts an extra reserve force will be kept. Strong patrol parties will traverse the streets in every direction during the day, and with these preparations, the large force at the disposal of the Commissioners and the determination to keep the peace of the city at all hazards, it will be a dangerous proceeding to attempt a riot. The Metropolitan Police Commissioners are also empowered to call out the militia should their services be required; but the necessity for such a call is not anticipated. The idea of closing the factories and stores on election day, which has been discussed by some, is not considered a good move. Every employer will certainly allow his men a chance to vote, but giving them the entire day to be devoted to idleness would not be conducive to the quiet of the city. At any rate, timid people may dismiss any fears of riot or bloodshed on the eighth of November. The police will be on the alert, and are competent to protect the metropolis, for, after all, the proportion of disorderly-disposed persons will be very small compared with the great mass of order-loving, law-biding citizens.

He should be elected, and can be, if the efforts be unflagging for him until the close of the polls.

abstract: Loyal Ladies' Meeting at Church of Messiah, N. Y.; Speech at Loyal Ladies' Meeting, New-York
snippet: Loyal Ladies' Meeting at Church of Messiah, N. Y.; Speech at Loyal Ladies' Meeting, New-York
lead_paragraph: A grand meeting of the loyal women was held last evening at the Church of the Messiah, under the auspices of the Young men's Union Club. At an early hour the Church was filled to its utmost, with one of the most respectable audiences ever gathered within its walls. Ladies of education and refinement who understanding the great questions and principles at issue, gathered together to indorse by their presence the actions of the Union party, who are working for the reelection of ABRAHAM LINCOLN as President of the United States, and a vigorous prosecution of the war, until rebellion is utterly and entirely extinguished. About eight o'clock the meeting was called to order by the President of the Young men's Union Club, who introduced as Chairman of the meeting WM. CURTIS NOYES.

abstract: The Chilian Government is still waiting for something to "turn up in Peru," in respect to the Spanish question, "in the meantime preparing for eventualities, and showing its patriotism and friendship for the neighboring country by acts permitted by international usage." An extraordinary session of Congress is to be held, "to deliberate on questions of greet importance;" but those questions are not indicated as yet. The attempted revolt of the Indian chief, ANTIL, of which I wrote you by a previous mail, is still attracting considerable attention in Chili. Apparently successful attempts are made to link this affair with the Spanish invasion of Admiral PINZON. It is asserted that a letter has been found, dated in August of last year, which says: "The squadron of our Queen is to go to Peru to seize one of its ports, and will afterward visit the Island of Chiloe, to gather men with which to make war on Chili and Peru, that we may become, as before, Spaniards." Proofs are also adduced that ANTIL had communicated with the officers of the Spanish gunboat Covadouga, who promised him "that things would soon change." But all this amounts to little, if true, and is of doubtful authenticity.

abstract: Schurz at German Mass Meeting, New-York
snippet: Schurz at German Mass Meeting, New-York
lead_paragraph: One of the most numerous, as well as one of the most intelligent audiences ever congregated in that edifice, assembled last night at Cooper Institute. The call was for a mass meeting or the German Unionists, and was most enthusiastically responded to, the hall being densely crowded by 7 o'clock, a large proportion of the audience being ladies. About half-past 7 o'clock the meeting was called to order by Dr. GOLDMARK, who nominated as President Dr. ERNEST KRACOWITZER. The Chairman responded in a few earnest remarks, cordially thanking the audience for the honor conferred upon him.

abstract: Olustee, the; three Vessels Burned by, >amp;c.
snippet: Olustee, the; three Vessels Burned by, >amp;c.
lead_paragraph: Capt. N.C. WALKER, of the bark Empress Theresa, of and for Baltimore, from Rio Janeiro, in ballast, reports: 1st inst., 1st 35° 30′, lon, 74° 10′, was boarded by the rebel privateer Olustee, Lieut. W.A. WARD commanding, who told us we were a prize to the Confederate States, and ordered us to get our clothing and go on board the steamer, which we did, when they immediately set her on fire, and went in chase for another vessel which was in sight; but night coming on, failed to find her; the men kept on board until the 3d inst., when in lat. 39° 18′, lon. 74°, we came up with the schooner A.J. Bird, Capt. FRENCH, of and from Rockland, for Washington, D.C., with a cargo of lime, laths and potatoes. The crew were ordered on board the steamer and the schooner scuttled. There was also to in sight at the time the schooner E.F. Lewis, of and from Portland for Philadelphia, with a general cargo, which was disposed of in the same manner as the Bird. The Olustee then ran for another schooner which was close by, and which proved to be the schooner Antelope, Capt. DOBSON, from Matanzas for New-York, and to which vessel we were all transferred, twenty-eight in number, after signing the usual parole. Capt. WALKER had its wife, child and sister, and also two passengers, who were all served alike. The pirates took possession of all the nautical instruments, and everything else of value that they could get their hands on.

abstract: Flores, Gen. at Ecuador
snippet: Flores, Gen. at Ecuador
lead_paragraph: The only news of special importance from this State is the death of Gen. FLORES, who died of a natural death. His death will be a great blow to President MORENO, whose staunch supporter he has been under all his difficulties. In fact, without FLORES MORENO would long ago have been driven from the country which he governs so sternly. Both MORENO and FLORES favored, it is believed, the European aggressions on this Continent, and both are charged with having sought an European, or rather French, protectorate over Ecuador.

Hundreds of fraudulent votes may, by timely care, be kept from the ballot-box, and every false vote suppressed is one Union gain. Let all for three days be vigilant, and here help on the good cause our brave boys are battling for at the front.

The assemblage was immense, and the entire arrangements were under the superintendence of Mr. LAWRENCE HARNEY, who performed his duties admirably. abstract: The proceedings at Montreal, before Judge COURSOL, in the case of the St. Alban's raiders, are represented to be very satisfactory. Several of the raiders were fully identified, as was also a large amount of the money stolen from the St. Alban's Bank.
lead_paragraph: The proceedings at Montreal, before Judge COURSOL, in the case of the St. Alban's raiders, are represented to be very satisfactory. Several of the raiders were fully identified, as was also a large amount of the money stolen from the St. Alban's Bank. The counsel for the United States had a consultation after the adjournment of the court on Friday, and determined to proceed with one case, reserving the right to proceed with the others. But if the prisoners are surrendered upon this one case, further steps will be unnecessary. The object of this movement is to close the case within a few days. Hon. JOHN ROSE has been retained in behalf of our Government. The returned veterans of the First Vermont Cavalry are ordered to assemble at Burlington, Vt., without delay, and hold themselves in readiness for further orders from the military authorities.

abstract: This article of commerce requires more trouble and care than cotton. When ripe in the Fall it drops to the ground, and is gathered by negroes. After being water-rotted in the bayous (or creeks) for some months, it is then taken out and sun-dried,then taken to the warehouse, hackled, cleaned and selected, put in bales, and freighted to New-Orleans, the best selections taken by contract, for the French market, at 15c. It is used in France by the furniture-dealers, mattress-makers and saddlers. It is there dyed, which gives it a glossy appearance similar to horse-hair, and mixed with it. The crop is short here, owing to the Government taking all the dry and cured for hospital purposes, and for want of labor. The contract here for France is a failure on the part of the contractors. It is used by the manufacturers North, by carriage-makers, saddlers, sofa and furniture dealers. It is not subject to delemation if put in dry places. It now takes the place of cotton in many ways, owing to the high price of the latter. T.B.J.

abstract: Independence; The Fixed Demands of
snippet: Independence; The Fixed Demands of
lead_paragraph: There are still, we understand, individuals who imagine that the South would come back to the Union under MCCLELLAN, if they could continue to hold their slaves and escape confiscation. We ask such to carefully consider what is our best evidence on this point. Is it not contained in the speeches of DAVIS, and the letters and addresses of the other rebel leaders in the different States? Do they not all declare unanimously and determinedly that the only condition of peace is their recognition as an independent Power? The recent speech, of JEFF. DAVIS at Columbia, which we copied the other day, repeats this with more intensity than ever, in the face of all his defeats.

abstract: The contest for the City Judgeship lies between Messrs RUSSELL, HOW[???] and STEWART, Mr. TULLY, of Mozart No. 2, having withdrawn from the course. Mr. How[???], Mozart, is evidently rapidly gaining on Judge RUSSELL, of Tammany, and it looks now as though he would outstrip him. He is a much more popular man, and, with his friends, is more energetically at work. All the while ORLANDO L. STEWART, the non-partisan candidate, but nominated by the Unionists, is rapidly adding to his strength. The more his character and ability are discussed, the more anxious are the public to put him on the bench, and secure an independent, uncontrolled and fearless Judge. There seems to be every indication of his success, but good citizens must keep to work to insure it.

abstract: Maximilian and his Patron
snippet: Maximilian and his Patron
lead_paragraph: Almost every other mail brings us ominous intelligence about the Mexican Emporer. At one time it is reported that he is at daggers drawn with the Mexican Priesthood; next comes, the rumor that MIRAMON has seized half his Capital; and now we have an item from Havana, which sets forth that NAPOLEON is so exasperated against Austria, on account of her conduct toward Denmark, that he has made up his mind to withdraw all his soldiers from Mexico, and abandon MAXIMILIAN to his fate. This comes from what may be regarded as a Spanish source, and is not entitled to implicit confidence, since Spaniards and Cubans would exult at the collapse of the Franco-Mexican Monarchy, and would be delighted to lend a hand, if they dared, to tumble it down. But if the intelligence proves authentic, it will be the worst news for poor MAXIMILIAN that has yet got vent. Of course it is well known that a division of the Franco-Mexican army is under orders for home, and it is equally well known that it has long been the intention of the French Emperor to withdraw the entire French force, the moment his protege shall have organized a mercenary army adequate to the defence of his throne. Recalling all the French soldiers instanter, however, without allowing MAXIMILIAN time to recruit an army, is a very different matter, and would be the death-warrant of the new Emperor and the new Empire. The throne of the Hapsburg has no root in Mexican soil. It is an exotic, which all classes and factions regard with dislike, and, when once the French disappear, churchmen and laics will come forward with equal alacrity to compete with each other in tearing it to pieces. If MAXIMILIAN were wise, he would divest himself of crown, purple and sceptre, pack up his imperial paraphernalia, and hie back to Europe with the departing auxiliaries. For if he remain long enough he may chance to fall a victim to the popular fury.

abstract: Maj.-Gen. G.B. McCLELLAN, U.S.A., reviewed the Democratic clubs, of this city, last night, from the balcony of the Fifth-avenue Hotel. The programme of the evening comprised a grand torchlight procession.
lead_paragraph: Maj.-Gen. G.B. McCLELLAN, U.S.A., reviewed the Democratic clubs, of this city, last night, from the balcony of the Fifth-avenue Hotel. The programme of the evening comprised a grand torchlight procession. The Ward organizations of the Democratic party assembled at an early hour in the vicinity of Union-square, bringing with them a variety of banners, transparencies, flags, mottos, Chinese lanfers, &c. After some delay, they were marshaled in some kind of order, and took up their line of march down the Bowery, through Canal-street, up Broadway and Fifth-avenue, past the Fifth-avenue Hotel, and from thence to their several Wards. It having been announced that Major-Gen. G.B. McCLELLAN, U.S.A., would review his forces upon this occasion, a tremendous crowd collected in the vicinity of his hotel, completely blockading the street, and for a long time resisting the efforts of the police to clear a passage for the procession. The General appeared on the balcony at about nine oclock, accompanied by his friends, and was greeted with cheers and shouts. He remained there until his forces and Gov. SEYMOUR's friends had passed by, receiving the applause of the assemblage for the masterly manner in which he conducted the review, which, as every one knows, is not a new thing to the hero of Manassas. The General's colors -- white flags -- were plentifully displayed by the ladies from the windows of the hotel. The whole thing passed off well, but the General is understood to believe that unless he receives large reinforcements, he will not have men enough to win his first battle on Tuesday next.

abstract: Col. Jos. E. HAMBLIN of the 65th N.Y. Volunteers, commanding a brigade in the Sixth Army Corps, under Gen. SHERIDAN, was the recipient of a seranade on Thursday evening, from the members of the 7th Regiment, National Guard (to which he was formerly attached), with GRAFULLA's full Regimental Band, at the residence of R.C. RATHBONE, in Forty-sixth-street. Col. HAMBLIN has recently returned from the Valley of the Shenandoah, where he was severely wounded at the battle or Cedar Creek, early on the morning of the 19th of October, while gallantly leading his Brigade in a charge on the enemy. Although faint from the loss of blood, and his horse killed under him, he refused to leave the field, and remained in command until late in the afternoon. The wound -- which is in the thigh -- is is improving, and he hopes to be able to resume his position in the front at an early day. Col. HAMBLIN has taken an active part in the war since its commencement, having originally left New-York in the Summer of 1861 as Adjutant of DURYEE's Zouaves.

RAYMOND for Congress in the Sixth District. Hon. E. DELAFIELD SMITH and Capt. C.H. MARSHALL enforced Mr. RAYMOND'S claims, and there was a warm indorsement by the assemblage.

abstract: Votes Conspiracy; What Can We Do ?
snippet: Votes Conspiracy; What Can We Do ?
lead_paragraph: The frauds in reference to the soldiers' votes continue to occasion great excitement and discussion and well they may, for their extent is likely to be enormous. The parties were proved to have forged large numbers of ballots before their detection, and one of them said that there were twenty men at Washington engaged in the business. This statement is enough to awaken a very painful apprehension everywhere, for no one knows where the fraudulent ballots may make their appearance. The Chairman of the Central McClellan Club of Brooklyn publicly stated that there were already in Brooklyn three thousand majority of soldiers' votes. Brooklyn men naturally ask whether these are votes written out by Donahue & Co., or by soldiers themselves; and so it must be all over the State.

abstract: It is suggested that challengers and inspectors of elections may be assisted in detecting the forged votes by keeping in mind the names of the officers whose names it has been testified were appended to the jurats. The one most frequently used was that of C.G. ARTHUR, who is variously represented to have been Assistan Adjutant-General and Assistant Quartermaster, with the rank of Captain. This man ARTHUR it is proved, has no existence. LEWIS J. OTTENOT had his name forged as Captain of the One Hundred and Seventh New-York State Volunteers, whereas he was only a Lieutenant in that regiment. Lieut-Col. J.M. MURPHY, Seventh New-York Artillery, has also been placed under arrest, changed with signing his name to the jurats fraudulently. Doubtless other names will be brought out in the course of the investigation.

abstract: We observe that by some parties Gen. WALBRIDGE's name is put forward as a candidate for Congress in the Fourth District. To avoid all mistakes and misunderstanding in the matter, we are authorized to state that he is not a candidate for any office at this election. Hon. CAROLAN O'B BRYANT is the Union nominee in the District, and if the full Union strength is cast for him, as it should be, his chances for election are good.

abstract: JOSEPH J. BINGHAM, editor of the State Sentinel, and Chairman of the Democratic State Central Committee; a Third Degree member and a Grand Councilor of the Sons of Liberty, testified before the Military Commission Oct. 28. as follows: I joined the American Knights in October or November, 1863, at Military Hall, then leased to the Democratic Club of this city. I was initiated then. Dodd, Harrison, M. Jacobs, Dr. Johnson, Vandegrift, and others were present. In August or September I was introduced to P.C. WRIGHT by DODD. WRIGHT gave his history and claimed to have found in the papers belonging to Gen. GAINES, of New-Orleans, the records of a secret society which existed during the Revolutionary war, of which Gen. LEE was President, and MADISON, JEFFERSON and WASHINTON were members. WRIGHT designed to establish a similar order, and had come to this State for that purpose. He said it existed in Missouri, Illinois and the Central American States and was to extend all over the world. He wanted BINGHAM to help him found it here, but he declined because he was opposed to secret societies. He asked other leaders to join. Most of them declined. It was understood that DODD was to be a member. DODD was an active leading Know-Nothing. DODD urged BINGHAM to join, and said it was political and educational. A State University, to inculcate sound political doctrine, and a newspaper were to be started. DODD said he wanted to advise with the witness about many things. He could not, unless he joined the order; that he could not even tell the names of the members of the order, for the obligation bound him to such secresy. He offered to put BINGHAM through informally. BINGHAM saw the seeds of discord for the party, if he did not join and unite the different elements against the Administration. DODD informed BINGHAM that he was a delegate to the State Council of November, 1853. He attended and took the Grand Council Degree. DODD presided. He was present but an hour, when he retired, and wrote his report, advising the postponement of the paper until funds were raised to support it a year, and the indefinite postponement of the University scheme. Dr. BRYANT and CUSHMAN were on the committee; he told CUSHMAN he could not stay, and got him to read the report; did not hear of any military appointments then nor until after the exposure of the sons of Liberty; he was notified by DODD to attend the Grand Council of Feb. 16; was in twice that day; heard CONKLIN, one of the Major-Generals, speaking; he was called on for a report, and replied that he had not drilled anybody, and had nobody to drill; it was his first idea that it was a military organization. BINGHAM said that he thought no good would come from the order, and HEFFREN coincided with him and said it was a humbug. He concluded not to belong to the organization; paid his fees and asked DODD if any formal withdrawal was necessary. DODD said he could withdraw when he liked. He didn't consider himself a member after that, though his having been in the Order gave him the confidence of the members, and he had learned many things he otherwise would not have known. Heard that DODD delivered an address on the 16th of February. At that meeting Dr. Bowling, Dr. Bryant, Mr. Blake, of Terre Haute, Mr. Cushman and Squire McBride, of Evansville, were present: also, Heffren. His next connection with the members of the Order was with Dodd, Bowles, Judge Bullitt, of Kentucky, and a Mr. Barrett, of Missouri, who met at his office. He supposed they were all members of the Order. Judge Bullitt invited him down to the Palmer House to take whisky. On the 2d or 3d day of August DODD called on him to issue, as chairman of the Democratic Central Committee, a call for a mass meeting on the 16th of August. He asked his word of honor that he would not reveal anything he might say. BINGHAM furnished it. DODD said a revolution had been determined on at the council of the 16th, held at Chicago, which consisted of four members from Indiana, four from Missouri, four from Illinois, and four from Kentucky, DODD, BOWLES and BULLITT were present. DODD said they arranged there to release the rebel prisoners at Johnson's Island, Camp Chase, Ohio, Camp Morton, Indiana and Camp Douglas, Illinois, and the released prisoners at Camp Douglas were to release those at ROCK Island. At the same time they were to rise in Louisville and seize the Government stores and property. BINGHAM was astonished. DODD wanted a mass meeting called, under pretense of opposing the draft, and instructing the Chicago delegates. BINGHAM refused. DODD wanted him to call a Congressional Convention to nominate a Congressman, as a cover for his revolution. BINGHAM refused. DODD went to MCDONALD to have him influence BINGHAM to call the convention. BINGHAM thought he ought to reverse the plot, and tried MCDONALD with the watchword, "What success," to know whether the secret had been intrusted to him. He found it had not, and imparted it to MCDONALD on Aug. 4. They could not determine what to do, and agreed to meet again. Next day, while going home, he met MCDONALD KERR, of New-Albany, and said, "What success." He answered, "Do you know anything? The people are all alarmed in our part of the State, in Washington, Harrison and Floyd counties, with the idea that a revolution is in progress. They are selling their crops because they think greenbacks safer." KERR went on and revealed DODD's scheme. Both then went to MCDONALD's. KERR told him his plot. BINGHAM did not then tell MCDONALD of his withdrawal from the Order, but was understood to still belong. KERR's information involved Dr. ANTHON. MORTON was to be put out of the way, and ANTHON to be Governor. They went to ANTHON's house, called him up, and he denied any knowledge of the plot. They met at MCDONALD's [???] morning, and invited prominent, Democrats to [???] them. McDonald, Judge A.L. Roache, Wm. H[???]son, Aqulila Jones, Samuel H. Buskorne, Jos. R[???], Dr. Yeagle, Col. Calllwell and others were there. KERR told his story. They said the revolution must be stopped. DODD and JOHN C. WALKER were called in. They did not then acknowledge anything about it. At first KERR told BINGHAM that if they would not abandon it, it was his interest to inform the authorities and have been arrested. DODD and WALKER then spoke very earnestly about public affairs, saying the Government could not be restored under the old state of things, and nothing would save it but a forcible revolution. An appeal to the ballot-box was futile; the people would resist the draft, and they ought to direct the revolution, rather than let it direct them. DODD and WALKER promised to stop it, and it was understood they sent such orders to the various counties. BINGHAM didn't inform the authorities, because he thought they knew it, because it was agreed that notice of the uprising should be given by publishing a barbecue near Louisville. The revolution was to take place the day after the barbecue. KERR said BULLITT and other prominent members of the order were arrested because of that notice, and that many left the State for Canada. BINGHAM thought this so important, that he called the Democratic Central Committee together Aug. 13, to consult on its effect on the party. Another reason why he did not inform the authorities was, because he didn't wish to injure his party in the coming election. There was danger of that, if the revolution was made public. DODD was here for two weeks and WALKER for ten days. He told them they would be arrested, and they left. DODD claimed that the scheme was true until KERR charged it upon him. At the two days' meeting of the Central Committee, Aug. 12, this revolutionary plot was discussed. They said the plot must be dropped. WALKER was called to that meeting, and assured the Committee that it was stopped, Aug. 11. WALKER told BINGHAM he must be at the Bates House to meet the rebel officers from Louisville, who were to consult him while en route to Chicago to release the rebel prisoners there, and notify them that the revolution was postponed. In August, about the time the arms were found in DODD's building, a messenger brought him a communication from DODD and WALKER, then in Chicago, professing to be addressed to the Committee of Thirteen, asking its publication in the Sentinel. He examined it, and refused to publish it. They proposed to publish it at DODD's office, but BINGHAM having an interest, said they should not publish it, and sent it back to WALKER, who said he wrote the address, and signed DODD's name as Chairman of the Committee of Thirteen. DODD was Grand-Commander. The men were sworn to obey him implicitly in this revolution. DODD expected assistance from members of the Order who came up to the mass meeting of Aug. 16, BINGHAM said no inducements or threats had drawn out this testimony. It was voluntary.

abstract: Army Reductions, Premature Announcement
snippet: Army Reductions, Premature Announcement
lead_paragraph: -The rumors which were put in circulation in British newspapers as to an intended reduction in the army are pronounced premature by the London Army and Navy Gazette -- whose authority is usually good. From the tone of the Gazette's correction, we take it that in no case wilt there be any reduction of the Imperial army, although that of India may possibly be cut down. We presume that these retrenchment rumors are put abroad in view of the coming Parliamentary general election. The state of the Continent of Europe is certainly not such as to invite any general disarming among those that wish still to be considered leading Powers.
