abstract: The Rochester Democrat states that on the day for registering votes, a prominent Democrat of one of the Wards of that city stated to the inspectors of election that he had one hundred and fifty soldiers' votes in his possession which contained only the McClellan electoral ticket, and inquired if he had authority to make up the deficient State and local tickets by adding there to the Democratic nominations! Singular and absurd as this statement was, the Board of Inspectors (Democratic) were divided in opinion, and could not decide the knotty question! The matter was accordingly referred to three of the leading lawyers in Rochester, Messrs. HENRY R. SELDEN, SANFORD E. CHURCH and WM.P. COGSWELL, for their opinion. Mr. CHURCH was the first one called upon, and gave as his opinion that the person holding the vote had undoubted authority to supply the deficiencies by adding State and local ballots to complete the set. Judge SELDEN was, of course, of a contrary opinion, holding the common sense opinion that it was the soldier and not the 'proxy' who voted, and whose will was to be consulted. Mr. COGSWELL gave the same decision. The Democrat states further that the ballots named were received unsealed and open to inspection and abuse. This is exactly contrary to the law, which provides that the ballots shall be sealed, and if opened before the day of election the vote must be lost. It thinks they are undoubtedly a batch of the lot manufactured by FERRY, DONAHUE and the negro, which, it will be remembered, were, according to FERRY'S confession, left deficient as regards the local and State tickets, and the deficiency was to be supplied in this State to suit the several localities. The Copperhead who had them in charge was, however, too green in the business to follow up the programme, and knew no better than to refer the case to the inspectors of election instead of doing it all himself. In this way he has revealed the plot, so far as he is concerned, by which one hundred and fifty forged votes were to have been pushed in next Tuesday.
lead_paragraph: The Rochester Democrat states that on the day for registering votes, a prominent Democrat of one of the Wards of that city stated to the inspectors of election that he had one hundred and fifty soldiers' votes in his possession which contained only the McClellan electoral ticket, and inquired if he had authority to make up the deficient State and local tickets by adding there to the Democratic nominations! Singular and absurd as this statement was, the Board of Inspectors (Democratic) were divided in opinion, and could not decide the knotty question! The matter was accordingly referred to three of the leading lawyers in Rochester, Messrs. HENRY R. SELDEN, SANFORD E. CHURCH and WM.P. COGSWELL, for their opinion. Mr. CHURCH was the first one called upon, and gave as his opinion that the person holding the vote had undoubted authority to supply the deficiencies by adding State and local ballots to complete the set. abstract: Vallandigham and the Chicago Creed
snippet: Vallandigham and the Chicago Creed
lead_paragraph: It deserves especial notice that Mr. VALLANDIGHAM, under his own signature, claims the paternity of the essential resolution of the Chicago platform, which declares the war for the maintenance of the Union to have been a "failure." It likewise deserves notice that this claim of his has not been disputed by the organs of the party. The very essence and soul of the platform is thus affiliated to a man who, while he had the power as a legislator, voted steadily and consistently against every supply bill for paying the soldiers, and maintaining the national credit. Apart from the second resolution of the Chicago platform, that instrument is a mere compound of meaningless generalities. A part from Mr. VALLANDIGHAM, even that positive feature of the concern would have been wanting. Whatever there is of honest, open declaration in the party creed is VALLANDIGHAM's, and his alone. He is the founder of the party faith, not by his own assertion merely, but by the confession of his confederates.

abstract: Affairs in
snippet: Affairs in
lead_paragraph: The last Oriental mail brought good news from New-Zealand to England. The Maori rebellion is virtually at an end. The victory of Col. GREER has broken the spirit and the power of the Waikato tribes, whose principal warriors, to the number of 150, repaired soon after to the British camp, sued for peace, surrendered their arms, and signed the declaration of allegiance in proof of their sincerity. These chiefs acted not only for themselves, but as the representatives of a formidable body of natives who were located in the neighborhood, and awaited information touching the issue of the negotiations, in order that, if the conditions were favorable, they, too, might make their submission. The conditions offered to the natives are certainly most favorable, as explained by the Governor; but it seems somewhat doubtful whether they will be honestly carried out. The good intentions of Gov. GREY need not be called in question, yet he may lack the power to realize them. His Excellency can accomplish little without the sanction of the Colonial Administration and Colonial Legislature, both of which are strongly opposed to the lenient policy. The Governor assured the Maori Chiefs that they should be well treated, and that only a small portion of their lands should be forfeited. Hardly, however, had he uttered this assurance when the Government, with their surveyors and auctioneers, were busy at work on a great body of territory, one-half of which they pronounced confiscated, and the other half they compelled the natives to sell at such prices as the robbers felt disposed to pay. The entire tract contains 47,000 acres, and of these, all were wrung from the rebels save 3,000. This is a pretty illustration of the value which should be attached to Gov. GREY's assurance, and of the disregard of the New-Zealand authorities for their sovereign's representative whenever, his ideas happen to clash with their own.

abstract: Speech at Brooklyn Union Meeting; Speech at Brooklyn Union Meeting
snippet: Speech at Brooklyn Union Meeting; Speech at Brooklyn Union Meeting
lead_paragraph: A grand mass meeting of the War Democrats was held last evening at the Brooklyn Academy of Music. Long before the doors were open a large crowd assembled eager for admittance, and within fifteen minutes after they were opened, every seat in the house was filled. Before 8 o'clock every aisle was also filled, and there was assembled within the building one of the most respectable and intelligent audiences, very many of whom were ladies, ever gathered within it. COLLETTIS' brass band furnished some excellent music. At 8 o'clock Major-Gen, SICKLES made his appearance upon the stage and was greeted with a hearty round of applause, the entire audience rising to their feet, the gentlemen cheering and the ladies waving their handkerchiefs. Three cheers were then proposed for Gen. SICKLES and given with a will, and scarcely had the audience resumed their seats when a gray-haired old gentleman rose and proposed "three more cheers for the hero of Chancellorsville." Again the audience sprang to their feet, and again the cheers were given as only strong patriotic men can give them. After the cheering had ceased, the meeting was called to order by Mr. E.T. WOOD, who said he had been deputed by the War Democrats of Brooklyn to call the meeting to order, and he wished to congratulate the whole country that there was a Democracy still left in this land, this glorious old United States, that did not believe in the Chicago platform [cheers;] that there was yet a Democracy which did not believe in a cessation of hostilities until the rebels in arms should cease to fire on the United States flag, and that there was a Democracy which did not believe this war to be a failure, and which could not discover any failure in the grand march of GRANT toward Richmond, nor SHERIDAN's glorious actions in the Shenandoah, [cheers,] and he wished to congratulate the audience that old JOE. HOOKER, a Democrat, had bravely carried the American flag even above the clouds, [cheers,] and that he and Democrats like him were ready to sustain the old flag and carry it safely through everything with which it might have to contend. Such Democrats as these had met at the Cooper Institute a few nights previous, and he was proud to say he was one of them, and he thought the audience would agree with him in saying that at that grand meeting they had framed a platform which would need no whitewashing, and one which the candidate it supported need not take nine days to think over, and consider as to whether or no it was respecable. Many gentlemen of Brooklyn had asked him what this War Democracy intended to do? He would tell them one thing they did not intend to do; they did not intend to go so far up Salt River as never to be heard from again, and they did intend to support the Government, and to support and act with the brave soldiers in the field. He then nominated as President of the evening Hon. SAMUEL E. JOHNSON, who was unanimously elected, a list of Vice Presidents and Secretaries was then read and accepted, when, after a short speech, the Chairman introduced

abstract: Candidate for Congress; our Candidate for Governor
snippet: Candidate for Congress; our Candidate for Governor
lead_paragraph: -- Unstinted as the Copperheads have been in their abuse of the Union candidates generally, they have hardly ventured to utter a syllable against REUBEN E. FENTON. Whether this has been because they thought it hardly expedient for their interests south of the Potomac to traduce one whose self-sacrificing services to the soldiers had given him so strong a hold upon their respect and gratitude, or because of his peculiarly unassailable character, they best know. But, either way, it is a matter of pride to the Union party that the opponent of HORATIO SEYMOUR is a man they dare not asperse. We shall have a Governor for the next two years worthy of the Empire State, not only in loyalty, but in every quality that makes true manhood.

abstract: our Noble Dead
snippet: our Noble Dead
lead_paragraph: When such deaths as the recent one of the lamented Col. LOWELL, of Boston, are brought before the public, we can appreciate anew how vast have been the sacrifices of the free States in this war. It is not the refuse of our population -- nor even that portion which is indifferently valuable, which has been offered during the last three years in devotion to our cause. Those who have gone were often those whom we least could spare. How many of the best young men of the country, can we all recall -- many of them the descendants of old and honored families, many on whom years of patient industry and culture had been spent to fit them for high positions of usefulness and honor; some possessing ample fortune, some gifted with those high qualities of character which pointed them out as "leaders of men," beloved and respected through wide circles of friends; others scholars and showing already marks of high intellect, and even of genius; others again fitted for great success in practical branches, and with those talents which, in this country certainly, carry fortune with them -- all of them abandoning ease and literary culture, and civic honors, and the refinements of wealth, for the hard life of camps, and at last sacrificing life willingly for the great cause of liberty and country. If the wealth of a country lies in its best men, then would our Union soon seem impoverished. Those who survive, and who follow the pursuits of peace, seem mean and ignoble compared with these heroic young men. We feel that in these losses have gone more than wealth or lands, or all other losses.

abstract: Election; To-morrow's Election
snippet: Election; To-morrow's Election
lead_paragraph: There is one thing which we must beg of the public to remember, to-morrow, and that is, that this Presidential Election differs from all those that have preceded it, and in all likelihood, from all those that may follow it, in the irretrievableness of its consequences. A mistake committed in the choice of a candidate at any election that has hitherto occurred, could always be rectified four years subsequently, with but little damage to the Commonwealth. A mistake committed tomorrow will be irremediable. Its results will be felt probably centuries hence, and either rejoiced over or deplored for generations to come.

abstract: GEORGE N. SANDERS writes to a Montreal journal, for the purpose of declaring that under no consideration would his Confederate friends cross the border to-morrow to record their votes. Even if the rebel refugees were guaranteed the protection of the United States Government, Mr. SANDERS says they would refuse to take any part in the Presidential election. This, we suppose, is to be taken as highminded on the part of SANDERS' friends. They are doubtless doing a more profitable business in the general thieving line along the borders. And besides, Gen. DIX is likely to have something to say about casting rebel votes to-morrow, which SANDERS' men could hardly be expected to relish. If these distinguished refugees, then, are not excessively honest, they are wonderfully prudent. They will be badly wanted by their Cessation friends here on Tuesday; but, on the whole, it is perhaps better for them not to come. Gov. SEYMOUR's army agents have got into some little difficulty by extra devotion to the cause. And it is well to be warned. Let SANDERS stay where he is, even if he has to go into the petty larceny business.

abstract: in Command of New-York
snippet: in Command of New-York
lead_paragraph: Maj.-Gen. BUTLER arrived in this city from before Richmond last week, and makes the announcement this morning, in the form of "General Orders, No. 1," that "in obedience to the orders of the President, and by the assignment of Maj.-Gen. DIX, commanding Department of the East," he "assumes command of the troops arriving and about to arrive, detailed for duty in the State of New-York, to meet existing emergencies." Gen. BUTLER sets forth that the precautionary measure of sending troops to this State has been adopted by the Government because it has information that raids on our frontier, like that at St. Alban's, are in contemplation by Confederate emissaries; but that he has force sufficient to preserve the public peace, and to prevent and punish incursions upon our borders. In reply to the false assertion that the presence of troops might have an adverse effect upon the free exercise of the right of suffrage, Gen. BUTLER says that nothing could be further from the truth, and he enjoins upon the soldiers that there shall be no interference unless the civil authorities are overcome. He also utters a warning against fraudulent voting, and gives a caution to rebels from the South who may attempt to defile our ballot-boxes.

abstract: We have three days' later news from Europe, by the America, which sailed from Southampton, on the 26th of October. The vessel Senator, which had arrived at Queenstown, reports having been boarded by the privateer Florida, on Sept. 13, in lat. 6° North, lon. 25° West. The intended privateer San Francisco, which was built at Nantes for the rebels, but which the French Government had not allowed to be given up, made a trial trip to Belle Isle and back. Her engines worked well. Her speed was 13 3/4 knots per hour. GARIBALDI's yacht is lying off Cowes, waiting for a favorable wind to return to Caprera. The trial of FRANZ MULLER was to take place on the 27th or 28th of October. We have some further particulars relative to the Franco-Italian Convention. The Italian papers which contained GARIBALDI's pronouncimento against the convention had been seized by the Turin Government. The bill for the transfer of the capital to Florence is before the Chamber of Deputies. Further commercial failures are reported in England. The rebel loan is quoted steady at 64 1/2.

abstract: A special dispatch from near Plymouth, via Rocky Mount, North, Carolina, dated on the 31st ult., says: "After three days' hard fighting the enemy passed up Middle River and came down the Roanoke this morning. Gen. BAKER, commander of the garrison, fought until the enemy's gunboats had passed our forts and dismounted all our guns in the harbor. An evacuation was then ordered under a severe shelling, which was effected without much loss. Col. WHITFORD acted with conspicuous bravery." As Middle River does not appear on the ordinary maps, and there may appear to be something of a paradox in the statement that gunboats went up one river and came down another, it is proper to state that there are three channels in the Roanoke at this point, separated by strips of land extending above Plymouth, the main channel passing by that place. Vessels ascending the middle channel would emerge above Plymouth, and thus be enabled to descend in the rear of the place. Meantime, where was the Albemarle?

lead_paragraph: Two performances have been given during the past week at the Theatre Frangals. On Tuesday "La Joie de la Malson" (the "Little Treasure") was played, and introduced M. JUIGNOT to his patrons, by whom he was most heartily received. Mlle. KARSCH was the "little treasure," and played with good taste and spirit. Mlle. LARMET, so far, has made the best success of the season. The lady's performances in this piece, and in "Nos Alliees," on Saturday, were admirable. The attendance has been excellent, and everything promises a season of unusual brilliancy and merit. In consequence of the election to-morrow there will be no performance in the evening. It will take place on Thursday evening, when the comedy of "Le Genare de Monsieur Poirier" will be produced. This piece, it will be remembered, was cleverly turned into English by Mr. DELILLE, under the title of "My Noble Son-in-law."

abstract: Arrest of
snippet: Arrest of
lead_paragraph: The Copperhead newspapers of the East have made an ado about the military arrest of J.J. BINGHAM, editor of the State Sentinel, in Indianapolis -- denouncing it as another tyrannical invasion of the press, though in fact his paper was not touched. This person being put on trial, has made a clean breast of it. He says that he joined the "American Knights" a year ago -- that last August he was called upon by DODD, the commander of the organization in Indiana, and some other prominent members of the order, and, under pledge of secrecy, was told that a revolution had been determined upon in resistance to the draft -- that arrangements had been made to release the rebel prisoners at Johnson's Island, Camp Douglass, Camp Chase and Camp Morton -- that GOV. MORTON was to be killed -- and that there was to be a rising at the same time in Louisville to seize the Government stores, and other property. BINGHAM thought the information so important, that as chairman of the Democratic Central Committee, he immediately called a meeting of the committee, "to consult on its effect on the party." The committee decided that the plan must not go on, and for that reason it was postponed. Being asked in court why he had not informed the authorities that this plot was on foot, BINGHAM replied, "I did not wish to injure our party at the coming election. There was danger of that if the revolution were made public." BINGHAM closed his sworn statements by saying, "no inducements or threats have drawn out this testimony. It is voluntary."

abstract: -By unerring indications, acknowledged by all sharp heads of either side, behind the scenes, there has been rapid and large defections all through the cities of New-York and Brooklyn from the lead of the "Whipped-Spaniel" (see JEFF. DAVIS' speech) Democracy, within the last four weeks, and mostly within the last four or five days. Thousands of patriotic men have become disgusted and left them. There are 127,000 registered voters in New-York City, and we presume two-fifths as many more in Brooklyn. To arouse certain latent portions of "the party," among these, the usual venerable stimulus has been resorted to, immense sums spent, torch-lights, processions, banners covered with the stereotyped phrases about "Bastiles," Old ABE's Jokes," "Abolition Pictures of Africans," &c. But the stimulus of these old agencies seems to be gone. The demonstration of Saturday night through our streets was a failure. It is certain that the large proportion of our citizens, even those not accustomed to deep thought, are now treating this election as an occasion for solemnity, and not a time for mere sky-rockets.

abstract: Erie; Train off Track--4 Killed, 30 Wounded
snippet: Erie; Train off Track--4 Killed, 30 Wounded
lead_paragraph: The Buffalo and Dunkirk passenger express, on the New-York and Erie Railroad, due in this city at 12:45 P.M. yesterday, met with a shocking accident at the Callicoon Station, 136 miles west of here, at half-past nine o'clock in the morning. The train was three hours behind time, but, it is said, was proceeding at the usual rate of speed, not stopping at Callicoon, and was thrown off the track in consequence of the switch having been left open. It seems that there has been no switchman at that place, and as near as we could be informed, the responsibility of the switch has been left with the conductors, who have had occasion to use it. The engine, tender, baggage-car, and three passenger cars were precipitated down an embankment of thirty feet and smashed to pieces, the engine being turned end-for-end, the boiler torn from the frame, and the whole mass heaped in the mud of the creek which the railroad crosses at that place. There were six passenger-cars. Of the three last two ran partly off the embankment; the last one remained on the track. THOS. G. CLARK, Traveling Superintendent in the Post-office Department, headquarters in this city, had just stepped upon the engine to ride a short distance, and was killed. He has been long and well known in connection with the Post-office. His body was brought to this city at 11 o'clock last night, the first train coming through at that hour. ARTHUR BANK, of Port Jervis, a machinist in employ of the New-York and Erie Railroad Company, was killed, and his remains were taken to Port Jervis. Two others were killed -- HORACE BERRVGER, the fireman, and WM.H. CREDDLE, a private of the One Hundred and Forty-third Regiment New-York Volunteers. WM. HULL, of Susquehanna, was so severely cut and bruised, it is thought, he cannot recover. Many others were seriously injured -- the number of wounded being between thirty and forty, of whom several were ladies. The conductor was Mr. FRED. BUTLER, who exerted himself to the utmost to make comfortable the sufferers, as did also the people of Callicoon.

abstract: Sharing Fate of his Comrades
snippet: Sharing Fate of his Comrades
lead_paragraph: -- Mr. BELMONT, in that speech which he delivered at the Cooper Institute on Wednesday evening, informed his auditors that Gen. MCCLELLAN "offered to share the fate of his comrades as a common soldier when deprived of his command by the intrigues of HALLECK and STANTON." This reminds us somewhat of the magnanimous "offer" made a year ago by the redoubtable TOOMBS, of Georgia. That eminent person declared, in a speech delivered, we believe, in Augusta, that "when all was lost," meaning all that appertains to the Confederacy, he would himself seek a patriot's grave by baring his breast to the bayonets of the foe. There was, however, nothing in the world to prevent the brave man from offering himself up as a sacrifice for his country before "all was lost," and it was then only that his untimely end would be of the slightest use to the public. His perishing after all was over, would profit nobody, and his postponement of this supreme proof of his devotion until everybody else had stopped fighting, naturally led a good many people to suspect that in reality he never meant to make it.

abstract: -The Copperhead leaders here have had for their programme the rolling up of such immense majorities in the Cities of New-York and Brooklyn, that the rest of the State could not confront them. They have for some time given up all hope of electing their Presidential candidate, but have fancied there could be a chance, in the way alluded to, for SEYMOUR's success, after and upon which they unquestionably intended to commence their disunion and Southern affiliation plots, in conjunction with their rebel military and political friends. This is the programme of the leaders here. But the hope involved in it is fast failing them. SEYMOUR has no more chance than Gen. MCCLELLNAN. The masses in the cities are not ambitious of changing themselves into a pack of what JEFF. DAVIS called "whipped spaniels."

abstract: -- Let no exertions be spared to secure the election of WILLIAM E. DODGE, the only Union candidate for Congress in the Eighth District. Mr. DODGE would honor the place, not the place him. Greatly against his own private interests, he yielded to solicitations that he should so serve the public. He belongs to that class of our merchants who recognize that there are public duties from which no good citizen has a right to excuse himself. It is too seldom that the voters of this city have the opportunity to say whether they will accept such services or not. Mr. DODGE's great financial knowledge and his thorough acquaintance with all the commercial interests of our metropolis would prove of immense benefit in Congress, in adjusting the great revenue measures and aiding to settle wisely all the difficult financial questions connected with the support of the Government. The present Congress, though abounding with general talent, sadly feels the need of men of practical financiering experience, as has been plainly shown in its crude and inconsistent legislation on financial subjects. The voters of the Eighth District are fortunate in having it in their power to do much to supply this deficiency; and we trust, not only for their own credit, but for the substantial interests of the city and the country, that they will not fail to make the most of their opportunity. It is needless to say one word respecting the stainless character, the tireless energy, the ardent public spirit, and the staunch loyalty of WILLIAM E. DODGE. They are known to every man who knows anything of the current history of our city. We are glad to know that there is an excellent prospect that the Eighth District will be redeemed.

abstract: The State of New-York is now the special mark of the Copperheads. They have about given up all expectation of electing McCLELLAN, and are staking all their hopes upon SEYMOUR. They are thoroughly awake to the...
lead_paragraph: The State of New-York is now the special mark of the Copperheads. They have about given up all expectation of electing McCLELLAN, and are staking all their hopes upon SEYMOUR. They are thoroughly awake to the importance of having some official base for their factious warfare upon President LINCOLN; and they understand perfectly well that there is none so advantageous for this as the Executive office of the Empire State. HORATIO SEYMOUR, in his present position, has served them better as a power for mischief than all their other agencies combined. We think that it is not too much to say that he has done more by his official influence, direct and indirect, to embarrass the Government, and to stay up the hopes of the rebellion, than all the rest of the Copperhead leaders put together. So long as they can keep him at the head of affairs in this great State, they will not despair, whatever their overthrow elsewhere. To accomplish this they have gone into the most enormous and infamous frauds ever known in our political history. They have scrupled at nothing -- have without reserve committed deeds of as black a dye as any crimes in the calendar.

abstract: Son of Liberty; Confession of
snippet: Son of Liberty; Confession of
lead_paragraph: -Every day of the trial of the conspirators of the Order of Sons of Liberty, in Indianapolis, brings out new and startling revelations. HORACE HEFFRON, Deputy Grand Commander, has turned State's evidence, and testifies that the order was a military organization -- that it had appointed a Committee of Thirteen to prepare an insurrection, to kill Gov. MORTON, overturn the State Government, and form the Northwest into a separate confederacy. He also testified that he had been told by an Adjutant-General of the Order that five hundred thousand dollars had been sent by rebel agents in Canada into the Northwest, to purchase arms for the Order.

abstract: alleged Support of McClellan from pique; Election; Danger to Property from McClellan's Election
snippet: alleged Support of McClellan from pique; Election; Danger to Property from McClellan's Election
lead_paragraph: Everyone who has any property-interest at stake in the country, should consider seriously at this time the effect of his vote in the Presidential election on the property of the nation. We Americans have become so accustomed to "terrible crises" just before elections, and to awful perils threatened in view of any given action at the polls, which entirely subsided and disappeared when either candidate was chosen, that at last, when the danger has really come, we hardly recognize it. There are probably tens of thousands of Democrats at this moment, with large stakes in the country, who have a vague idea that somehow things will turn out right, even if their candidate is elected, and that they had better stick to "the old party."

abstract: Springfield Republican on New-York Politics
snippet: Springfield Republican on New-York Politics
lead_paragraph: The Republicans of New-York have a singularly bad habit of throwing away their opportunities. If they have a chance to do something handsome and achieve a decided success, the chances are that they will divide that they may be conquered the more easily. This is what they are absurdly doing at this election in the Sixth and Eighth Congressional Districts in New-York City. United they have a fair prospect of carrying both districts. So, to make defeat certain, there are two Republican candidates running in each district, and the contest is very sharp, while the Democrats stand by, ready to take the prizes offered to them. It would be a great matter to break the unity of the New-York City delegation in Congress for the Opposition, and it is inexcusable in the Republicans that they refuse to do it. The Sixth District would do itself great credit by electing Mr. RAYMOND, of the TIMES. His Republican competitor, Mr. RUSH C. HAWKINS, may be a very excellent man, but Mr. RAYMOND has a national reputation, and eminent qualifications for service in Congress. It would be a wise and patriotic thing in Mr. HAWKINS to withdraw and give his support to Mr. RAYMOND, since it is certain that by running against him he gives the place to the Democratic candidate. So in the Eighth District Mr. WILLIAM E. DODGE will undoubtedly obtain the larger part of the Republican votes, but Mr. MANNI???ERS, the Second Republican candidate, will probably secure enough votes to give the election to the Democratic candidate. Is there no means by which these senseless divisions can be healed, and two valuable Republican members of Congress be elected from New-York City? The object is certainly worth an effort.

abstract: Election; "The Momentous Day"
snippet: Election; "The Momentous Day"
lead_paragraph: The day has come -- the day of fate. Before this morning's sun sets, the destinies of this republic, so far as depends on human agency, are to be settled for weal or for woe. An inevitable choice is this day to be made by the American people, between a policy carrying salvation or a policy carrying ruin to the nation. On the one hand is war, tremendous and terrible, yet ushering in at the end every national security and glory. On the other is the mocking shadow of a peace, tempting us to quit these sacrifices, and sink again into indulgence, and yet sure to rob us of our birthright, and to entail upon our children a dissevered Union and ceaseless strife. As the popular decision of this day is rendered in favor of the principles declared at Baltimore, or the principles declared at Chicago, so must either this or that consequence follow. The two men for whom the votes are to be cast are nothing in the presence of this mighty issue. Whatever their respective merits or faults, and however legitimately these, in ordinary times, might determine which of the two should be accepted and which rejected, such personal considerations are but as the dust in the balance when policies of such dread import are to be weighed. The Union party has no reason to shrink from any comparison of the candidates. But such comparing is, after all, very much like debating the qualifications of ship commanders, one of whom would have to do with the ship on the broad high seas, under the fierce gale, the other with the ship already launched into the resistless sweep of a Niagara, or sliding down into the relentless vortex of the Maelstrom. GEORGE B. MCCLELLAN might be all that his most extravagant admirers claim him to be, and a thousand times beyond, and yet he would be as helpless as an infant to stay the destruction of the Union in the line of the policy marked out for him by his party at Chicago. It is not within the power of mortal man to abandon the war at this stage, and make terms with the rebellion that will not involve the wreck of all that constitutes us a nation. Every man that casts his vote to-day should keep his eyes on this mighty fact. His choice is to be made, not between persons but between policies. The sovereign question is whether this rebellion, which is assailing the life of the Union, is to be dealt with on the principle of maintaining the national authority, or on the principle of surrendering it -- in other words, whether we are to have stability through the ascendancy of law, or subversion through the triumph of lawlessness. We are making this decision not for ourselves simply. We are settling the lot of the generations that shall come after us. If the people err,

lead_paragraph: A large meeting of the Democrats of the Sixth Congressional District was held last evening at Jackson-square, to ratify the nomination of Hon. ELI P. NORTON for Congress. Notwithstanding the inclemency of the weather, a very large number of citizens assembled. A fine band of music was in attendance, ???reworks and transparencies displayed in great abundance, and it was in every particular one of the most complete and enthusiastic meetings held by the Democrats in this district. At 8 o'clock the meeting was called to order, and, on motion, Hon. WILLIAM CHAUNCEY was called to preside. Spirited addresses were made by Hon. ELI P. NORTON, Hon. JAMES BROOKS. W.B. RANKIN and others. The Chairman then read a letter from Hon. JOHN MCKEON, strongly indorsing the nomination of Mr. NORTON: after which the meeting adjourned, with strong and hearty cheers for the nominee.

abstract: New-York--Nulet, J, Policeman, Shot by a Prisoner
snippet: New-York--Nulet, J, Policeman, Shot by a Prisoner
lead_paragraph: About 3 o'clock yesterday morning Policeman JOSEPH NULET, of the Twenty-ninth Precinct, while in the act of taking a prisoner whom he had arrested for disorderly conduct to the Station-house, was shot in the head with a pistol, and almost instantly killed. The murderer immediately made his escape, and up to a late hour last night he had not been arrested. His name even is unknown. The deed was perpetrated in West Twenty-ninth-street, between Broadway and Fifth-avenue.

abstract: The Washington correspondent of the Buffalo Express, writing recently of our State Agent at the National Capital, says he cares little for MCCLELLAN or the Opposition party, so that he can accomplish something for SEYMOUR. Were he man of less pretensions and more brain he would have retired from the field a long time ago. The rebuffs he receives from our boys in the hospitals are very amusing, and oftentimes send him away grumbling at his want of success. The boys never saw him in the hospitals until within the past month. During all the Summer when the sons of New-York were filling every hospital, when the sick and wounded, the crippled and dying were calling for help, and wondering why the agent of their own State did not show his face and exhibit his sympathy by administering to their wants, he was nowhere to be found. No sympathy, no care, no relief came to their bedside; but now that their votes are needed to elect his master, he is particularly officious and frequent in his visits. He finds, however, that they are as wanting in sympathy as he has shown himself to be during their suffering. They remember the kind words spoken and the relief administered by the Hon. REUBEN E. FENTON, during their suffering; they remember that night and day, week day and Sunday, he was busy providing for their welfare, caring for their wants, cheering them by his presence; and when unable to attend personally, they saw his agents, who were paid from his own pocket, and who administered comfort by their kinds words, and supplied their wants from the liberal storehouse of their friend. Remembering these things, the boys ???are not particularly choice in their epithets to the agent of GOV. SEYMOUR.

lead_paragraph: FELLOW-CITIZENS: Coming now to the last days of the rebellion and to the difficult duty of reconstruction, no one can fail to see the importance of looking beyond mere personal and party considerations, and sending to Congress men who will bring to that responsible post knowledge to comprehend the situation of the country, wisdom to device practical as well as practicable measures of reconstruction, and the ability to explain their nature and to persuade others to adopt them. abstract: The undersigned, a Committee appointed at a meeting held at the Union League Club House, appeal to the people of the North to join them in an effort to furnish to our gallant soldiers and sailors, a good Thanksgiving dinner. We desire that on the twenty-fourth day of November there shall be no soldiers in the Army of the Potomac, the James or the Shenandoah, and no sailor in the North Atlantic Squadron who does not receive tangible evidence that those for whom he is periling his life, remember him. It is hoped that the armies at the West will be in like manner cared for by those nearer to them than we. It is deemed impracticable to send to our more Southern post.

The ripe and mellow wisdom of this eminent statesman deserves, and will command, general public attention.

abstract: The recent order from the War Department, granting furioughs to all soldiers in hospitals to return to their homes, has taxed the Quartermaster's Department of this city to the utmost. Capt H. BROWNSON, Assistant Quartermaster, with his corps of twenty assistants, has been assiduously at work night and day since Tuesday last. Thirty-one cars filled with soldiers were sent off to-day eastward by the New-Haven Railroad alone. The Harlem Road also sent out an extra train. Dr. HOFF. Medical Director of transportation, has cared for more than 1,000 men per night during the past week, distributing transportation to the men in the morning. The labors of these faithful officers of the Government have been severe and arduous.

abstract: Butler's, Gen; Presence, Orders, and Staff
snippet: Butler's, Gen; Presence, Orders, and Staff
lead_paragraph: Gen. BUTLER's ringing and explicit order on assuming command of the entire military forces in the State of New-York, profoundly excited the city yesterday. The blood of the people was stirred by it, in spite of the damp and drizzling weather, Its terse reasons, its trenchant statements, its sharp rebukes and significant warnings, struck home alike to loyal hearts and disloyal consciences. To the one class it brought full assurance of order and peace at the polls, and to the other a perfect understanding that devilish machinations of every kind would be foiled in their first outcroppings. Gen. BUTLER's sudden transfer from the field before Richmond, where only a week since he was sulking at open foes, to the command of the troops in the Empire State, where there is come reason to believe that secret enemies of the nation have been active in their vile plotting, was scarcely expected. It was hinted at a few days since, but was hardly known outside a narrow official circle, and its public announcement had all the effect of a great moral sensation. There had been misgivings felt by many that to-day would witness a repetition in this city of the disgraceful scenes of the July riots of 1863; there had been a widespread and indefinable dread that rebel emissaries would seize the exciting time of a general election to put in execution the villainous threats recently made by the Richmond papers of laying New-York, Buffalo, and other Northern cities in ashes; there had been vague fears entertained by weak-kneed folk that it would be unsafe in certain districts to exercise the right of suffrage. But the doubting, the dreading and the timid, at once felt a seusible diminution of their tears on the announcement that Gen. BUTLER, the man of iron nerve and steady purpose, who knows how to deal with all sorts of mobs, was in their midst, with a proper force to preserve the peace. The wisdom of the Government in selecting the man who had scattered the howling rabble of New-Orleans like chaff, and reduced that city to order most serene, approved itself to the conscience of every patriot, and made Copperheads squirm and writhe in torture.

abstract: Election; Rebel Efforts to and Peace Candidate; On Making Spaniels Civil by Whipping; Helping the McClellan Peace Candidate
snippet: Election; Rebel Efforts to and Peace Candidate; On Making Spaniels Civil by Whipping; Helping the McClellan Peace Candidate
lead_paragraph: The rebels have not been able to help the Peace candidate much by their late military operations. They started three or four campaigns for that purpose, but they have all come to grief -- just at the wrong time for them. PRICE made a grand rush into Missouri a few weeks since, to stump the State for Little MCCLELLAN, and ravage it for JEFF. DAVIS; but, before the election, PLEASONTON has routed him in fearful style, and his two best officers, MARMADUKE and CABELL, are by this time on Johnson's Island. HOOD and BEAUREGARD, in like manner, went forth to invade Tennessee, and JEFF. DAVIS proclaimed publicly at Columbia that the main object of the campaign was to help the prospects of the peace candidate for the Presidency by showing to the North the hopelessness of the war. "I believe," said he, "it is in the power of the men of the Confederacy to plant our banners on the banks of the Ohio, where we may say to the Yankee 'be quiet, or we shall teach you another lesson.' Let fresh victories crown our arms, and the peace party, if there be such at the North, can elect its candidate." In the same speech he said: "Does any man imagine that we can conquer the Yankees by retreating before them, or do you not all know that the only way to make spaniels civil is to whip them?" This speech was delivered on the 4th of October, and in it DAVIS dwells again and again on the imperative necessity of rebel successes "within the next thirty days," showing his desperate anxiety that they should occur before our Presidential election, and in time to affect popular sentiment and action at the North. Well, thirty days and more have passed, and what is the upshot, or what is the prospect, of HOOD's and BEAUREGARD's great politico- military campaign in behalf of the peace candidate? The rebel army has not set foot in Tennessee; the feeble attempt which it made to cross the Tennessee River was easily repulsed; and Gen. SHERMAN evidently regards the whole movement with philosophical contempt. He holds Atlanta firmly; all his communications with Chattanooga are perfect; the latter stronghold is impregnable; so likewise are Murfreesboro and Nashville, and what can HOOD and BEAUREGARD do? The probability is that henceforth Gen. SHERMAN will pay but little attention to them, and will now prosecute the campaign through Georgia in his own way.

abstract: ENTHUSIASTIC UNION MEETING IN HOBOKEN. -- One of the largest and most enthusiastic meetings ever held in Hoboken, upon merely a common call, convened in Harmonia Hall, on Saturday evening. The large hall was densely crowded notwithstanding a torchlight procession which was parading the streets. The first speaker was Hon. EDGAR B. WAKEMAN, candidate for Congress in that district. Mr. GEORGE TERWILLIGER, of this city, followed, and in the course of an eloquent address, said: Let us imagine what would take place should such a misfortune occur as the election of MCCLELLAN. He would no sooner be seated in the Presidential chair than the attempt to exhaust all the resources of statesmanship would be tried. An order would be at once issued to our Generals in the field to suspend hostilities. The heroes of many a well-fought field will be told, "Your services are no longer required. All your services have been of no avail. The war is a failure, and we don't want you any longer." Sadly and sorrowfully they will return to their homes, and Commissioners from the grim traitor will be sent to Washington. Then will commence the trial of exhausting all the resources of statesmanship, and after a long trial, sufficient to blind little MAC, the oily BENJAMIN will turn suddenly to him, and say. "It is no use MCCLELLAN, you know you were elected noon the Chicago Platform, and that meant to give us our independence, and acknowledge our Confederacy, and you must do it, "Oh!" MCCLELLAN will say, "I did not so understand it, and moreover. I have sent my armies home. You are taking me at a disadvantage." "I can't help it," BENJAMIN will say, "We were not foolish enough to send our army home. We have kept them together, and recruited them, and if you don't give us what we ask, we will send you whirling North, the same as your SHERIDAN sent our forces whirling up the Shenandoah Valley." MCCLELLAN seeing the iron will of the ghastly traitor will submit. The Southern Confederacy will become an established fact -- the old Union will be broken -- the old flag will trail in the dust. This picture was so truthful that the audience rose to their feet and gave three cheers to the speaker. lead_paragraph: ENTHUSIASTIC UNION MEETING IN HOBOKEN. -- One of the largest and most enthusiastic meetings ever held in Hoboken, upon merely a common call, convened in Harmonia Hall, on Saturday evening. The large hall was densely crowded notwithstanding a torchlight procession which was parading the streets. The first speaker was Hon. EDGAR B. WAKEMAN, candidate for Congress in that district. Mr. GEORGE TERWILLIGER, of this city, followed, and in the course of an eloquent address, said: Let us imagine what would take place should such a misfortune occur as the election of MCCLELLAN. He would no sooner be seated in the Presidential chair than the attempt to exhaust all the resources of statesmanship would be tried. An order would be at once issued to our Generals in the field to suspend hostilities. The heroes of many a well-fought field will be told, "Your services are no longer required. All your services have been of no avail. The war is a failure, and we don't want you any longer." Sadly and sorrowfully they will return to their homes, and Commissioners from the grim traitor will be sent to Washington. Then will commence the trial of exhausting all the resources of statesmanship, and after a long trial, sufficient to blind little MAC, the oily BENJAMIN will turn suddenly to him, and say. "It is no use MCCLELLAN, you know you were elected noon the Chicago Platform, and that meant to give us our independence, and acknowledge our Confederacy, and you must do it, "Oh!" MCCLELLAN will say, "I did not so understand it, and moreover. I have sent my armies home. You are taking me at a disadvantage." "I can't help it," BENJAMIN will say, "We were not foolish enough to send our army home. We have kept them together, and recruited them, and if you don't give us what we ask, we will send you whirling North, the same as your SHERIDAN sent our forces whirling up the Shenandoah Valley." MCCLELLAN seeing the iron will of the ghastly traitor will submit. The Southern Confederacy will become an established fact -- the old Union will be broken -- the old flag will trail in the dust. lead_paragraph: The contest in the Sixth District is a regular quadrilateral. There are two Democratic and two Union candidates in the field. ELIJAH WARD is regularly nominated by several of the machine conventions, but there were many Democrats, who thought three terms were quite as many as Mr. WARD had earned by his public services; and they accordingly put in nomination ELI P. NORTON, Esq., who withdrew two years ago in WARD's favor, but declines to do so again. A very large and enthusiastic meeting of Democrats was held last evening on Jackson Square to ratify his nomination. According to present appearances he is quite as likely to be elected as Mr. WARD.

abstract: Hon George Brown's Speech
snippet: Hon George Brown's Speech
lead_paragraph: -- In a speech delivered at Toronto, on Thursday last, Hon. GEORGE BROWN, one of the leading members of the Canadian Government, gave a semi-official outline of the scheme of federal union adopted by the Quebec Conference. It differs in no essential particular from the programme which our special correspondent was in a position to furnish several weeks ago. Mr. BROWN, indeed, says that the outline (which was first published in the TIMES) was given with surprising accuracy. We notice from the tone of the Toronto addresses that the delegates are not disposed to submit their project to the test of a popular vote. They seem to think that there is a sufficient indication of the popularity of the measure in the fact that the delegates belong to different political parties. It is doubtful whether this argument can hold water. The people may be prepared to give their assent to the principle of union, and may yet be thoroughly opposed to the details of the measure. As, for instance, to that part of it which deprives them of the right of electing members of the Legislative Council, and vests that power in the Crown. It is not a satisfactory sign, in any case, this of hurrying through a great constitutional measure without consulting the people.

abstract: Well, Gen. BUTLER has been in active command of the city and State of New-York for forty-eight hours. So far as we have heard, he has not yet erected a single gallows or hung anybody; he has shot nobody; he has knouted nobody; he has hamstrung nobody; he has crucified nobody; he has impaled nobody on a poker, or bastinadoed nobody. He has sent nobody to Fort Lafayette, and put nobody in chains or irons. He has suppressed no newspapers, and insulted no women. Bat he took the most active and admirable measures to secure the peace of the city and State during the election yesterday; and the peace has been undisturbed.

abstract: Rebel Change of Base, on; Intelligencer, Immense Article
snippet: Rebel Change of Base, on; Intelligencer, Immense Article
lead_paragraph: If the rebels carry into effect their proposed policy of arming their slaves to fight for the Confederacy, it will be, in the first place, a complete abandonment of the programme laid down by them when they began their rebellion. They revolted on the express ground that the form of social organization existing at the South, was the only one in which liberty and progress could be both secured; that "free society" was a failure, and that the true solution of the great difficulty of modern times, the reconciliation of the interests of labor with those of capital, was the one which the South had discovered and adopted, -- the possession of the laborer as property by the capitalist.

abstract: Scudder's, H E, Life of D C Scudder
snippet: Scudder's, H E, Life of D C Scudder
lead_paragraph: The romance of missionary adventure has been unquestionably diminished by facility of locomotion and increased means of intercourse with regions once considered hopelessly remote. Its records more seldom meet our eye than formerly; but able and devoted men are nevertheless still working, in numbers greater than at any former time, in the cultivation of a field where little apparent??? success appears to cheer the laborer, and an exalted sense of duty must be his guide and support in the absence of sublunary triumphs. The volume before us is the record, by a younger brother, of one who went out as a missionary to Hindostan, and died there eighteen months after his arrival, in his 28th year. So brief a career might seem scarcely to claim a volume, but in the hands of a brother the subject grows under his loving care, and we obtain a competent picture of one, in many respects, worthy of commemoration. DAVID COIT SCUDDER, though cut off at so youthful a period of life, had approved himself no common man. The h???e influences of a Puritan household -- pious, without asceticism -- familiarized him for years with his destined field of labor, and all the energies of a close and earnest student were employed in fitting himself for his intended occupation of it. Probably few missionaries ever reached India better furnished, intellectually, for their work. There was nothing approaching to cant in DAVID SCUDDER. That his religious convictions were all powerful, was proved by the position he filled at their suggestion; but he was the man to give the whole of his intellect full play, feeling that the more avenues he kept open for knowledge, the better. A good instance of the breadth of his studies is given in the chapter entitled "Search among Cromlechs." This will be read with attention in England, and gives some valuable antiquarian information overlooked by all the English residents in India. Mr. SCUDDER wrote well and unaffectedly. He is judiciously allowed to tell his own story in the letters and journals that compose the greater part of the volume. He was not a sanguine worker, but saw clearly the immense obstacles to missionary success on the system now adopted. The book unconsciously throws light on this question, as on many others connected with the Christianization of India.

abstract: The deaths in New-York during the past week were 417 -- 113 men, 104 women, 110 boys and 90 girls -- a decrease of 8 from the mortality of the previous week, and a decrease of 11 as compared with the mortality of the corresponding week of 1863. Of the deceased, 171 were children under five years of age. The mortality by the principal diseases was as follows: Consumption, 72; inflammation of the lungs, 32; infantile marasmus, 19; infantile convulsions, 24; typhoid fever, 19; disease of brain, 15; diphtherite, 15; small-pox, 16; deaths from external causes, 29; among which are reported 2 premature births, 3 drowned, 9 killed by accidents. There were 57 deaths in the institutions, and 30 interments in Potter's field.

abstract: Familiar Letters from Europe
snippet: Familiar Letters from Europe
lead_paragraph: There is little in these unpremeditated and genuine effusions of a genial and cultivated mind to call for critical remark. They are, what they profess to be, familiar letters -- brief notes, addressed from time to time to members of the writer's circle of friends and relatives, descriptive of the objects that most prominently excited his curiosity in a tour through England, France, Germany and Greece. President FELTON'S visit to Europe naturally brought him in contact with the first men of the time, and rather tantalizing glimpses are given of days of intercourse with literary celebrities and others, when full accounts would have been more gratifying to most of us who are hero-worshippers of the Boswellian type. The studies of Prof. FELTON'S Greek Professorship fitted him for the intense enjoyment of the classi- ???alportion of his journey, and perhaps the most noticeable feature in this book is the testimony it bears to the old Orthodox belief in the Homeric question. While reading the Iliad face to face with the scenes of the immortal tale, he says deliberately, and with Anglo-Saxon-common sense: "I cannot doubt that HOMER saw this spot. I do not see how any one can traverse these seas, and not believe in Troy, and the personal existence of HOMER. It would do the learned critics of Germany no harm to come here, and look about them a little, before they decide that Troy is a fable, and HOMER a myth." To the many hundreds throughout the country who came in contact with Professor FELTON during their student days, this volume Will be welcome, as recalling the memory of one too early lost from the literary and social circles, where his presence imparted to all a share of the joyous elasticity and gaiety of his own happy temperament.

abstract: The election passed off yesterday throughout the country with entire quiet, so far as we can learn. The weather was unpropitious, but did not suppress the great interest felt in the contest though it did interfere with the working of the wires at night, and we have failed to receive as full retnrns from all the States as was expected.
lead_paragraph: The election passed off yesterday throughout the country with entire quiet, so far as we can learn. The weather was unpropitious, but did not suppress the great interest felt in the contest though it did interfere with the working of the wires at night, and we have failed to receive as full retnrns from all the States as was expected. Enough has been received, however, to assure the loyal world of the gratifying fact, that the Union party have carried every State but two -- New-Jersey and Kentucky, and even in the former State the Democratic majority is greatly reduced. New-York State was most hotly cone???ted, but shows a handsome majority for LINCOLN and FENTON, and a gain of, at least, five Union Congressmen Pennsylvania, Indiana and Ohio show large Union gains over the October election -- Pennsylvania being carried by 14,000 on the home vote. Let all true Union men hail the result with loud acclaim and true joy! The nation is safe.

abstract: Religious Faction Fights in
snippet: Religious Faction Fights in
lead_paragraph: They have periodical faction fights in several of the Canadian towns. They had a succession of them of a serious kind, when GAVAZZI visited the provinces a dozen years ago. They had a relapse again, when the Prince of WALKS visited them. And it appears from re ports received last night that Toronto is anxious to emulate the example of Belfast and get up a general religious row. It seems to have begun in a Fifth of November Orange celebration, where some over-zealous advocates of the principles of 1688 proposed -- probably in jest -- to burn OCONNELL, GUY FAWKES, and the Duke of NEWCASTLE in effigy. A party of Catholics having got scent of the matter, organized themselves into armed bands ???raded the streets during the night and seem to have created a sensation gene rally throughout the town. The Orangemen wisely refrained from their intended demonstration, and nobody appears to have been hurt.

lead_paragraph: Tangible evidences were yesterday to be seen In this city, of the important victories recently gained over PRICE'S invading forces, some particulars of which have been given from day to day, during a week past, in the columns of the Republican. These evidences were the presence of several rebel officers of high, rank, consisting of Maj.-Gen. J.V. MARMADUKE, of Missouri ; Brig.-Gen. WM.L. CABELL, of Virginia ; Col. LEE CRANDALL, of the Forty-seventh Arkansas Infantry; Col. W.F. SLEMMONS. of Arkansas; and WM. L. JEFFREYS, of Missouri. JOHN WADDELL, a nephew of Gen. D.M. FROST, formerly of St. Louis, and Surgeon C.H. SMITH, are also of the party. The rank of the former we have not learned, and the latter, we understand, is not to be held as a prisoner, but is to be exchanged, or permitted to return South soon from this city.

abstract: Doran's, Dr. Annals of English Stage
snippet: Doran's, Dr. Annals of English Stage
lead_paragraph: Readers are indebted to Dr. DORAN in these pleasant volumes, for the first history of the English acted Drama, fitted for ordinary perusal by its moderate length and the amusing nature of its contents. It is sure to become a popular book, as long as the great names of the golden age of the Theatre retain their attraction. In the composition of a work of this kind the chief difficulty lies in selection, for, scattered through a great variety of sources, the materials for a history of the English Stage are far more abundant than any that the learned professions or more dignified pursuits can show. Judged by this test the pulpit and the bar occupy a less prominent position than that of the "poor player," who, when "seen no more" upon the stage, yet "frets and struts" in the pages of the biographer, or his own reminisences. Some of the most lively and sparkling books in our language are of this description, and a literary workman of Dr. DORAN'S ability could not fail to make a digest of them that retains much of the charm of the originals. The actors -- those "diverting vagabonds" -- (as Dr. JOHNSON somewhere called them,) stand indeed a better chance to be remembered than most of their graver cotemporaries. There are many among them whose talents might adorn, and their virtues reflect credit on any sphere of action. GARRICK. KEMBLE, SIDDONS, CHARLES KEAN, BETTERTON, and others, are names that would ennoble any profession, and if many of equal ability with those mentioned failed to rival their virtues, the very delinquencies that their names recall, but add to the never failing interest with which we read of PEG WOFFINGTON, KITTY CLIVE, SAMUEL FOOTE, EDMUND KEAN, COLLEY CIBBER, and a whole host of names classic on the boards of Old Drury. Under ???riple heading of "Actors, Authors and Audiences," Dr. DORAN leaves no corner of theatrical history unvisited that could add to the completeness of his picture of the drama in England. This is traced from its origin, when the players were merely an appendage to regal state, acting by virtue of a royal patent, under the regulation and supervision of an officer of the King's household, the Lord Chamberlain, to the year 1843, when "their Majesties servants" became a formality only, and free trade in the drama was established. Dr. DORAN'S style is objectionable as being too obtrusively vivacious; he is nothing if not piquant, and can scarcely repeat the witticism of another without barbina the arrow and sharpening the point. This manner of writing is, however, less out of place in dramatic annuls than in the discussion of graver subjects; and his book bids fair to be the source from whence future ideas of the players and playwrights of the past will continue to be drawn. The work is got up in very correct typographical taste, and does credit to Mr. WIDDLETON'S enterprise.

abstract: Browne's, J Ress, Crusoe's Island
snippet: Browne's, J Ress, Crusoe's Island
lead_paragraph: A volume of varied attractions, which owes as much to the pencil as it does to the pen of its accomplished author and illustrator. Whatever part of the world he may unexpectedly find himself in, Mr. BROWNE'S vivacity never deserts him, and he always possesses the graphic talent to lay before his readers the very scenes and actors that his lengthened rambles around the world have made him familiar with. A leaf of his South American experiences is given in the first paper: a descriptive sketch of Juan Fernandez, the island of ALEXANDER SELKIRK, but certainly not that of Robinson Crusoe. This must be sought, according to the veritable record of the book, on the other side of the South American Continent, near the mouth of the river Orinoco. This slight oversight in the title -- acknowledged by the author himself -- does not affect the merits of the book. Washoe and California are the writer's chosen ground. Mr. BROWNE'S account of these countries is the material on which thousands form their estimate of them. "A Dangerous Journey" has the excitement of terror to add interest to the usual effective style of our author. Though not entirely new to the readers of Harper's Magazine, the contents of the book are well worth preservation in this separate shape.

abstract: Aristocracy of, Veteran Observer on; Aristocracy of the Democratic Party; on President Lincoln's Administration, (Veteran Observer.)
snippet: Aristocracy of, Veteran Observer on; Aristocracy of the Democratic Party; on President Lincoln's Administration, (Veteran Observer.)
lead_paragraph: For forty years, what is called the Democratic Party of this country, has been engaged in a persistent effort to sustain an aristocracy. If the Democratic Party, so named, shall be overthrown utterly (as seems probable) in this election, it will be due to this single cause. From the year 1825, when JOHN QUINCY ADAMS was elected President, the Democratic Party allied itself to the Southern aristocracy, and maintained its supremacy by using the concentrated power (in electoral votes) of that aristocracy against Northern republicanism. No one will contradict this, who either understands political history, or knows the South as well as I do. Mr. RUSSELL of the London Times, has described that aristocracy very well. The educated men of the South were gentlemen, the vulgar overseers were black-guards, but both classes were aristocratic; and both exercised aristocratic power, in contradiction to the only other classes -- "poor white trash," and "niggers."

abstract: Dix, John A; Letters and Speeches
snippet: Dix, John A; Letters and Speeches
lead_paragraph: Looking back on an active and extended career in public life, Gen. Dix has found worthy of perpetuation various memorials of the events with which he was personally connected as a public officer, or that came before him in his legislative capacity while representing the Empires State of New-York in the Senate of the United States. That he has done wisely in placing on record his public acts and the documents connected with them no one will deny; and it is to his credit as a statesman and a man that there is so much in the past that he takes pleasure in recalling. It is at least evidence that his views have borne the test of time, and were adopted on enduring principle rather than in obedience to any ad captandum cry of the moment. Gen. DIX has always loved and cherished literature, for its own sake as well as for the delightful solace it affords to the mind jaded and weary of the tortuous paths of modern politics; and these elegant volumes contain evidence of the healthy scholarship that assimilates its intellectual food and does not make a mere parade of acquirements to astonish the groundlings. The chief portion of the volumes comprises Gen. DIX'S Senatorial Speeches, collected and revised by himself in accordance with a long cherished resolution. They were mostly delivered during the years 1846-49, and show the connection of the author with all the great national movements of the time. Some of the more prominent topics of these speeches are "the Oregon Question," "French Spoliations," "The Warehouse System," "The War with Mexico," "The Appointment of a Minister to the Papal States," &c. The entire list shows how wide is Gen, DIX'S range of information, and it is not too much to say that even at this day something will be found of importance on every question discussed. The next division consists of occasional addresses and a few specimens of the numerous official reports intrusted to his care during his connection with public affairs. Many of the addresses relate to social rather than to political subjects, as "Rural Life and Embellishment," "On the Growth of New-York City," "The Progress of Science," "The Education of Teachers," &c., and show a mind fertile in resources, and able to bring them to bear at once on any topic requiring attention. Only a few papers relating to the present condition of affairs are included in these volumes; among them, however, is displayed, in lithographic fac simile, the memorable order concluding with the instruction to shoot on the spot "any one who attempts to haul down the American Flag." The volumes are brought out in the finest style of typographical execution, and are preceded by a steel portrait of Gen. DIX. By him the work is dedicated to his wife, as an acknowledgment of the intelligent and devoted cooperation she has lent him in all the vicissitudes and labors of his life.

abstract: Cooke, J P; Religion and Chemistry
snippet: Cooke, J P; Religion and Chemistry
lead_paragraph: A new branch of scientific investigation, tending (as all true science must tend,) to the establishment of the great truths of natural theology, on a basis that acquires additional permanence from every fresh scrutiny, is carefully wrought out in this handsome volume. The endowment of the Graham foundation had for its end a principle similar to the famous bequest of the Earl of BRIDGEWATER, in the last generation, and the results of Mr. GRAHAM'S munificence, by which it was provided that the power, wisdom and goodness of God should be illustrated from time to time by evidence derived from the progressive study of nature, promise to equally important for Christian science. Prof. COOKE is recognized abroad and at home as one of the first names among our cultivators of natural philosophy, and he was judiciously chosen to cooperate with AGASSIZ and GUYOT, by whom series of lectures have been delivered, that will shortly appear in a style uniform with the present work. The range of Prof. COOKE'S inquiries being limited to a single topic -- the atmosphere and its component parts, and the testimony they afford of an intelligent first cause in their adaptation to the physical condition of man -- greater detail is attained than is customary in works on natural theology. Viewed as a scientific book alone, on its special subject, we know of none that can come in competition with Religion and Chemistry, while the polished and elegant style of the author, and his earnest conviction, everywhere apparent, that the truths he explains owe their chief value to the glimpses they afford us of the Divine economy of creation, impart to it a peculiar and signal value. How and in what manner, to the enlightened philosopher, "the Heavens declare the glory of God and the firmament showeth His handiwork, as Plainly as they do to the untaught eye of faith, may briefly be described as the object of these lectures They proceed from an examination and analysis of the separate elements composing the atmosphere as oxygen, nitrogen, carbonic acid, &c., in which the scientific information is of the latest character, to the arguments from special adaptation, and the general plan, as furnishing unquestionable proof of intelligent design. With some cautionary remarks on the necessary limits of scientific and religious thought, the author completes a work creditable to himself, and calculated to arrest and reward the attention of all thinking men.

abstract: North American Review, October
snippet: North American Review, October
lead_paragraph: This number opens with an animated and picturesque article on "Baron STEUBEN," founded on his life by FREKERICK KAPP, in which Prof. GREEN brings out in due prominence the characteristics of the worthy veteran, and the vast importance of the services he rendered to the struggling Revolution. "Recent Italian Comedy" is more of local and particular interest." The Conditioned and the Unconditioned" will be caviare to the multitude. "The Indian System," by one who is familiar with the border land, stigmatizes all our Government relations with the aborigines as "conceived in folly and carried out by fraud," and produces a strong array of facts in support of this view. "Life of WILLIAM BLAKE." discusses with sympathy and admiration that great poetic artist. "Ocean Steam Navigation" is a capital article, and surveys the whole subject, explaining, among other things, the causes of the failure of the Collins line and the success of the Cunard Company. It is written with a full knowledge of the matter in all its bearings, and contains valuable hints for future guidance. Goldwin Smith does justice to one of the ablest writers and clearest thinkers of the day, who has earned the gratitude of all Americans. In the words of the reviewer, If the highest duty of a professor of history is to apply the lessons of the past to the understanding of the present time, and In the conflict and confusion of contending forces and opinions, to discover and set forth the truth, he has well performed it." "Nathaniel Hawthorne" opens new and charming views of the ancestry, surroundings and private life of our late novelist. The Near General Election" battles vigorously for the right. The Critical Notices are acute and uncompromising specimens of independent animadversion, not entirely of what CARLYLE would call the rose-water order. We regard this as the best number of the North American yet published by the new editors. Leaving out the Metaphysics, every article is readable and interesting.

abstract: -An unsuccessful attempt was made a few weeks since to defraud one of our banks of a large amount of money. A man came to Newark, hired an office, and deposited $800 in a bank. A day or two after he drew out $750, leaving $50. Soon after he deposited a forged certified check of $14,000 upon the Merchants' Bank of New-York, and the same day sent a man to draw out $8,000. The cashier, however, was somewhat suspicious, and refused to pay the latter sum, and on investigation it was found that the check for $14,000 was forged. Efforts were made to arrest the scamp, but he had decamped, and no trace of him has been found. The bank retains his $50 yet. A similar game was perpetrated with success on banks in New-York City and elsewhere, probably by the same man. -- Newark Advertiser, Oct. 3.

abstract: Officers WM. P. TELLER and SMYTH, of the Eleventh Precinct, yesterday afternoon were called upon to arrest a man charged with voting illegally in the Fifteenth Poll District of the Eleventh Ward, situated at No. 416 Tenth-street. While the prisoner was being conveyed to the Station-house, and when near the corner of Avenue D and Fourth-street, an attack was made upon the officers by a gang of rowdles, some of whom fired nearly a dozen shots at them. One of the balls took effect in the left ear of Officer TELLER, passed backward and lodged in his head. The desperadoes then fled. Officer SMYTH pursued them, and just as he was on the point of capturing TELLER'S assailant, the latter paused momentarily in his flight, threw off his coat, drew a revolver and fired several shots at SMYTH. Very fortunately none of the shots took effect. All of the gang finally succeeded in making their escape. Capt. MOUNT, of the Eleventh Precinct, has the names of several of the would-be murderers, and he and his men are making active exertions to secure them. Officer TELLER was conveyed to the Stationhouse, where the ball was extracted by one of the Police surgeons. Subsequently he was conveyed to his residence, No. 298 East Fourth-street, in an exhausted condition. It is thought the wound will not prove fatal.

lead_paragraph: The statesman- like and philosophical speech delivered by Mr. SEWARD at Auburn on Monday evening, and which was published exclusively in the TIMES of yesterday, contains much matter for the profound thought of the country. Its broad and comprehensive patriotism, its determined and unflinching spirit in the prosecution of the war, its cheerful and hopeful view of affairs -- all its characteristics are such as become one occupying his distinguished position. If we might find any fault with the matter, it would be that the speech was not delivered a few days earlier, so that it might have been spread before the people of the ??? continent previous to the ???tion. As it was, it reached hundreds of thousands of voters through the TIMES.

abstract: Wm. BUCKLEY, of No. 229 Water-street, made complaint before Justice DOWLING yesterday at the Tombs Police Court, against NICHOLAS VAN GILDER, whom he charges with having voted illegally at the Second poll district of the Second Ward.
lead_paragraph: Wm. BUCKLEY, of No. 229 Water-street, made complaint before Justice DOWLING yesterday at the Tombs Police Court, against NICHOLAS VAN GILDER, whom he charges with having voted illegally at the Second poll district of the Second Ward. When VAN GILDER offered his vote, he gave his residence as No. 1 Fulton Market. Upon being challenged he swore in his vote, after which inquiry was made and it was found that no man of the name of the accused had lived at No. 1 Fulton Market; and, moreover, that the place was not a dwelling, but merely a cellar under the market. Officer HAYS, of the Second Precinct, arrested VAN GUILDER, and Justice DOWLING committed him for trial in default of one thousand dollars bail....JOHN SIMMS and JOSEPH BAIRD were arrested by the Twenty-third Precinct Police, charged with attempting to vote illegally. The prisoners were taken before Justice DOWLING, and committed to await an examination.... Mr. JOHN GILL, of No. 101 East Twenty-sixth-street, caused the arrest of HUGH HAVILAND, a soldier, 38 years of age, on the charge of having deposited a fraudulent vote. Justice KELLY committed him.... A sailor, named NATHAN B. LUTHER, was taken into custody by Officer VAN WALKINSHAW, of the Twenty- seventh Precinct, charged with having voted illegally. Justice DOWLNG committed the accused to await the production of evidence against him....A man named WM. H. GREEN was taken into custody by the Seventeenth Precinct Police, on the charge of inducing soldiers to vote illegally. He was committed to Prison at the Essex Market Court.
