abstract: Election; Its Significance and Lesson
snippet: Election; Its Significance and Lesson
lead_paragraph: The country has, after four years' experience of it, given an emphatic adhesion to the policy of President LINCOLN. Any objections to it, grounded on the assumption, which has been so loudly put forward, that he had used the powers of the Government in a way of which the country did not dream when it lodged them in his hands, and of which it has not approved since it has witnessed it, are now completely disposed of. The nation has watched his manner of administering the Government for four years. It knows all about the confiscation act, the "arbitary arrests," the emancipation proclamation, the conscription acts, the "bastiles," the ??? public debt, the test oaths, the dismissal of GEORGE B. McCLELLAN, and the employment of negro soldiers; there is hardly any subject upon which it has not heard Mr. LINCOLN's opinions. There is no charge which his opponents bring against him, with which it is not perfectly familiar. It knows that he tells "little stories" to people who call upon him; that he is not handsome; that his clothes are not well made; that he is unable to prevent our armies from occasionally meeting with reverses in Georgia or elsewhere, when he is in Washington; that he did not prevent the Alabama from making her escape from Liverpool; that the roads in Virginia were muddy in the first year of his administration; and that a drought occurred in the last; and yet, knowing all these things, the majority of the people of the loyal States have deliberately, and after full discussion, expressed their desire that he shall continue to hold office during four years more.

Mr. GREENLEAF graduated from Dartmouth College in 1811. From 1820 to 1850 he was the honored and eminent Principal of Bradford Academy, where he fitted thousands of young men for college, many of whom have since become distinguished in the various walks of life. Mr. GREENLEAF was probably still more widely known as the author of a series of mathematical works, which have had a wide popularity, and are found in public and private schools all over the land.

abstract: Confederacy Alliance Scheme, Reported by Sanders and Clay; Rebel Emissaries in the Provinces
snippet: Confederacy Alliance Scheme, Reported by Sanders and Clay; Rebel Emissaries in the Provinces
lead_paragraph: We received last night special and authentic information from Quebec, that GEORGE N. SANDERS and CLEMENT C. CLAY have sought and obtained a quasi-official interview with the Government there, whether with the approval of Lord MONK or not, we do not learn. The mission, of course, was suggested by anticipations of a possible intention on the part of the authorities to surrender the St. Alban's robbers. The rebel emissaries, however, embraced the occasion to lay before the members of the Provincial Government what purported to be the basis of a secret agreement, entered into between the Richmond authorities and the Emperor MAXIMILIAN. The agreement. included the terms of an alliance, offensive and defensive in its character, between Mexico and the Confederacy.

abstract: It is well to say at the outset that the capture of the Florida in a Brazilian port is clearly illegal, being a breach of that law of nations which we as much as any other Power just now more than most Powers, are interested in upholding.
lead_paragraph: It is well to say at the outset that the capture of the Florida in a Brazilian port is clearly illegal, being a breach of that law of nations which we as much as any other Power just now more than most Powers, are interested in upholding. There might be some justification for seizing her in an English port, as she owes her powers of mischief to the failure of the English authorities to execute their own laws; and her career of destruction, so far from having been a subject of regret to the English public, has, we fear, to the majority of them, been a source of high satisfaction. If, therefore, an American Captain had assailed and sunk her in British waters, although the act would undoubtedly have been a violation of law, there might have been some excuse found for it in the ordinary feelings of human nature. There are some tests which even the patience of the most patient cannot stand, and if American patience were to break down under the spectacle of a course of robbery begun in violation of English law, protected by the English flag, and applauded by the English people, whatever lawyers might say, morality could not severely condemn.

abstract: Fenian Conspiracy in Toronto
snippet: Fenian Conspiracy in Toronto
lead_paragraph: The Fenian organization in Toronto appears to be a more formidable affair than it appeared at first night. The police have made important discoveries, ??? we gather from the Toronto Globe, and the master has caused unusual excitement. In the house of one of the Fenian leaders. named McGUIRR, the peace found nothing of a suspicious character till after they had proceeded up stairs, when, as they were entering a room, they met a woman coming out with a box in her arms. She acted as if she was trying to avoid them, and at she was trying to get away, McDOWELL caught her, and demanded the box, which, after some bantering, she give up. It was opened on the spot, and found to contain some twenty or thirty heavy pikes. They are well made deadly-looking instruments, about eight inches long, she ??? like a spear-head of the olden time. At the bull-end there is a screw which fastens the head 10 the candle, and the instrument is then ready for its deadly work. abstract: The election returns continue to come in very slowly, in consequence of the continued bad weather, which seriously interferes with the working of the telegraph. Enough is now known, however, in regard to this State, to establish beyond a doubt that the Union majority on the electoral ticket is from six to eight thousand, while GOV. FENTON's majority may be somewhat more. Seven Union Congressmen are certainly gained, including Messrs. RAYMOND and DARLING of this city, HUMPHREY of Brooklyn, KETCHUM of Dutchess, GRISWOLD of Rensselaer, CONKLING of Oneida, and HOLLEY of Buffalo. The loyal public will regret that the corrected returns in the Eighth District of this city elect BROOKS (Peace Democrat) over WM. E. DODGE, the merchant and patriot, by 146 majority. This makes the Congressional delegation stand 21 Union to 10 Democrats. Our readers can rest assured that New-  York has cast her majority on the side of the Union. The general result is highly gratifying. Mr. LINCOLN receives the electoral vote of every State but Kentucky, New-Jersey and Delaware, amounting to 213 votes. MCCLELLAN receives that of the States named, amounting to 21. Mr. LINCOLN's majority is therefore 192. The next House of Representatives will stand 140 Union to 44 Democrats, giving the Union party a clear majority of two-thirds.

abstract: Postal Money Order System
snippet: Postal Money Order System
lead_paragraph: The Money-Order system already gives promise of a large business. But we cannot join in the felicitations of those who find satisfaction in the prospect of its becoming a valuable auxiliary in commercial transactions. When we described the proposed arrangements of this new branch of the postal service in these columns, we took occasion to point out that one of the great dangers against which the department had to guard, was that of making these postal drafts a convenience for petty traders. We hear, now, with some degree of concern, that the use of the Post as an agency for commercial drafts, has already developed into a business of considerable magnitude. The limited amount of each separate draft is overcome, of course, by a repetition of the purchase, on the part of the buyer, to suit his convenience. He may purchase ten thirty-dollar orders in a day, or he may buy fifty; and he may repeat the operation from week to week.

abstract: Florida Capture; Capt. Winslow's Summary
snippet: Florida Capture; Capt. Winslow's Summary
lead_paragraph: -- The particulars of the capture of the Florida will be all the more eagerly scanned from the doubt which surrounds the transaction, on grounds both of policy and law. Capt. WINSLOW, at the Boston Navy-yard, on Tuesday, gave a brief summary of the facts which, we have no doubt, are perfectly authentic, although that distinguished officer had no further act or part in the matter than bringing the prisoners captured from St. Thomas to Boston harbor. The capture was made on the morning of the 7th of October, while the Florida was lying in the harbor of Bahia, close up to the city. This statement differs not a little from that which we published on Wednesday. That report represented that the Wachusett was lying close into the harbor, but that the Florida was outside. The difference, as affects the interpretation of the maritime rights of the neutral Powers, of course, amounts to nothing. But the difference is not without significance, as marking the strength of impulse as distinct from the strength of reason, which, in the two cases, would guide Capt. COLLINS in acting as he did.

abstract: New Campaign; New Campaign
snippet: New Campaign; New Campaign
lead_paragraph: It is not at all strange that the circumstances concerning the new campaign proposed by Gen. SHERMAN, which were published exclusively in the TIMES of yesterday, should have produced a profound sensation throughout the country. We have had nothing of a military character analogous to it in the course of the war -- if we except the grand march made by SHERMAN from Vicksburgh across the State of Mississippi, at the beginning of this year; and even that remarkable campaign differed, and was inferior, in many important particulars, to the new one whose outlines we gave. The end to be achieved in this case is far more important; the distance to be traversed much greater; the time to be covered much longer; the difficulties to be overcome much more formidable; and the operating column much heavier. In the former case, the rebel army was in his front, and he drove it before him; in this case he leaves it in his rear, and takes no heed of it. From Atlanta to Augusta is one hundred and seventy-one miles; from Augusta to Charleston one hundred and twenty-one miles, to Savannah one hundred and thirty-six miles. But, as an evening cotemporary, in quoting our news, correctly remarks, "the country is not difficult; no mountain ranges lie in the way, to make transportation laborious, such as ROSECRANS met in Tennessee in his campaign against Chattanooga; no passes or defiles present easily defensible positions to an opposing force; the whole region both to the south and east is rich in food, and has been untouched by the war. And in whatever direction they may march, SHERMAN and his troops well know that at the end of their route friendly cooperation and abundant supplies await them.

abstract: The news which we announced yesterday morning, that the arrival of the famous steamer Kearsarge at this port had brought the intelligence of the capture in Brazilian waters by the Union gunboat Wachusett, of the notorious rebel cruiser Florida, sent a thrill of surprise and delight through the community even in the midst of the excitement and anxiety of Presidential election day. The joyful news spread over the city like wildfire, and was the universal subject of discussion and of mutual congratulation, until the interests of the Congressional and National elections seemed almost to be forgotten in comparison. One of our reporters paid a visit to the Kearsarge during the day, and by the kind courtesy of her officers. Paymaster J.A. SMITH being especially obliging, was enabled to obtain a detailed account of the singular affair in the bay of Bahia, comprising all the particulars which are accessible to the public.

lead_paragraph: We have an abstract of JEFF. DAVIS' message to his Congress, which met in Richmond on the first secular day of this week. It discusses military and financial matters, and foreign relations, and also the great question which has recently been brought up in the Southern press, of arming the slaves to fight for the Slave Confederacy. Mr. DAVIS opposes in general, the idea of arming negro slaves, but, after all, he practically favors their being armed; and, moreover, he would reward with the boon of freedom such slaves as shall serve efficiently with arms in the field.

abstract: Speech at Boston; Sailor's Fair
snippet: Speech at Boston; Sailor's Fair
lead_paragraph: The grand National Sailors' Fair to be held in Boston during this week and next, was opened last Wednesday evening with complete success. It is held in the spacious and elegant Boston Theatre. The audience present at the opening was a large and exceedingly brilliant one. It drew together, says the Boston Courier, "men of all parties and ranks in life, united in a common purpose -- to aid in the establishment of a Sailors' Home for Seamen and Mariners disabled in the naval service of their country. All differences of opinion, of policy, in the conduct of the war, were laid aside for this grand and noble occasion. An imperative need exists for a "Home" for the brave seamen who have perilled their lives in their country's defence, and become disabled for further service. That is enough. It is a call to arouse every generous sympathy; it is an opportunity, for which we should feel grateful, to testify, in some degree, our regard for the navy, -- its commanders and its men, -- which has done so much for the honor of the country and to maintain its flag and the call has been responded to in a manner worthy of the men and women of New-England, who have devoted themselves to the work of raising funds for the support of an adequate establishment for our disabled and worn tars.

abstract: ATTACK ON A DWELLING-HOUSE BY RUFFIANS. -- On Wednesday evening three ruffians made an attack on the dwelling-house of Mr. J.P. SKILLMAN, merchant, No. 280 South Fifth-street, and fired vollies of stones, a number of which entered the windows. There were several ladies in the front room at the time, who, fortunately, escaped injury. The men continued throwing stones for some minutes, and then went away, but subsequently returned, and repeated the outrage, after which they left, before assistance could be obtained to arrest them. The cause for this procedure is unknown, but it is believed that Mr. SKILLMAN's house was mistaken for that of Rev. Mr. VERRINDLER, City Missionary, adjoining, who, it is stated, has been threatened with violence at the hands of parties to whom Mr. VERRINDER's labors as City Missionary are obnoxious.

abstract: Centenarian Voter for Lincoln
snippet: Centenarian Voter for Lincoln
lead_paragraph: Deacon JOHN PHILLIPS, of Sturbridge, Mass., who is 104 years, 4 months and 9 days old, appeared at the town hall and deposited his ballot for Presidential electors and State officers. He was brought in a carriage, and they conveyed into the hall in a chair, supported by a platoon of our returned soldiers, and received by the citizens of the town rising from their seats, amid the tears and heartfelt emotions of all present. After resting for a moment, the venerable patriot expressed a desire to shake hands with all the returned soldiers. Some thirteen soldiers then formed in line, when each one was introduced to the patriarch, and took him by the hand, with the announcement of the time each had served in the army. After this, three hearty cheers were given for the returned soldiers, and three rousing cheers by the whole assembly for the "old soldier of the revolution."

abstract: As every well-regulated New-Yorker Knows, "extremes meet" in the Nursery and Child's Hospital. While the charity itself comforts and saves the most dependent class of our population, the ladies who administer it represent the gayest and most brilliant social circles of the metropolis.
lead_paragraph: As every well-regulated New-Yorker Knows, "extremes meet" in the Nursery and Child's Hospital. While the charity itself comforts and saves the most dependent class of our population, the ladies who administer it represent the gayest and most brilliant social circles of the metropolis. Hence it came to pass in the "good old times" before secession vexed the land, that the annual ball of the Nursery was of all annual balls the most charming, the most animated, and the most "fashionable." The "Annual Ball" has ceased to be; but the Nursery still extends its priceless relief to hundreds of poor and distressed mothers, and the Child's Hospital still opens wide its doors of tenderness to the disinherited of the earth. And as in the place of the ball something must be found to persuade fashion into paying its tithes of alms, the ladies of this excellent institution have judiciously availed themselves of Mr. MARETZEK's brief interregnum at the Academy, to offer the world the finest concert of the season -- a concert to be adorned not only by the lights of the opera-stage, but by the stars of the opera-boxes.

abstract: Votes Among Vicious Population of New-York; Election Returns; Interesting Figures
snippet: Votes Among Vicious Population of New-York; Election Returns; Interesting Figures
lead_paragraph: We would like to have those "respectable" Democrats who stood by their party in the recent election, bestow a little attention on the analysis of the returns from this city. They should ask themselves the question why it is that the lowest districts of the city, the haunts of vice and crime, the notorious headquarters of gamblers and ruffians, and all the most crowded and wretched of the "tenement-house" districts, give tremendous majorities for the Opposition, while the wards where are intelligent American mechanics, and where are gathered the most education and character among the merchants and professional men, uniformly poll a strong Union vote. We venture to say that throughout the country, from Maine to Kansas, this is the general rule, though with here and there marked exceptions. The vicious and ignorant population of the cities and manufacturing villages has been for MCCLELLAN, while the strength of LINCOLN lay in the farming class, and the intelligent classes of the towns.

abstract: New Revolution Threatened
snippet: New Revolution Threatened
lead_paragraph: We, in common with the civilized world, are regarding with deep interest the grand experiment which the Southern Confederacy is about making with the arming of the slaves. The skillful and desperate oligarchy which control it, having lost all their own property in the struggle, are about casting that for which the rebellion was made into the burning cauldron of civil war. They have exhausted the white population, forcing into the ranks State officials, detailed producers, and even those over forty-five years and under eighteen who could bear arms. DAVIS, with that clear, cold glance of his, sees that his ambition has buried under the soil of the battle-fields the flower of the Southern youth, and that now he must turn to his last resource -- the most desperate of all expedients -- the arming of the slaves.

abstract: and Capt Ericsson
snippet: and Capt Ericsson
lead_paragraph: - It will be seen that the great ocean iron-clad monitor ram Dictator, which made her trial trip in the bay yesterday, failed to approve herself the perfect machine which had been promised. There has been great discussion about this vessel among naval men during her progress in building; but Capt. ERICSSON's name, and his notes, have done much to keep up public confidence in her. Persons had even gone so far as to assert that she would not float above water at all; but that when she got her guns, ordnance-stores and coal aboard, she would be at least level with the water, if not several inches or feet under it. In reply to these criticisms and assertions, Capt. ERICSSON wrote a note a few days ago, in which he said that "nothing has occurred to indicate that the Dictator will disappoint the expectation of the Navy Department;" and further stated, that on the 2d inst., when she had two-thirds of her stores, half her complement of shot, and six hundred tons of coal aboard, she was thirty-one inches out of water at the stern, and forty-three inches out of water at the bow -- that her draft was halt an inch less than the estimates, and that she would have to be brought eight inches deeper in order to be in proper fighting trim. These statements from Capt. ERICSSON were very reassuring. On the trial trip, yesterday, however, according to the naval report of it, the vessel was carefully measured, and found to be above the surface of the water as follows: Forward, 2 feet 10 inches; aft, 2 feet; amidships, 15 1/4 inches. How much further she will be depressed when she gets all of her war stock aboard, remains to be seen -- though we suppose it is a matter capable of calculation. The naval report also sets forth other serious defects in the Dictator's steerage and movements.

abstract: and the Corn C???b
snippet: and the Corn C???b
lead_paragraph: Apropos of JOSHUA BATES, the great London banker, whose death has just been so appropriately noticed by our Chamber of Commerce, a little incident occurs to us that amusingly yet fully illustrates his jealous love for his native land. In the month of January, 1847, at a certain dinner party in London, at which Lord JOHN RUSSELL, Lord MORPETH, Mr. BATES, and many other distinguished men were present, the conversation turned upon the Irish famine; and the remark was made by Lord JOHN that he rejoiced that so good a substitute for the native breadstuff had been found as the Indian corn. Turning to Mr. BATES his lordship went on to say, "Why, BATES, some of the cobs have twelve or fourteen rows of grain on them." Mr. BATES coolly replied, "Yes, my Lord, I have seen from twenty to twenty-four rows on a cob." "That is a rank Yankeeism," was the pleasant retort of the Premier, and the whole company shouted in approval. The burst of incredulous merriment over, Mr. BATES bought his peace by a wager of a dinner for the company all round that he could produce such an ear. "Done!" exclaimed Lord JOHN, and the bet was clinched.

abstract: I. LAWRENCE GRENNA, of No. 188 East 36th-st., New-York City, have been suffering from blindness of the left eye for a considerable period. The eye was continually in a state of great inflammation, from which the good eye became affected, and, indeed, my general health we greatly injured by it. Hearing of Dr. Von Elsenberg a great reputation, and as everyone said mine was a hopeless case, I called on the Doctor, who, after examining me, undertook my case, and within a fortnight I found myself almost completely cured. It is now a month sine I placed myself under Dr. Von Elsenberg's treatment, I am happy to be able to state that the inflammation is entirely gone, so that I see perfectly with both eyes, added to which I am in good health, a blessing I have not enjoyed since I was blind. I do conscientiously and gratefully swear to the above statement, in a Court of justice at the City Hall of the City of New-York, the 10th day of October, 1864.

lead_paragraph: The victory achieved, -- the result secured, -- the great end and aim of the campaign accomplished, -- there was a large and enthusiastic gathering of loyal Union-loving citizens at Cooper Institute last evening, called together under the auspices of the New-York Republican Young Men's Association, to give expression to the general joy which pervades the community, at the decided and overwhelming majorities cast on Tuesday in support of the principles of liberty, nationality and Union. The ladies were present in large numbers, to add, by their presence, to the eclat at the occasion. Every available foot of space was occupied at an early hour; and as for [???]eats, much to the inconvenience of the representatives of the press, a raid was made even upon the chairs set apart for reporters. Everybody congratulated everybody else; the greatest enthusiasm and goodfeeling prevailed, and the audience, while waiting for the speakers, occasionally burst into an extemporaneous chorus.

abstract: A grand reception was accorded to Capt. WINSLOW and the officers and crew of the Kearsarge on Thursday, in Faneull Hall. The old "Cradle of Liberty" was handsomely decorated for the occasion. In the centre of the hall, suspended from the celling,
lead_paragraph: A grand reception was accorded to Capt. WINSLOW and the officers and crew of the Kearsarge on Thursday, in Faneull Hall. The old "Cradle of Liberty" was handsomely decorated for the occasion. In the centre of the hall, suspended from the celling, was a twelve-rayed star of the national colors. From this radiated streamers in every direction. The balconies were inscribed with the names of "WINSLOW" and "THORNTON," the Captain and Lieutenant-Commander of the Kearsarge, "PORTER" and "FARRAGUT." Between these appeared shields bearing the national escutcheons, with the shields of the City of Boston and the United States, with the national ensigns as supporters. Upon the platform was a model of the Kearsarge, which was examined with much interest.

abstract: Literary Gossip
snippet: Literary Gossip
lead_paragraph: An interesting literary relie has come to light unexpectedly in Scotland, where a gentleman, Mr. J.D. CAMPBELL, of Glasgow, has printed an elegant 4 -- to the edition limited to 250 copies -- "Some portions of the essays contributed to the Spectator, by Mr. JOSEPH ADDISON, now first printed from his M.S. note book." The original manuscript from which the volume is printed, was purchased for a small price of a London bookseller in 1858. On examination it was found to contain, though imperfect at the beginning, several of ADDISON'S papers for the Spectator, written out in a neat clerkly hand on one side-of the leaves like a first draft, and numerous interlinear corrections, and additions on the opposite blank pages, in the undoubted writing of ADDISON himself. These changes and enlargements are very curious, and show by what careful attention to minutiae, the style, "familiar but not coarse, and elegant but not ostentatious," (to use the words of JOHNSON,) that has conferred immortality upon its author, was acquired and perfected. Among the better-known papers thus shown in progress of construction are the essays on Jealousy and Fame, and a portion of the celebrated essay on the Imagination. A more instructive lesson on composition could hardly be given than this work affords. Some critics have insinuated doubts, owing to a want of a history of the M.S., but the internal evidence of its genuineness appears to be complete and satisfactory.

abstract: This beautiful prize steamer arrived at this port last evening, from Hampton Roads, in tow of the U.S. steamer Calypso, F.D. STUART, Acting Master commanding, by which vessel she was taken, and anchored off the Battery. Acting Ensign, WILLIAM JENNINGS, is in command of the prize. The Lady Sterling was built in London, and launched about four months ago. She is built of iron, and is about 960 tons burden, and had on board when captured over 400,000 pounds of cotton and some four tons of tobacco. Although she was in a disabled condition -- one of her cylinders being useless -- her Captain resolved to leave Wilmington with her. On the night of Oct. 28, coming out by what is known as the Western Bar Channel, she was soon seen by the United States steamer Eolus, and endeavoring to escape from her, found the United States steamer Calypso directly in her way. From the Calypso a number of shots were fired at the runner, the second one -- a shell -- exploding in the cotton stowed in her fore-hold. Notwithstanding this she still kept on her way, the Calypso being in hot pursuit, and making about thirteen miles per hour. After a chase of some three hours in duration, during which some seven or eight shots were lodged in different parts of the hull and machinery of the blockade runner, she was forced to surrender. The United States steamer Eolus being near at the time of the capture, has a share in the prize. The United States steamer Mohican convoyed the Calypso and prize to Sandy Hook, and sailed again for Hampton Roads. The following is a list of the officers of the Calypso:

abstract: And Confederacy; Sanders' Denial of Alliance; Courrier des Etats Unis on Mexico and Confederacy Alliance
snippet: And Confederacy; Sanders' Denial of Alliance; Courrier des Etats Unis on Mexico and Confederacy Alliance
lead_paragraph: The Courrier des Etats Unis hastens to deny that there is any truth in the report circulated by GEORGE N. SANDERS, as to a secret alliance between MAXIMILIAN and JEFF. DAVIS. It proclaims the whole thing false. When we published SANDERS' statement, we did not place much reliance upon it. But this disclaimer by the Courrier does not make the report, to our judgment, much less credible than it was before. We can hardly expect even the confidential literary agents of the French Emperor to know all that has transpired in the secret councils of the new Mexican Emperor. SANDERS, at all events, knows what his Richmond masters have told him. It may be a pure fabrication; but it is none the less one of the few remaining cards the rebels have to play, and they are attempting to play it with whatever skill they can command.

abstract: Extra-official Ambassadors to Quebec
snippet: Extra-official Ambassadors to Quebec
lead_paragraph: -We perceive that two excellent and well-meaning citizens of the United States have undertaken, on their own account, a mission to Quebec, to confer with the Provincial authorities on the subject of preventing further raids upon the border. We take it that labor of this sort might with advantage be left to the regular official agencies. There is more useful work for active and enterprizing citizens in forming a perfect organization for home defence along our border towns. The Provincial people do not seem indisposed to prevent a repetition of the St. Alban's villainies if they can; but in any case, if they fail to see what is their duty in the existing crisis, special and private appeals will hardly awaken them to a better sense. The border towns should be stirred to active and thorough preparation for any emergency.

abstract: All remains quiet at the headquarters of the General commanding the troops in the Department of the City and State of New-York. The same vigilant state of preparation is maintained to-day as, on the 8th of November, but all anticipations of a disturbance have ceased. On Thursday afternoon Gen. BUTLER and his Staff rode up to the Central Park and admired the pride of New-York in its Autumnal beauty. Last night the General visited the Cooper Institute and participated in the "jubilee" of the Young Men's Republican Club. The soldiers who were hurried on to this city last week have not fared very well since their arrival. They have been so closely confined here that they have had no opportunity to purchase any additions to their usual rations, and the Government has not been able to furnish them with soft bread. A movement is now on foot to give these men a supply of eatables of such a kind as will be most acceptable to them. Mr. B.T. BABBITT, of this city, has purchased one hundred barrels of excellent apples, which will be forwarded to-day to Brig.-Gen. HAWLEY, of Fort Richmond, Staten Island, to be distributed among the troops in and around New-York. The generous citizens of New-York have never failed to respond to any call which promised to add to the comfort or happiness of the soldiers of the Union, and in this case the reputation of the city for hospitality is concerned. Gen. GORDAN. Chief of Staff to Gen. BUTLER, will give all necessary information in regard to sending articles to the troops.

abstract: No Pause in Campaigning

lead_paragraph: The news from Gen. SHERMAN's army in Georgia, as well as from Gen. GRANT's army in Virginia, is certainly of a kind to show that there is to be no pause in the prosecution of active operations this Winter. SHERMAN is about to undertake one of the most remarkable campaigns of the war; and we judge from what we know that it is not at all unlikely that GRANT will have Petersburgh, and that the rebel army will be closely shut up in Richmond, before the close of this rapidly closing year.

abstract: On Thursday evening last, at the Academy of Music, JOHN B. GOUGH delivered his new lecture, Fact and Fiction, before the Mercantile Library Association. The Academy was literally packed, and with the elite of New-York, rarely does it ever look more brilliant, even on opera nights. Every seat was taken, and all the best ones were secured several days before the lecture was delivered. At 8 o'clock the speaker was introduced to the audience by Mr. THEODORE H. VULTER, President of the Mercantile Library Association. Mr. GOUGH's new lecture is a very creditable and entertaining one; many of his hits at the follies of the age were very amusing and very well made, and called forth bursts of laughter and applause from the audience. His patriotic allusions, his praise of GRANT. SHERMAN, FARRAGUT and SHERIDAN, and the expression of his earnest wishes for the welfare of his country, were received with the greatest enthusiasm. At the close of his lecture three hearty cheers were given for LINCOLN and JOHNSON, after which the audience dispersed.

abstract: There are some interesting facts in regard to registry for the elections of Tuesday last, which deserve public consideration before they are forgotten. About 15,000 more voters were registered than votes were deposited. A certain proportion of these were undoubtedly registered twice in consequence of removals to other wards. But 6,000 would probably cover all these. We may fairly estimate that 9,000 or 10,000 voters staid at home, and from the great defection in the expected Democratic majority we may possibly conclude they were Democrats. What occasioned this astonishing falling off of persons who, a few weeks ago registered their names to vote? We think it not at all an improbable thing that the arrival of Gen. BUTLER has had a very significant connection with this fact. There are more than 10,000 Southern refugees in the city. They very naturally expected to vote. Had they voted, we should have had Gov. SEYMOUR for another two years, which alone would have been worth a victory for JEFF. DAVIS. But the name and the preparations of Gen. BUTLER struck terror into them, and they kept away from the polls. In two of the strongest Democratic wards -- the First and Fourteenth -- there seem to have been some 2,000 more votes than were registered. The explanation we leave to those who have charge of the returns.

abstract: Our, and Chicago Platform on "Failure" of War; and Our Soldiers
snippet: Our, and Chicago Platform on "Failure" of War; and Our Soldiers
lead_paragraph: We who remain at home have but little idea of what this war is. Its sufferings, its hardships, its toils, its dangers, come not upon us, but upon the soldiers in the field. Their knowledge upon these points, therefore, is far better than ours. And so it is as to what has been done in the war, and what remains yet to be done. Their appreciation of all that is difficult, all that calls for endurance and sacrifice, must be keener and more accurate than ours. And yet from them there comes no complaint, no cry of dissatisfaction or discouragement. If we could only bring the people who are at home up to the same plane of feeling which the soldiers occupy, what doubt could there be in any one's mind of the result?

abstract: New-York, on the Citizens' Association; Reply to Commercial Advertiser on Citizens' Association
snippet: New-York, on the Citizens' Association; Reply to Commercial Advertiser on Citizens' Association
lead_paragraph: The Commercial Advertiser, of this city, bestows considerable attention upon the operations of the Citizens' Association, and expresses apprehensions in regard to it, because, as it says, the Association is directed by a policy, not actuated by a principle, and that it expects to accomplish municipal reform by changing one set of officials for another. The Commercial thinks the Association mistakes the remedy for municipal corruption, and that if it succeeds in changing the character of our city rulers it will be an endless and hopeless task to keep pure the fountains of power. The true remedy, in the judgment of the Commercial, is in an amended charter, freeing the city from legislative interference, and in the decentralization of power, so that the city government shall have no fat jobs to farm out.

abstract: Trenholm's Rebel Currency Scheme; Finances of the Confederacy
snippet: Trenholm's Rebel Currency Scheme; Finances of the Confederacy
lead_paragraph: The romance in which DAVIS indulges in his last address to his Congress is specially shown in his financial references. The rebel treasury, he arows, is not in a bad condition at all. Things, in fact, look altogether hopeful. Between the present time and the first of June, 1865, he will want in all only $438,102,679, to carry him through, and more than this sum his Congress has already provided him with; for, on the 1st of January, 1865, he will have fund on hand, in the shape of unappropriated balances, to the amount of $467,416,504.

lead_paragraph: Years ago Europe looked across the miles of waves that loss between us, and wondered at our marvellous prorperity: wondered that our experiment of self-government, so antagonistic to all her Old World notions, should have developed so successfully. Steadily, surely we had progressed until the right to be considered one of the great powers seemed but the preliminary to a necessity of acknowledging us the greatest. Whether Europe considered this young giant of the West something to be feared whether Europe, observing the little sectional disagreements that pervaded our Governments councils, made her influence felt to bring about the crisis that has since expanded into oar terrible present, let history and the future demonstrate.

abstract: New-York--G Rickel Shot in Rose-st Saloon
snippet: New-York--G Rickel Shot in Rose-st Saloon
lead_paragraph: At an early hour yesterday morning, a shocking murder was perpetrated in a lager beer saloon in the basement of No. 55 Rose-street. It seems that two Germans residing in the rear of that number, named GEORGE NICKEL and LOUIS SCHLVECK, went out on Friday evening for the purpose of enjoying themselves in an innocent way by partaking of lager and in pleasant conversation. They went into one or two saloons, where, it would seem, they partook somewhat freely of the German beverage. At a late hour they returned home. When opposite their dwellings, they concluded to go into the front basement of No. 55 and have one more glass. They did so, and, as appears by the following testimony, taken yesterday by Coroner NAUMANN on the inquest, they had been inside but a few moments when the man behind the bar, named CHARLES P. ENGSTRON, drew a pistol from beneath the counter and instantly fired at NICKEL. The ball entered just on the right side of his nose, passed through the centre of his brain and came out at the back part of his skull. NICKEL fell to the floor and died almost instantly. It will be seen by the testimony of deceased's friend that at this time no word had passed between deceased and the barkeeper, and that the shooting was entirely unprovoked. abstract: the Kagosima Expedition
snippet: the Kagosima Expedition
lead_paragraph: The profits of Japanese commerce will hardly indemnify foreigners for all the trouble, cost and disgrace incurred in attempting to coerce those misanthropic orientals into sociability. The attack of Admiral KUPER on Kagosima, and the destruction of that city, brought as little of gain as of glory to England, and now another expedition has been planned against another recusant Daimio, which promises to be no more satisfactory in its results than the former one. The expedition against Kagosima was undertaken to compel the Prince of Satsuma to surrender the assassins of RICHARDSON; the present expedition is to be undertaken to compel the Prince of NAGATO to permit foreign vessels to navigate what is called the "Inland Sea." The entrance to this sea is protected by forts, which have been of late greatly strengthened, and which open fire on every European or American ship that ventures to approach them. To silence these forts then, and to bring Prince CHOSIN to terms, a formidable naval force has been organized, to which such of the foreign Powers having treaties with Japan, and which consider themselves aggrieved by this action of NAGATO, has contributed all the means of offence at their disposal in those waters -- the English, fifteen steamers, of various armament; the Dutch, four corvettes; the French, a line-of-battle ship and two smaller vessels; and the United States, one steamer.

abstract: Tallmadge, Gov, of Michigan; Elton, Hon. John P., of Connecticut; Medary, Samuel, of Ohio
snippet: Tallmadge, Gov, of Michigan; Elton, Hon. John P., of Connecticut; Medary, Samuel, of Ohio
lead_paragraph: The telegraph announces the death of Ex-Gov. SAMUEL MEDARY, at his residence in Columbus, Ohio, on Monday. He was born in Maryland about the commencement of the present century, and emigrated to Ohio upon attaining his majority. In the political campaign of 1828, he was editor of the Sun, published in Clermont County, and supported Gen. JACKSON for President. In 1833 he represented his county in the State Senate. During his Senatorial career, he was elected by the State Legislature, State Printer, and removed to Columbus, where he published the Western Hemisphere, a Democratic sheet, which, in a short time, was changed to the Ohio Statesman. Under the Administration of Mr. POLK, Col. MEDARY was Postmaster at Columbus; under that of Mr. BUCHANAN he was appointed Governor of Minnesota, and upon the admission of that Territory into the Union as a State, was transferred to Kansas as Territorial Governor, and served in that capacity until that Territory also became a State, when he returned to Ohio, where he soon after established the Crisis. Elected [???] represent, in part, the Capital District in the Chicago Convention, Gov. MEDARY made arrangements to attend, but was prevented by that sickness which proved fatal.

abstract: A dispatch from Chattanooga, dated Nov. 11, says that on Monday morning, Nov. 7, at daylight, the rebels attacked our pickets south of Atlanta, killed one, wounded two of the Third Indiana, but subsequently they fell back.
lead_paragraph: A dispatch from Chattanooga, dated Nov. 11, says that on Monday morning, Nov. 7, at daylight, the rebels attacked our pickets south of Atlanta, killed one, wounded two of the Third Indiana, but subsequently they fell back. On Wednesday morning the rebels made three attacks on Atlanta, shells being thrown as far as Boiling Mill. The most desperate attack was made on the Rough and Ready road. The rebel artillery was within one hundred yards of our works, and their infantry and dismounted cavalry within two hundred yards. Our men were aroused from their slumbers, and quickly manned the defences and soon drove the rebels off. The rebels were part of YOUNG's command, and they finally retreated toward Macon. Our army is in excellent spirits and well supplied with nations. The election has gone largely for LINCOLN. The Cincinnati Gazette has a dispatch from Nashville, which denies the reported evacuation of Atlanta by Gen. SHERMAN, and the destruction of the Atlanta and Chattanooga Railroad.

abstract: -In the Spring of 1861, when the calls to patriotism went like wildfire over the lamd, a young man in the Third Ward of Chicago, named GEORGE W. TREYSER, was engaged to be married to a young lady in a Western city, who died last week, and was buried here. He enlisted, promising to return as soon as the war was over, and left his affianced almost broken-hearted. At the battle of Wilson's Creek he was killed. When the news reached this city, his betrothed went into fainting fits, and for two days her life was despaired of. She never recovered her reason entirely, but lived, as it were, under the shadow of some impenetrable gloom, She selected a chicken from a brood and took if to her room, where she made a plaything or a pet of it. She gave it a name, which in time it knew, and soon came at her call. It would perch on her head as she would sit looking from her window, and pick crumbs from her lips when she saw fit to feed it, and pick at per teeth as though they were kernels of co[???]h. She would sit for hours caressing the chicken, which grew into as sleek and pretty a rooster as ever lived, and which formed an affection for its mistress truly wonderful. And thus the pair lived till three weeks since, when the chicken was killed by a dog. Since this time the girl grew languid, nervous, disheartened, and at last died with a broken heart. Such, in brief, is an actual incident which thus passes into the history or the singular freaks of affection. -- Natchez (Miss.) Courier.
lead_paragraph: -In the Spring of 1861, when the calls to patriotism went like wildfire over the lamd, a young man in the Third Ward of Chicago, named GEORGE W. TREYSER, was engaged to be married to a young lady in a Western city, who died last week, and was buried here. He enlisted, promising to return as soon as the war was over, and left his affianced almost broken-hearted. At the battle of Wilson's Creek he was killed. When the news reached this city, his betrothed went into fainting fits, and for two days her life was despaired of. She never recovered her reason entirely, but lived, as it were, under the shadow of some impenetrable gloom, She selected a chicken from a brood and took if to her room, where she made a plaything or a pet of it. She gave it a name, which in time it knew, and soon came at her call. abstract: on Offensive and Defensive War, and a factious opposition; on Offensive and Defensive War and a Factious Opposition
snippet: on Offensive and Defensive War, and a factious opposition; on Offensive and Defensive War and a Factious Opposition
lead_paragraph: In one of his most elaborate speeches, the great nullifier, JOHN C. CALHOUN, marks the distinction between an offensive and defensive war, and between a factious and reasonable Congressional opposition, with a philosophic clearness which merits some attention from his professed followers, North and South, at this crisis. The occasion of the speech was the report of a bill from the Committee on Military Affairs, reported to the House of Representatives on the 10th of January, 1814, authorizing the President to raise, for five years' service, fourteen regiments of infantry authorized by an act of the previous session. Mr. CALHOUN's duty was to show the justice and expediency of the measure. Its rejection involved the withdrawal of the force designated for the conquest of Canada, the general reduction of the army, and the abandonment of all naval operations against the public enemy.

abstract: Manhattan, Monitor, Exploits of
snippet: Manhattan, Monitor, Exploits of
lead_paragraph: As it is now generally conceded that the 15-Inch shot of the monitor Manhattan was the one which did serious injury to the rebel ram Tennessee, the course pursued by her in the engagement of Mobile Bay, is a matter of public interest. Prior to the attack upon the Mobile Bay forts, the monitor Manhattan arrived off the Bay, and shortly after steamed inside and anchored between Sand Island and Fort Gaines, in a position under fire from Forts Morgan and Gaines, and where no wooden vessel, during the three years of blockade had ever been placed; she was also in such a position that the rebel ram Tennessee could have attacked her at any time with impunity from any interference on the part of the wooden vessels, as they were all, with the exception or one gunboat outside of the outer bar of the Bay.

abstract: Serenade to
snippet: Serenade to
lead_paragraph: -Quite an interesting event took place on Thursday evening, in front of the residence of Mr. JOHN M[???]. The occasion was a serenade given to Mr. CHARLES C. KING, of the Treasury Department, Washington, D.C., brother-in-law of Mr. MORTIMER. The friends of Mr. KING, hearing of his arrival in the city, and desirous of expressing some mark of their esteem, took this method of doing it. After several beautiful airs from DODWORTH's celebrated band, Mr. KING was called out, and in response to a call for a speech, said he came to the City of New-York to assist in electing the Lincoln and Johnson electoral ticket, and predicted that four years more of the rule of the present Administration would restore peace and harmony to the country. He also uttered some severe remarks on the traitorous acts of Gov. SEYMOUR, and congratulated his listeners on the elevation of REUBEN E. FENTON to the gubernatorial chair of the Empire State. In conclusion, Mr. KING thanked them for this flattering evidence of their regard, and retired amid vociferous applause from the assemblage.

abstract: of Detroit, Voted for Washington and Lincoln
snippet: of Detroit, Voted for Washington and Lincoln
lead_paragraph: -A most impressive scene was witnessed at the polls of the Third Ward, in this city, on Tuesday last. An elderly man, over whose head almost a century had passed, and who had voted for GEORGE WASHINGTON, when he was chosen President of the United States, turned his trembling steps from the grave, upon the brink of which he was almost tottering, and came, supported by his son and grandson, to give his last vote for ABRAHAM LINCOLN. He had twice voted for the Father of his country, and it was permitted him to vote twice for its Preserver. He had twice voted for GEORGE WASHINGTON, and he had lived to vote for the reelection of the man who will be gratefully remembered by the coming generation, not only of this country, but of the world, as the second Washington. The name of this venerable patriarch and patriot is GEORGE WILDER. He is the father of ARETUS A. WILDER, the well known machinist of this city. His son and grandson also cast their votes for ABRAHAM LINCOLN. -- Detroit Advertiser.

abstract: The latest intelligence from the Army of the Potomac shows that no material change has yet taken place in the situation around Richmond. There was much rejoicing in the Union army at the result of the elections.
lead_paragraph: The latest intelligence from the Army of the Potomac shows that no material change has yet taken place in the situation around Richmond. There was much rejoicing in the Union army at the result of the elections. A dispatch dated Friday, Nov. 11, says that on Wednesday evening, about 7 o'clock, a force of the enemy was discovered massing in front of our line, near Fort Steadman, when the guns of the fort opened fire, driving them to their works to seek shelter. The rebel batteries replied briskly for a time, but they were soon silenced by our shells and mortars. A force of about one hundred and fifty rebels shortly after made a sortie from their lines and attempted to penetrate ours, but, being met by a salute from our pickets, were not long in finding their way back, and putting themselves under cover.

abstract: Brazil-Florida Case; British Press Denouncing Capture; Florida Case; Brazilian and British View of; Rebel Press Denounce the Capture of the Florida
snippet: Brazil-Florida Case; British Press Denouncing Capture; Florida Case; Brazilian and British View of; Rebel Press Denounce the Capture of the Florida
lead_paragraph: The rebel organs in London, it will be seen, are in desperate haste to denounce the capture of the Florida in Brazilian waters. They describe it as an act of piracy. They are so fierce in their indignation, that it is easy enough to see they have a special interest in the matter. They threaten, that if the Florida is not instantly, released, it will be the duty of all the maritime Powers of Europe to interfere and compel her surrender by the United States to the Confederacy. This party bluster is not very dignified, it must be confessed. Beside being altogether unnecessary, so far as it could be supposed to influence our Government in its dealings toward a friendly Power, it barely escapes being impertinence in the present relations existing between Great Britain and Brazil for British journalists to lecture us on our duty toward that country.

abstract: The movement to provide a Thanksgiving Dinner for the soldiers and sailors goes on bravely, and yet much remains to be done. The work must be all completed this week. The Committee estimate that they need thirty thousand dollars in money, besides the large contributions in kind which they expect. They have raised in four days nearly half this sum, but they want the remainder at once. There is a sufficient willingness to give. No one who is asked refuses, but there is not time to call upon every one, and if the movement fails of its completeness it will be owing to the neglect of those who, while heartily sympathizing with it and willing to aid it, do not come forward themselves, but wait to be asked. To all therefore, we say, if you are going to give poultry or meat or pies don't fail to send it to Getty's Building in Trinity Place, before Saturday. Cook it, if you can. If you can't, the bakers of the city are moving to cook it without charge, and to-morrow's paper will tell you where these patriotic men may be found, or you may send it uncooked to Getty's Building, and the Committee will see that it is cooked. To those who are so situated that they prefer to give money, we say send it to-day to THEODORE ROSEVELT, Treasurer, No. 94 Maiden-Lane, and don't be satisfied with giving yourself, but solicit your friends to give also. This is a noble movement. Not less than one hundred and fifty thousand soldiers and sailors are to have a good Thanksgiving dinner. Who will not do his share in giving it to them? It is not a movement for the soldiers of any State or locality, but for all in the armies and squadrons of the East. Don't let it fail for want of a few thousand dollars or a few thousand pounds of poultry. In one Ward of this City an association has been formed, a room taken, and an appeal placed in every house in the Ward. A similar course should be pursued, not only in the other Wards in this City, but in every town throughout the north and east. Nearly every one can become a contributor, but every one can become a solicitor.

The Committee estimate that they need thirty thousand dollars in money, besides the large contributions in kind which they expect. They have raised in four days nearly half this sum, but they want the remainder at once. There is a sufficient willingness to give. No one who is asked refuses, but there is not time to call upon every one, and if the movement fails of its completeness it will be owing to the neglect of those who, while heartily sympathizing with it and willing to aid it, do not come forward themselves, but wait to be asked. To all therefore, we say, if you are going to give poultry or meat or pies don't fail to send it to Getty's Building in Trinity Place, before Saturday. Cook it, if you can. If you can't, the bakers of the city are moving to cook it without charge, and to-morrow's paper will tell you where these patriotic men may be found, or you may send it uncooked to Getty's Building, and the Committee will see that it is cooked. To those who are so situated that they prefer to give money, we say send it to-day to THEODORE ROSEVELT, Treasurer, No. 94 Maiden-Lane, and don't be satisfied with giving yourself, but solicit your friends to give also. This is a noble movement. Not less than one hundred and fifty thousand soldiers and sailors are to have a good Thanksgiving dinner. Who will not do his share in giving it to them? It is not a movement for the soldiers of any State or locality, but for all in the armies and squadrons of the East. Don't let it fail for want of a few thousand dollars or a few thousand pounds of poultry. In one Ward of this City an association has been formed, a room taken, and an appeal placed in every house in the Ward. A similar course should be pursued, not only in the other Wards in this City, but in every town throughout the north and east. Nearly every one can become a contributor, but every one can become a solicitor.

abstract: This ex-extensive and well-arranged zoological establishment, at Nos. 539 and 541 Broadway, which was a favorite resort of families during all of last Winter, opens for the season to-day, the animals comprised in Mr. VAN AMBURGH's fine collection having just returned from a seven months' tour through the New England States. The exhibition will be open throughout the day and evening, and a variety of interesting performances are announced to take place at 11 1/4 A.M., 3 and 8 1/2 P.M., each day. A newly-rained troupe of performing animals will be introduced for the first time in this city, while the elephant "Tippoo Saib," and highly-educated ponies, monkeys and mules will amuse and astonish visitors with practical evidences of their sagacity and superior training.

abstract: Comanche, Iron-clad, Launch
snippet: Comanche, Iron-clad, Launch
lead_paragraph: LAUNCH OF THE CAMANCHE -- AN IMPORTANT HISTORICAL EVENT -- YANKEES THE FIRST TO PLACE AN IRON-CLAD WAR VESSEL ON THE BOSOM OF THE PACIFIC OCEAN, &c., &c. -- It has been announced by telegraph across the Plains and over the mountains that on the 14th of November, 1864, the iron-clad monitor Camanche would be launched at San Francisco, Cal. The event will be handed down on the page of history as one of the greatest achievements of American enterprise. England, with all her boasting, cannot claim that she was the first to place her iron-clads in those waters. It is true, little Peru has an iron-clad just completed, but we date back to Nov. 11, 1863, when the Camanche arrived (in pieces) at San Francisco in the ship Aquilla. The Camanche is one of the first batch of monitors, and was built by SECOR & Co., under the superintendence of GEORGE BIRKBECK. Jr., at Jersey City. She was placed on board the ship Aquilla and sent around "the Horn," arriving at San Francisco on Nov. 11, 1863. On the 16th of November, 1863, during the prevalence of a very severe gale, the Aquilla sunk, having over[???] rode her anchor and stove a hole in her bottom, and both vessels sunk in about 40 feet of water. It was not long before the contractors set to work, and the pieces were removed from the bilged vessel and landed safe on shore. A year has elapsed (lacking two days) and the Camanche is completed and afloat, a floating monument of American enterprise and of the growing importance of our navy. The following are the prominent dimensions of the Camanche: Extreme length over armor, 200 feet; extreme length of boat proper on water line, 190 feet; length outside of stem and stern-posts, 159 feet; breadth of beam of boat proper, 37 feet 8 inches; depth of hold amidships, 11 feet 10 inches; crown of deck amidships, 5 inches; shear of deck, 12 inches; distance from stem to extreme end of boat, 10 feet 9 inches; distance from stem to extreme end of armor forward, 16 feet; distance from stern-post to extreme end of boat aft, 20 feet 3 inches; distance from stern-post to extreme end of armor aft, 23 feet. She has one turret and carries a battery of two improved 15-inch guns, and as a harbor defence she will be of great service to San Francisco. We now have our iron-clad navy represented in the Pacific Ocean, and there is no telling where we may be in this respect in the next quarter of a century. Though insignificant as this launch may seem to some persons, yet it marks with an indelible clearness the progress of our navy in the waters of the world. The builders and the country should be proud to near of the successful launch of the Camanche, the first iron-clad of the Pacific.

abstract: and Gov Brown; Mutual Abuse; and Jeff Davis--Mutual Abuse
snippet: and Gov Brown; Mutual Abuse; and Jeff Davis--Mutual Abuse
lead_paragraph: The perils which environ rebeldom are not producing unity of sentiment among its leaders. The message of JEFFERSON DAVIS, which he delivered to his Congress in Richmond a week ago to-day, is not the only evidence which has lately come to hand of the state of internal commotion in which the Southern Confederacy finds itself at present. We gave yesterday the message which Gov. BROWN, of Georgia, delivered to the Legislature of that State on the 3d inst.; and this, taken with the articles from the Georgia newspapers, shows a state of feeling which must be anything but strengthening to the Confederacy. JEFF. DAVIS, in his late visit to his army in Georgia, took occasion to apply some very extraordinary and indecent epithets to Gov. BROWN; and from the message of the latter it appears certain that there was no love lost between these leaders. BROWN does not like DAVIS policy any better than DAVIS likes BROWN's person, though it must be confessed that if the rebel Governor equals the rebel President in trenchancy of language, he by no means compares with him in vulgarity of personal abuse. BROWN upbraids DAVIS for his policy toward the people and States of the South, and for his policy toward the Government of the North. He accuses him of attempting to establish a military despotism over the Southern Confederacy; and accuses him with refusing to enter into negotiations for peace with the North. He declares himself satisfied that a "large majority of the people of Georgia disapprove many of the acts and much of the policy of the Confederate Administration." He pronounces Southern independence without State sovereignty and liberty, to be very little better than subjugation, as "it matters little who our master is, if we are to have one," and urges the rebel troops "never to consent to lay down their arms till these principles are recognized by our foe and faithfully carried out in practice by our own (the rebel) Government." He warns the Southern people "never under any circumstances to consent to accept a strong centralized Government with military despotism;" and immediately after this, with his eye fixed sternly upon JEFF. DAVIS, he says: "I do not see how it can be denied by any candid man that we have, in practice, made fearful strides, since the war began, toward a centralized Government with unlimited powers. The longer the war lasts, the greater the tendency to this result, and the less probability at its termination of a return to the constitutional forms and republican simplicity which existed at its commencement."

abstract: Navy, Difficulty in Manning
snippet: Navy, Difficulty in Manning
lead_paragraph: England finds herself in a new trouble; she has miles of wooden walls, but is scarce of seamen to man them. The thousands of men who were shipped for service in the Crimean war have left the Royal naval service, their terms of enlistment having expired; and it has been stated, by the best of authority, that not one-tenth part of these men can be induced to return and serve under their native flag and pennant. England has become alarmed; she finds her best seamen leaving their homes, seeking, first employment in our merchantmen, and next in our war vessels. Once here, these men are lost to the English navy forever. The leading army and navy organ, speaking on this subject says: "The question of how the British Royal navy is to be manned for the future is becoming daily of increasing importance, and there is at present difficulty of finding men for the Victoria and Achilles."

abstract: ALLEGED FRAUDS BY MEANS OF BOGUS CHECKS -- ARREST OF THE ACCUSED PARTY. -- A man named EDWARD A. MESSENGER was arrested on Saturday afternoon by Detective MCDOUGAL, on a charge of swindling by means of false checks. From the complaint made before Justice DOWLING yesterday, it appears that the accused went to the clothing store of Messrs. BROOKES, BROS. & CO., corner of Broadway end Grand-  street, and ordered a suit of clothes, which he directed to have sent to the Tammany Hotel. He subsequently countermanded these directions and ordered the goods sent to the Continental Hotel. This was done, and the porter of Messrs. BROOKES, BROS. & CO. received in payment for them a check on the Shoe and Leather Bank for $120, which proved to be worth nothing. Mr. WEYBOND, an attache of the store, complained against the accused, and he was taken into custody as above stated. It appears that Messrs. BROOKES, BROS. & CO. were not the only firms that has been visited by the prisoner, and it is said other charges will be preferred against him. Justice DOWLING committed him for examination.

abstract: Braine's Commission; Roanoke Capture; Braine's Commission
snippet: Braine's Commission; Roanoke Capture; Braine's Commission
lead_paragraph: The summary of the judicial proceedings at Bermuda, in the case of BRAINE and his fellow-pirates, which we publish, throws no additional light upon the circumstances under which the Roanoke was captured and burnt. We give the report chiefly for the purpose of showing the ready way in which the case was disposed of. All that BRAINE found it necessary to do, was to produce his so-called commission from S. R. MALLORY, "Secretary of the Navy of the Confederate States." That commission, the signature to which was, of course, easily vouched for by rebel sympathizers at Bermuda, appears to have designated BRAINE especially for the task of "capturing upon the high seas the Federal steam Roanoke, or the steamers Morning or Evening Star, all of which are on a line running between New- York and Havana." We presume that it is useless attempting to raise any question of the right of the Bermuda magistrates to grant the pirates a release under the circumstances -- admitting that BRAINE's commission was what it professed to be. It is, apparently, a settled part of British policy to accept such acts as the capture of the Chesapeake and the Roanoke as coming within the scope of fair belligerent rights. And from the policy thus declared by the British Foreign Office, the Colonial Courts naturally take their cue.

abstract: -We observe the honors which have been conferred in Boston upon Capt. WINSLOW, the hero of the Kearsarge and Alabama battle in the British Channel. Boston, however, though it contains many great men -- and though its greatest, such as Mr. EVERETT and Mr. DANA, honored themselves by honoring Capt. WINSLOW -- is yet a small place in which to give due honor to a man of such services and distinction. New-York is the commercial emporium of the Continent, the fountain of honor, the centre of things in general. Here are all the great ovations to greatness -- to foreign princes from England or Japan, to foreign and domestic heroes, from KOSSUTH to CORCORAN. Capt. WINSLOW should be invited to the Empire City. The Common Council should take the matter in hand. The Chamber of Commerce should see to it. We do not believe that even Mayor GUNTHER would object to jubilations on such an occasion, for Capt. WINSLOW's triumph was in foreign waters, and was more over a foreign than a domestic foe. Congress will soon meet, and will doubtless at once take steps to make the Captain an Admiral; but the people desire to show their appreciation even before that. The Kearsarge is to be laid up at Boston for some time for repairs, and as Capt. WINSLOW will have a respite from duty, there will be no time lost to him in being brought to New-York. We observe that in Boston they do not even know how to pronounce the name of his celebrated ship, one of the papers saying that the g is hard and that the word has three syllables, both of which statements are errors. In New-York the people know both how to call the ship, and honor its commander.

lead_paragraph: DARING HIGHWAY ROBBERY. -- About 12 o'clock on Friday night, as Mr. SAMUEL R. GLEND, of No. 200 South Fourth-street, E.D., was returning home, he was knocked down by three men, at the corner of South Fourth and Eighth streets, and robbed. The ruffians searched all of his pockets, and finding no money, took from his knife, silver pencil-case, ferry tickets, neck-tie, and other small articles, and then made their escape.

abstract: ATTEMPT TO BREAK JAIL. -- Several prisoners confined in the King's County Jail, on the charge of murder, made arrangements to break out of their quarters during election week, but were prevented by timely discovery of the plot. They had been provided with pistols, saws and chisels by friends who had been permitted to visit them. The pistols were found under the flagging of the cell, and the tools in the waste pipe. The prisoners were placed in separate cells as soon as their object was ascertained.

abstract: Trial of at Flatbush; Dictator; First Trial and Officers of
snippet: Trial of at Flatbush; Dictator; First Trial and Officers of
lead_paragraph: Improvements in firearms are now attracting a great deal of attention, both in this country and Europe, in consequence of the great impetus given to the matter by the civil war between the Northern and Southern States. Up to the present time the armies of the United States have held their own in the matter of heavy ordnance; but so far as rifles and other small arms are concerned, the South has had the advantage. The very best guns made in Europe, and more especially in England, have been put at their disposal, and while we have depended upon guns, good enough in themselves, but by no means equal to the necessity of the case or, the advancements of the age, they have been applying the very best war instruments that science has invented or brought to light. This fact becomes notorious through the evidence of all our campaigns, and is still being made painfully apparent by the great mortality among our officers, caused by the superior power of the arms in the hands of the rebel sharpshooters. It is well known that Col. BERDAN, a gentleman who for many years past has devoted his attention to the study of mechanics, and more than ever to the improvement and perfection of small arms -- was the first to form a regiment of sharpshooters in this city. He would accept no men for the service but those who were the most perfect marksmen. He had numerous trials and experiments with his regiment, and it was not until he was perfectly satisfied with their skill and ability that he offered it to the Government. They were accepted, and of the service they did against the rebellion let the history of the war speak to the world. Such a body of sharpshooters, we believe, was never before seen, and during the full three years of service through which they passed, they proved to the world that the American sharpshooter was the most precise and unfailing that was ever heard of before.

abstract: Serenade to, and Speech; Serenade to and Speech; Serenade to and Speech
snippet: Serenade to, and Speech; Serenade to and Speech; Serenade to and Speech
lead_paragraph: Last evening the Veteran Union Club of this city, composed entirely of men who have served in the Union army and have been honorably discharged, and who, during the past political campaign, fought as hard for the success of the Union ticket as they did for their country's flag when in the field. Serenaded Messrs. DARLING, DODGE and RAIMOND, the three candidates the club supported, and worked to elect to Congress. At about 9 1/2 o'clock the club formed in line, and preceded by the band the Ninth Regiment N.Y.S.N.G. had with them through their three years' campaign, marched up to the residence of Mr. DARLING, in Forty-first-street, near Fifth-avenue, here the club formed a semi-circle, the band in the centre. After the band had executed two pieces, Mr. DARLING made his appearance at the window, where he was received and introduced to the club by Dr. FISHER.[???]

abstract: MORE FERRY ACCOMMODATIONS. -- The Jersey City Ferry Company will place the new and beautiful ferry-boat Newark on the route some day this week. She is not quite as large as the New-York and other boats; but she will be fast and very commodious. She is 176 feet in length. Her hull was built under the superintendence of Capt. C.A. WOOLSEY, Superintendent of the company. The engines are by ZENO SECOR, superintended by GEORGE BIRKBECK, Jr. She has one forty-inch cylinder, and eleven feet stroke of piston. The internal fittings are neat and plain. She is strong, and well adapted for the service intended.

abstract: Financial Troubles; Trenholm and Taxation; Trenholm and Taxation
snippet: Financial Troubles; Trenholm and Taxation; Trenholm and Taxation
lead_paragraph: -- Any one who desires to compare the report of DAVIS' new Finance Minister with that of his War Secretary, will find each an instructive commentary on the other. Mr. TRENHOLM, presenting the exigencies of the Treasury as a subject of public and prayerful meditation, draws attention to the fact that soldiers, soldiers' families, and the poor generally, have been the heaviest sufferers by the tax on the currency, and its depreciation. To protect the soldiers and the poor from the effects of this depreciation in the value of Confederate promissory notes, the Secretary considers a sacred duty; but the desperate nature of his scheme for applying a remedy shows that, sacred as the duty may be, it is not one that is likely to be performed. Taking the tenth part of the farmer's cotton, wheat and corn, at a price less than one-seventh of that which these commodities now bring, and making good the exaction, by certificates of exemption from taxation, after the war, may not be exactly the last refuge of the Confederate shysters, but it is certainly a marvelous way of raising the wind. The simple and candid manner in which Mr. TRENHOLM acknowledges that the rebel soldiers are gouged, is certainly more to be admired than DAVIS' preposterous statement that he needs no more money till after the 1st of June 1865. And yet we think TRENHOLM might, in his candid humor, have been even more explicit than he was. The rebel soldier, if he gets all that is promised him, gets a fraction over five dollars a year in money which can be said to be current. Mr. TRENHOLM, therefore, draws no exaggerated picture of the misery entailed on the rank and file of the rebel army when he says that soldiers' families have been the heaviest sufferers by the depreciation of the currency.

abstract: Alien, Drafted by Rebels, case of
snippet: Alien, Drafted by Rebels, case of
lead_paragraph: The telegraph, last afternoon, brought the intelligence from Montreal that the case for the prosecution against the St. Alban's robbers has closed. "Lieutenant" YOUNG afterward handed in a statement, to the effect that he is "a commissioned officer in the Confederate service." He farther declared that the expedition was not projected in Canada, but the object was to retaliate for the acts committed by Gen. GRANT, by Gen. SHERIDAN and others, which acts were not in accordance with civilized warfare. Having thus solemnly declared, "Lieutenant" YOUNG handed in his commission from Mr. SEDDON, "Secretary of War of the Confederate States." But before proceeding with his defence, he asked to communicate with his Government at Richmond, in order to obtain important testimony, which could be had within the period of thirty days.

abstract: Savannah Republican on Foreign Element in our Armies; Savannah Republican on
snippet: Savannah Republican on Foreign Element in our Armies; Savannah Republican on
lead_paragraph: A late number of the savannah Republican, which lies before us, discusses the matter of "Yankee brag," and in the course of its lucubrations asserts that the Yankee armies are now composed of foreign levies that it is a notorious fact that a genuine Yankee is seldom to be found in the Yankee ranks that "the only battle fought with a genuine Yankee army was the first, on the plains of Manassas" -- that "on every other field we (the rebels) have met the world in arms -- Irish, Dutch, Italians, Swiss, and hireling hordes from every nation under the sun, whom Yankee trickery and lies could bribe and bring over to make war against us." "The Northern people," adds the Republican, "except those who could obtain a profitable office, have staid at home, and in their quiet way grown rich in preying upon the army and the public treasury. When the time comes for them to fight, we shall have a close of the war, for they have no idea of exposing their precious carcases to the peril of Southern bullets."

abstract: Appeal of
snippet: Appeal of
lead_paragraph: The appeal which is made through our advertising columns this morning, by members of the Sanitary Commission, is one which we feel assured will not fail, especially in view of the approaching Thanksgiving, to meet a prompt, a generous and a cordial response. The Commission has expended during the past six months over one and a half million dollars, mainly for supplies for our brave soldiers not otherwise attainable. If the Commission could have curtailed the outlay, without running the risk of disappointing the hopes of those who had previously relied upon its succor, it would have done so on grounds of financial prudence. But every cent of its outlay has been, as it were, a necessity. No other provision was made to meet the wants which it supplied. And our loyal citizens must be prepared to hear -- as we are sure they will hear with no sordid misgiving -- that the Commission must be reinforced to carry on its good work. Let us ask our readers to turn to the appeal of Dr. BELLOWS and his colleagues.

abstract: Mr. AUGUSTUS PURDY, Clerk of Arrears in the Finance Department, yesterday began a sale at the City Hall of city property in arrears for assessments for various city improvements. The arrears are for the years 1853, 1854 and 1855. The catalogue of property for sale has been much reduced -- probably quite one half -- since it was first advertised a few weeks ago, by the delinquent owners paying up the claims of the city. Each piece of property is sold for the least term of years for which the bidders will take it and pay the city's claims against it. The list to be sold originally comprised 1,118 lots, mostly improved property, of which 101 were disposed of yesterday, at terms of from 30 to 900 years. The sale will be continued from day to-day till the 25th inst. The sums of the claims of the city, including interest, run from $15 to $1,000.
