abstract: New-York; Barmore, Miss, Burned at Wedding Party
snippet: New-York; Barmore, Miss, Burned at Wedding Party
lead_paragraph: Last Thursday night, a wedding took place at the house of Mr. H. BARMORE, No. 196 West Fourteenth-street, which was attended by numerous guests, and among them Miss FRANCES GARRISON, of Paterson, N.J. Soon after the ceremonies were concluded, this young lady retired to her apartment on the fourth floor. In striking a match, a portion of the phosphorus fell upon her light gauze dress, setting it on fire. In great excitement she ran down four flights of stairs, and before assistance could reach her, she was enveloped in flames. She was burned so badly that she died from the effects of her injuries on the following afternoon. An inquest was held by Coroner RANNEY on the same day, but no report was made by him at the Coroner's office until yesterday (Monday) afternoon. No report of the case had been made by the police up to yesterday noon. Deceased was a very estimable young lady, beloved by all who knew her. She was 18 years of age, and a native of New Jersey, and was the niece and an adopted daughter of Mrs. ABRAM VAN BLARCOM, of Paterson, N.J.

abstract: -- On Saturday, about noon, a man called at No. -- Concord-st., Brooklyn, saying that a gentleman who boarded there had been run over by a stage in New-York and so seriously injured that he had been conveyed to the hospital, and that he had come for a change of linen and a coat to replace the clothes ruined by the accident. The lady of the house, suspecting that all was not right, questioned him closely, the man giving straightforward answers to every inquiry made and evincing an intimate knowledge of the gentleman, even giving the name of his cousin who roomed with him, and saying that he had been sent for. Deceived entirely by the representations of the man, the lady supplied the articles as requested, only discovering the swindle upon the return of the gentleman in the evening.

abstract: Speech at Veteran Union Club
snippet: Speech at Veteran Union Club
lead_paragraph: A meeting of the Veteran Union Club was held last evening at Headquarters, No. 243 Eighth-avenue, to celebrate the recent Union victories throughout the country. The hall at an early hour was filled by an audience of ladies and gentlemen, who manifested great enthusiasm during the entire proceedings. The meeting was called to order by the President, Mr. HUGH GARDENER, who introduced as the first speaker, THEODORE TILTON. Mr. TILTON delivered a very able address, in which he referred to the arrival of Gen. BUTLER in this city, and said that those who had predicted war and bloodshed had been sadly disappointed. No country in Europe was as safe in a time of peace as ours during a time of war. He believed that all should now clasp their hands together, and resolve to save our country. Some faces were shadowed while contemplating our taxes. It should be remembered that the people were taxing themselves. The Government must be supported, and although our debt was large one, cotton crop of the South would pay it. We should laugh at debt when the Lord has given us a continent. If JEFF. DAVIS is able to hold the reluctant State of Georgia in subjection, why should we not be able to hold every rebellious State in the Union. The speaker argued at some length the policy of abolishing the Electoral College with a view to a more direct representation of the will of the people. He referred to GARIBALDI as a patriot who did not at first believe the North to be in favor of the abolition of slavery. We should give such noble men to understand that we are determined to put down slavery. The above is but a brief outline of Mr. TILTON's remarks, which were frequently interrupted by applause. After a song by Mr. MATHEW, Mr. MCDOUGALL, CHAS. S. SPENCER, Esq. and Ex-Gov. NOBLE followed in short but eloquent addresses, when the meeting adjourned.

abstract: A committee composed of some of New-York's most distinguished citizens tendered to Gen. and Mrs. BUTLER a public reception at the Fifth-avenue Hotel last night. A large number of invitations were given out, and the fortunate holders of tickets crowded the hotel at an early hour. At 8 o'clock the band struck up "Hail to the Chief," and the distinguished guests made their appearance. Gen. BUTLER, escorted by the Committee; Mrs. BUTLER, leaning on the arm of Gen. WETMORE and Miss BUTLER, accompanied by Hon. GEORGE OPDYKE, entered the main parlor of the hotel and took their stand between the windows. The General was followed by Brig.-Gen. Gordon, Col. Sewel, Col. Darling, Capt. Clarke, Capt. Puffer, Capt. Schaeffer, and others of his staff.

abstract: The London Morning Post says: "According to accounts from the Continent, the idea of an European Congress is again on the tapis. The principal object is stated to be the question of Rome and Italy. France, Russia and Prussia are stated as having agreed upon the subject. The Emperor NAPOLEON calculates on the adhesion of Italy and King LEOPOLD of Belgium. It is reported he has nearly overcome the objections of England and Austria. Should all this be accomplished, a general disarmament will, it is said, be the result of the Congress, and thus secure the peace of Europe."

abstract: The Manchester Guardian says: -- "A few weeks ago we noticed the departure from Liverpool of a steamer called the Laurel with about 100 men on board, many of whom had served with Capt. SEMMES. It was also hinted that Capt. SEMMES was himself on board. This news is confirmed by a dispatch received in Liverpool from Madeira, to the effect that the Laurel had been lying in Funchal Bay previous to the 17th. and early on the morning of that day she steamed out to sea and met a large screw steamer (understood to be the new Alabama,) on board of which were transferred the crew of the Laurel and cargo, consisting of guns, ammunition, &c. The screw steamer then made for the direction of Bermuba."

abstract: Children's Aid Society and Paris Assistance Publique; on the Poor of Paris; Relief of, in Paris and New-York. (Jerrold.); Paris; The Poor of, by Blanchard Jerrold
snippet: Children's Aid Society and Paris Assistance Publique; on the Poor of Paris; Relief of, in Paris and New-York. (Jerrold.); Paris; The Poor of, by Blanchard Jerrold
lead_paragraph: At the last meeting of the Social Science Congress at York (Eng.), Mr. BLANCHARD JERROLD presented a paper containing observations on some of the plans adopted for the relief of the poor of Paris. He briefly sketched the origin and gradual development of the administration of the Assistance Publique, and showed how, from 1801 down to the present time, improvement had been going on in the manner of administering relief to the poor of the French metropolis. After an interesting description of this system, Mr. JERROLD pointed out that the French system of treating and providing for neglected orphan and deserted children is in all respects unlike the English. The English brigade the little helpless ones, while the Paris Governors of the Poor scatter their proteges far and wide, in the homes of honest, well-conducted working-men. One admirable point in the regulations of the Assistance Publique is that it takes care of the children of poor people, who are laid up in the hospital or committed to prison. If so much is not given in money in Paris as in London, the numbers who are willing to give time and trouble to the poor are greater in Paris. Having dwelt with much emphasis upon the many peculiar and happy phases of French charity, Mr. JERROLD went on to say that the cherishing of home influence, as the best with which poor children can be surrounded, is the main feature of all Paris charities that deal with the young. He believed that the most good could be accomplished if a few among London philanthropists would establish an orphan society, that would possess not one brick in the way of asylum, but that should create a thousand new homes over the country for a thousand of the little Arabs of the streets. He put it as a question of "drill under a Gothic roof, with a number for a name, or of a new home in a wayside cottage, and farm labor in the fields."

abstract: A very elegant entertainment was given to Archbishop McCLOSKEY, on Monday evening last, at Deimonico's, by CHARLES O'CONOR, Esq. The company numbered about a hundred persons, all Catholics, and embracing some of the most distinguished of our citizens. Judge DALY represented the Bench, JAMES T.BEADY the Bar, JAMES GORDON BENNETT the Press, and Dr.BEDFORD the medical profession, while there were also present several of the clergy and a large number of the representatives of foreign countries. The Archbishop responded to a complimentary toast in brief and appropriate terms -- recognizing the great responsibility of the office he had been called to fill, and the influence exerted upon the whole country by the moral and religious tone of the City of New-York. The occasion was one of marked interest.

abstract: It is pleasant to know that even in case a new call for troops should be made, there is little danger that this city will be subjected to another draft, and that this exemption will not be secured by defrauding the armies of the Union of the services of the New-York soldiers. The Chairman of the Volunteer Committee is actively engaged in the work of enlisting men to the credit of this city; and he states that volunteers and substitutes can be procured in almost any number, and as fast as they can be examined and mustered in. The average number enlisted every day is forty; it sometimes reaches a much higher figure. A large proportion of the number are representative substitutes. Mr. BLUNT says he has no difficulty in filling applications of this character, and those of our citizens whose business or whose age renders it impossible for them to enter the military service of their country in person, can secure a representative to go in their place, by entering their names in Mr. BLUNT's book and planking down the sum of $220, $430 or $550, which will procure a substitute for two, three or four years. Mr. BLUNT follows the good old democratic rule, "First come, first served;" he takes upon himself the trouble of securing the substitute, and as fast as they are mustered in, they are credited to those who have paid the required sum, checking off the names in the order in which he finds them on his books.

The average number enlisted every day is forty; it sometimes reaches a much higher figure. A large proportion of the number are representative substitutes. Mr. BLUNT says he has no difficulty in filling applications of this character, and those of our citizens whose business or whose age renders it impossible for them to enter the military service of their country in person, can secure a representative to go in their place, by entering their names in Mr. BLUNT's book and planking down the sum of $220, $430 or $550, which will procure a substitute for two, three or four years. Mr. BLUNT follows the good old democratic rule, "First come, first served;" he takes upon himself the trouble of securing the substitute, and as fast as they are mustered in, they are credited to those who have paid the required sum, checking off the names in the order in which he finds them on his books.

abstract: Florida-Brazil Piracy; Law of; Neutrals and Captures at Sea; Florida Case
snippet: Florida-Brazil Piracy; Law of; Neutrals and Captures at Sea; Florida Case
lead_paragraph: There seems to be an impression abroad that the fact of the Florida having burned her prizes at sea, has, or may have, some legal bearing on the position with regard to her seizure at Bahia, which the Brazilian Government will assume. As the American public will doubtless shortly be called on to approve or disapprove of the course pursued by our Government in the matter, it is of the highest importance that there should not be, as there was in the Trent affair, any general misunderstanding as to the law of the matter. It is, therefore, well to say, that the popular impression that a belligerent is under a legal obligation to bring enemy's ships, when captured, before a prize court for condemnation, has, we believe, no foundation either in the books or in usage. Prize courts are instituted for the benefit of neutrals, and the liability of a neutral ship to capture is the question, and the only question, which a belligerent is in any case bound to submit to them. A cruiser is not obliged, by international law, to bring in an enemy's ship for condemnation, unless the ownership is in doubt. If this is the case, her duty is either to submit the point to a prize court, or dismiss the prize. If there is no doubt about it; it the fact that the prize is enemy's property is established beyond question on her capture, either by her papers, or her Master's admission, her destruction on the spot is perfectly justifiable. Moreover, this has been the practice of belligerents in all wars, whenever it was inconvenient for the captor to send his prize into port.

abstract: The steamship Australasian, from Liverpool NOV. 5, and Queenstown Nov. 6, arrived at this port at 1 o'clock, this morning. Her advices are two days later than those previously received. One item of news is especially important. The Manchester Guardian announces that the confirmation of the report that the steamer Laurel, which recently sailed from Liverpool with a cargo of arms and ammunition, and a number of SEMMES' men, did actually transfer her cargo to a large new steamer, called the New Alabama, in the bay of Funchal, Madeira, and that the said new steamer then stood off toward Bermuda. The report is also confirmed by a dispatch from Madeira to Liverpool.

abstract: Franklin vs Administrators Robert T Haws
snippet: Franklin vs Administrators Robert T Haws
lead_paragraph: George H. Franklin vs. James H. Pinkney et al., Administrators of Robert T. Haws, deceased. -- The plaintiff was a friend of the late Robert T. Haws, while the latter was Comptroller of this city, in 1860-1862, and held the office of Collector of City Revenue, having an office in the same building with deceased. Franklin, as alleged, kept no bank account of his own, but was in the habit of depositing his surplus moneys with Haws, by placing them in the Tradesmen's Bank, with Haws' assent, to the credit of Haws. Haws died suddenly, intestate, having, as claimed, in his hands, a considerable sum belonging to Franklin. His administrators having declined payment of the claim, this suit was brought.

lead_paragraph: The Tulip, one of the Potomac flotilla, which exploded her boller on Friday last, in the Potomac River, was a small screw vessel, of 183 tons. and was built at Brooklyn by JEWETT & Co., in 1863, with two other vessels the Diaching and Fuschia, for the Chinese navy, then under the young American-Chinaman WARD, who was killed before these vessels were paid for. The funds for them not being sent out, the contractors sold them to the Navy Department. The Tulip and Fuschia were sent to the Potomac flotilla just after the July riots of last year, they having been employed, at the time in guarding the harbor, the tulip's guns at one time being trained to sweep Wall-street If an attack was made upon the Custom-house or Assay Office. The Navy Register for 1864 gives her the following list of officers: Acting En??? S.G.Stuvtet, U. Stevens, Acting Master's Mates -- J. Reffenterg. C.H. McClellan. Engineers -- Acting Third Assistants, G.F. Parks, H.P. Gray, John Gordon.

abstract: Mr. W.H. FRY, the composer and critic, leaves to-day for St. Thomas by the steamer Emily S. Soudr, from Pier No. 13, North River, at 10 A.M. Mr. FRY's health has been in a precarious condition for several vears. During the Presidential campaign in 1860 he exerted himself with a will that was too great for his strength. A fluent, witty and powerful speaker, be overtaxed the capacity of an organisation that was always more mental than physical. His lungs became affected by too much work of this sort, and it is to repair them that he now goes to the friendly climate of the West Indies. We trust that his most sanguine hopes will be more than realized. Mr. FRY's griet, it will be perceived, comes from politics, His happiness, we are sure, has always been in music. Be is unquestionably the most prominent musician that America has yet produced. Two operas from his pen are known to the public -- "Leonora" and " Notre Dame de Paris" -- both of which were eminently successful. As a critic he leaves a void that cannot easily be filled. His style was trenchant, bis observation rapid and correct, his language peculiar but happy, and his manner always that of a gentleman. It is to be hoped that Mr. FRY's recovery may be rapid and permanent, and that he will shortly return to us again to grace a position Which be has made honorable by Kindly wisdom, ???enial advice, strict impartiality and a complete devotion to art.

abstract: ACADEMY OF MUSIC. -- DONIZETTI's ope??? ??? Linda de Chamounix," was given here last night with good success. Miss KELLOGG was the heroine and interpreted her rble with the clear musical delicacy and intelligence which characterize her every performance. Mere voice does not make an artist, although it is regarded as nine points of what is required to make one; cultivation too -- like all dry scientific details -- frequently runs short. What art requires is a temperament that is thoroughly responsive; that has the ability to execute and the power to conceive. Miss KELLOGG possesses this tempera-ment in a more eminent degree than any other American prima donna on the stage, and her performances are, in consequence, always important and interesting. Her Linda has from the first ranked as one of the best characters of her repertoire. We have seldom heard it better rendered than last night. From the opening cavatina, (which obtained an encore.) to the last dazed reminiscence of early joy, she was admirable. It is a pleasure to record a success that was as unequivocal as it was merited.

abstract: -- A mass meeting of this fine corps was held last evening at the Mercer House, corner of Mercer and Broome streets. The object of the meeting was to organize the New-York State National Guards. The old charter of those in the field has been renowed under the gallant Col. S.M. ELLIOTT, whose devotion with the old seventy-ninth (Scotch) is too well known to require explanation, his purse being ever ready to afford them the comforts they so much needed. The headquarters will be the Mercer House, as formerly.

abstract: Major-General BUTLER left this city at eight o'clock yesterday morning and proceeded to Washington, his staff accompanying him as far as Baltimore. His departure was almost as sudden and un expected as his arrival, but his work here was done and his presence was required in the field. A correct estimate of the importance of the late movement for the protection of the City of New-York cannot be formed without the knowledge of details which the Government at present wisely withholds. The information which led to such energetic action was ample and reliable. A few days before the election the Secretary of War was informed that a secret organization existed in the State of New-York whose avowed object was to accomplish the defeat of the Union ticket by force, if necessary. They had purchased arms in large quantities, and had held secret meetings for the purpose of drill. They had perfected a plan for raising an ???; they were prepared to furnish the mob with implements of war, and to lead them in the struggle. They were as certainly rebels at heart and in intent as the hordes of Las or the murdering bands of MOSBY. Taking this definite information in connection with the known fact that the City of New-York contains to-day fifteen thousand Southern rebels, too slothful and cowardly to brave the dangers and fatigue of the battle-field, but vindictive and revengeful enough to pay the hire of incendiaries and assassins, the Government did not feel justified in neglectlng the warning. The opposition press have universally ascribed the riots of July to the absence of all military forces from the city. That riot cost the City of New-York twelve hundred lives and millions of dollars; it is a sore that cannot be cured. The Government decided this time to apply the "ounce of prevention." On the 3d of November, Gen. BUTLER received an order directing him to proceed to New-York and take command of such troops as might be ordered to report to him there. In twelve hours the General was here, and had established his headquarters at the Hoffman House. In forty-eight hours a provisioned army corps was transferred from the banks of the James to the Hudson. It was an organized army in every respect, complete, with the proper proportion of cavalry and artillery, and composed of veteran troops selected for special service. That portion Intended for service in this city, was temporarlly encamped on Staten Island and at Fort Hamilton. Gen. BUTLER then devoted the days intervening before election to making h imself acquainted with the city, with its police arrangements, and with the means at hand to preserve order. Maps were studied, the Superintendent and Commissioners of police were consulted, and plans perfected. Telegraphic communication was established between his headquarters and every part of the city. Trustworthy commissioned officers were detailed to remain at each police station-house, and a special bureau of information organised. An engineer department was created, and a system of barricades agreed upon by which a riot might be confined to the part of the city in which it first broke out. But one chief point was never lost sight of. It was necessary that no excuse should be offered to the enemies of the Government for raising the cry of " armed interference with the freedom of the ballot-box." This part of the movement was executed in a signally successful manner. On the morning of the 8th of November, the City of New-York was surrounded by a cordon of soldlers in arms, yet not an armed man was visible. Horses were harnessed to the guns, and flying artillery could have been whirled through the streets to any point at a moment's notice, yet no one saw them or knew where they were located. It was this mysterious presence of a force felt but not seen that so awed the Southern rebels in New-York that, to use the language of the General himself in answer to a question as to future disturbances, "Truth crushed to earth may rise again, but they never will." The troops maintained their stations until Friday night, when they all returned to their camps on Staten Island, and yesterday the last company of them left the harbor of New-York on their way to the James, and thus ended the movement on the part of the Government for the protection of New-York from the horrors of riot and bloodshed.

lead_paragraph: The first annual term of the Columbia College School of Mines commenced yesterday, and the organization of classes was perfected. The building used by the school is the easterly wing of the college, situated on the corner of Fourth-avenue and Forty-ninth-street. Several these schools are in successful operation in Europe, but this is believed to be the first and only institution of the kind in the United States.

abstract: On the Elections and the War; on the Election, the War and an Amnesty
snippet: On the Elections and the War; on the Election, the War and an Amnesty
lead_paragraph: The citizens of New-york have done me honor over much. Their kindness, extended in every form known to christian courtesy, overwhelms me. That I should be able to add anything to the sum of Intelligence is a still greater honor. That I entertain very distinct views upon the subjects to which you have adverted is most true. Peace hath her victories no less renowned than war; and of all the peaceful victories ever yet achieved in the interests of human freedom that achieved in the peaceful quiet which a most brooded over this land on the 8th of November, was the greatest. Before we proceed for a moment to took at the material results, let us look at the moral. It has taught the world who shall look on, and it can now be said that it is no vain boast to America that the eyes of the world are upon her it has told all the world that we are able in the airess and strain of civil warlike that never seen before, to carry our institutions in peaceful quiet, reelect our rulers as we weigh them in the balance to find them either meritorious or wantings, without so much of trouble or disorder or riot, or of commotion, as attends. a constable's selection in a narish in England.

abstract: Railway Accidents
snippet: Railway Accidents
lead_paragraph: The number of railway accidents of a fatal character, which have recently occurred, begins to alarm the public. During the past month we have had them at the rate of about three a week. The list is headed by the accident on the Harlem Road, which occurred in the heart of the City of New-York on the 10th of October. The train which was then amashed up contained, a large number of soldiers. The train which, five days later, ran off the track on the Shore Line Road, also had soldiers on board -- two hundred and seventy-five sick and wounded. The fearful collision on the Lafayette and Indianapolis Railroad on the 1st inst., was marked by the same coincidence. Soldiers and members of the Sanitary Commission were on board. Two accidents on the Baltimore and Philadelphia Road, on the day of the Presidential election, were similarly distinguished by the live freight they carried. We do not presume to say that there was any rebel plot or conspiracy in these cases. But the coincidence is noteworthy. Half a score of such disasters inside of a period of less than thirty days is too much to make railroad travel an agreeable recreation.

abstract: Aid Societies, Convention of
snippet: Aid Societies, Convention of
lead_paragraph: The Soldiers' Aid Societies of this and the adjoining States, which have now for three years acted as the feeders of the Sanitary Commission, collecting and forwarding from all parts of the country most of the supplies and much of the money which that body has distributed to the soldiers, are sending delegates to a convention which is to meet this evening in the hall of the Cooper Institute. The object of the meeting is the interchange of opinions and information, by those who have, since the outbreak of the war, been foremost in the great work of charity which has been productive of so much comfort to the army, and has reflected so much honor on the country. Addresses will be delivered by the leading members and agents of the commission, Dr. BELLOWS, Dr. AGNEW, Mr. F.N. KNAPP, and others, descriptive of its operations during the past Summer over its vast field of labor, as well as of the nature and extent of the organizations in aid of it which Dr. BELLOWS has seen or established in California.

abstract: Speech on Amnesty or Subjugation
snippet: Speech on Amnesty or Subjugation
lead_paragraph: Gen. BUTLER's remarks at the Fifth-avenue Hotel on Monday evening will attract attention, -- not only on account of the quarter from whence they come, but from the nature of the suggestions which they make. The General sees in the result of the Presidential election, what all the world will recognize, a declaration, made with overwhelming unanimity by the American people, that this rebellion must be put down by force, so long as it remains in arms against the Government. To this the whole country now stands pledged, -- and neither Southern rebels nor their sympathizers abroad or at home, can any longer cherish doubts, or be misled by illusions on that subject. Gen. BUTLER thinks the present, therefore, a good time to make a full and formal tender of the olive branch, -- inviting all who are now in rebellion to cease fighting, and return to the Union, and promising all, leaders as well as followers, full and complete amnesty for their crimes. He urges that practical wisdom would suggest such a course, and that we are now strong enough in every respect, moral and material, to afford it. The General suggests further that some day be fixed as the limit of this offer, and that if be not accepted within that time, the war be then prosecuted openly and avowedly for the subjugation of the rebels and the confiscation of their lands to the soldiers of our armies. He vindicates the essential justice of this proposition by historical precedents, and presses it as the surest means of bringing the war to a successful close.

abstract: Speech at Nashville; Aristocracy of Labor
snippet: Speech at Nashville; Aristocracy of Labor
lead_paragraph: A flag-raising at an army depot in Nashville, last week, called out a large crowd, who called upon Governor JOHNSON for a speech. After complimenting Col.CRANE, the host of the occasion, for the ability and efficiency with which his department was administered, he spoke of the aristocracy of Nashville. They had ever been, and were to-day, rebels at heart, and in deed also, when they dared do anything for the rebel cause, He knew thereef he affirmed. They had misrepresented and villfied him because he had been true to the Union. Copperhead papers and speakers at the North had charged him with selfish motives in the course he had pursued. If losing all his negroes, if being robbed of $40,000 in bonds, if sacrificing all that he had to sacrifice, was selfishness, then he had been selfish. But the Government had been sustained in all its integrity, and he was more than recompensed. He had always been a Democrat, but in true sense. True Democracy meant the elevation of the masses. He was a Democrat, but at the same time an aristocrat; but his aristocracy was the aristocracy of labor, the men whose, brains and muscles had planned and wronght out those great achievement that had made the laboring classes of America the true chivalry of the world. The men who sneered at "greasy mecha???ics' and "small-fisted farmers" as the mud???s of society." were the very men who had not brains to conceive or ability to execute a plan. Labor was dignity, dignity is manhood, and manhood was aristocracy. Society was to-day in a chaotic state. The time had come to lay broad and deep the foundation of the new aristocracy, and by the blessings of God and the will of the laboring men it was to be cone.

abstract: The Board of Supervisors, as County Canvassers, met and organized at noon yesterday, to canvass the returns of the late election. Mr. TWEED was chosen Chairman. The returns of the Fourth, Sixth, Seventh and Thirteenth Wards, were canvassed, except of one district in each that were sent back for corrections of minor errors. The Board decided to meet daily at 12 M., and to adjourn at 4 P.M.; to defer all disputed points till the last day of the session (the usual practice,) and that all "scattering" returns must be sent back for a detailed statement of their nature.

abstract: THE PRODUCE EXCHANGE ENLARGEMENT. -- On Thursday next, Nov. 17, the Produce Exchange enlargement will be formally opened for business purposes. In addition to the floor heretofore used by the merchants, the entire of the first floor has been converted into a single spacious room, elaborately decorated, and provided with desks, tables, telegraph offices, and every other requisite of a first-class business centre. The walls and ceilings have been exquisitely frescoed, making the room extremely attractive. The wood-work is of the richest order, all in black walnut, and presents an appearance of solidity, in harmony with the substantial interests represented by the dense crowd of merchants who daily assemble at the Exchange. With this enlargement, and the improvements introduced into it, the Produce Exchange will afford every essential facility for the transaction of business on the most extensive scale.

abstract: Young Allowed to Send for Evidence to Richmond
snippet: Young Allowed to Send for Evidence to Richmond
lead_paragraph: THE ST. ALBAN's BRIGANDS. -- The telegraph brings the intelligence from Montreal that Judge COURSOL has granted the application of the brigand YOUNG's counsel, to, be permitted to send to Richmond for evidence of his official status. This, we confess, is not altogether unexpected intelligence. And yet we doubt whether the court will not find, that in giving this decision, it is opening up new complications, in the affair, foreign altogether to the issue presented to it. If YOUNG's commission is to determine the belligerent character of the prisoners, that commission will neither be confirmed nor invalidated by any evidence taken in Richmond -- even if the prisoners' counsel find the means of communicating with that city. Judge COURSOL, at least, must have been aware that neither YOUNG nor YOUNG's agents have any certain means of getting the required evidence within a month, or even within six months. It is, in fact, simply trifling with the matter to issue this commission for proving YOUNG to be what he claims. It would be quite as satisfactory to accept the status of the prisoners as proven, and if their case really does not come within the Extradition Treaty, punish them where they are for a violation of the neutrality laws.

abstract: and Peru
snippet: and Peru
lead_paragraph: SPAIN AND PERU. -- If we are to believe the London Morning Post, a special ambassador left Madrid for Peru on the 4th of November. He is the bearer of an ultimatum to the Peruvian Government, which threatens to destroy their fleet and seal up their harbors, unless they give full and complete satisfaction for the outrages alleged to have been committed against Spanish citizens. Threats quite as alarming as this have been made in the same quarter before, and nothing very serious has come of them. But it behooves the Republics of South America, nevertheless, to combine for any emergency that may arise, if they wish to preserve even the semblance, of an independent existence.

The gentleman who sent us the protest of "Five Hundred Indignant Ladies," at their treatment at the Cooper Institute meeting of Friday last, has sent us a reply to the note from "A.H.G.," published yesterday. abstract: Speech on Amnesty--The True Method; then Vigorous War; Subjugation of South not Sought by North
snippet: Speech on Amnesty--The True Method; then Vigorous War; Subjugation of South not Sought by North
lead_paragraph: Gen. BUTLER struck exactly the right key in his speech, in favoring a final and most liberal offer of amnesty to the rebels, and in the event of its rejection the most crushing warfare possible. All we can in the way of peace first, then, if that does not avail, all we can in the way of war -- that is unquestionably the true policy, dictated alike by humanity, justice and public expediency. The ship of state after this election is like the storm-beset ship at sea, whose staunchness has been thoroughly tested, and which now only waits but for a new reckoning to make port speedily, either in this direction or in that.

abstract: ACADEMY OF MUSIC. -- A brilliant audience assembled last evening to hear "Don Giovanni," but that work was not performed. Signor BELLINI was too indisposed to sustain the rols of the hero, and such is the morality of New-York, that it was impossible to find another Don Giovanni in it. A change of opera consequently had to take place. "Lucrezia Borgia" was performed instead, and received with favor.

abstract: Enlistments; Progress of
snippet: Enlistments; Progress of
lead_paragraph: The City of New-York set an example of sobriety and order on the day of the Presidential election. She is setting an equally good example every day in vigorously recruiting for the national army, so that she may anticipate whatever additional call for troops it may at any time be found expedient to make. There is no lack of volunteers, and the chief business is to see that the recruits that present themselves are of the right class; that they get their proper bounty money, and that those citizens who have first applied for representatives in the army are first served. The present rate of enlistment averages about two hundred and fifty a week. But if it were necessary to hurry the business, the number could be doubled.

abstract: The rebels have lately tried their hand at a rather sharp game upon our picket-line, near the Appomattox, where they threw a dam across a small stream that runs in front of our works, hoping to force back our line. On Sunday night, Gen. EGAN, while personally superintending the erection of works to prevent the rebels from carrying out this plan, was dangerously wounded in the wrist by a sharp-shooter. Fighting between the pickets was going on, at latest accounts, without important results to either side.

abstract: Bank of Commerce, >amp;c; Great Forgeries on
snippet: Bank of Commerce, >amp;c; Great Forgeries on
lead_paragraph: One of the most extensive and successful series of forgeries which have been perpetrated in this country for several years, was partially developed yesterday afternoon, before Justice DOWLING, at the Tomba Police Court. Only one complaint has as yet been made. This involves the sum of $25,127,50. The forgery consists in signing the name of Mr. RICHARD D. LATHROP, senior member of the wellknown dry goods firm of LATHROP, LUDINGTON & Co., Nos. 23 and 25 Park-place, to a check on the Mechasics' Bank, of this city. The money on this check, which purported to have been certified, was drawn from the Bank of Commerce. The fraud was not discovered until some time after the crime was perpetrated.

abstract: The story of forgeries in this city, brought to light yesterday, in the Tombs Police Court, promises, when it is fully told, to prove one of the most astounding in the history of crime. One case, involving $25,000, was yesterday gone into at some length, and a gang of ten ruffians, including some notorious burglars and counterfeiters, have already been secured. But this sum, large as it is, is supposed to be a mere fraction of the amount that will yet be shown to have been raised by the forgers on different banks. Some of those who profess to be informed on the subject, estimate the gross forgeries which this first case will bring to light, at from $300,000 to $500,000. And if the facilities for getting checks cashed at our banks are as great in every case as they appear to have been in that trial yesterday, we can readily believe the future disclosures may turn out to be fearful. It is premature now to comment upon the details which we publish this morning. But it is not premature to ask business men at once to look to their bank accounts. It is not premature to call for redoubled vigilance, if possible, on the part of the police. The city is evidently overrun with organized bands of plunderers, who arrange and perfect their plans for robbing the community on a scale of unprecedented magnitude.

abstract: -- Intelligence has been received in New-Haven of the death, by yellow fever, a few weeks since, of THEODORE WOOLSEY TWINING, Acting-Assistant-Paymaster on the United States bark Roebuck, which was stationed at the time at Tampa Bay, Fla. Mr. TWINING was born at West Point, Sept. 4, 1825, and was a son of Mr. A.C. TWINING, formerly a Professor in the United States Military Academy. In consequence of his father's subsequent connection with Middlebury College, Vermont, he spent his earlier years in that place. Subsequently the family removed to New-Haven, and young TWINING graduated at Yale College in 1858. He spent two years after graduation in miscellaneous pursuits, and in 1860 entered the Law School at New-Haven. After completing his course of study there, he was admitted to the Bar in 1862, but, instead of taking up the practice of his profession, he felt it to be his duty to enter the service of his country, and he therefore enlisted in the New-York Thirty-seventh Regiment, and served with it during a part of the time of its encampment at Baltimore. Subsequently, he received the appointment of Acting Assistant-Paymaster in the navy, and for nearly twelve months served on the United States ship Kensington, whence he was transferred to the bark Roebuck, on board of which he died.

lead_paragraph: THE NEW-YORK SEMI-WEEKLY TIMES is published THIS MORNING, and may be had at the counter of the publication office in wrappers ready for mailing. Price FIVE CENTS. In addition to the latest intelligence by telegraph up to the moment of going to press, there will be found in the current number full details of all military movements in the different departments from the pens of our special correspondents. Also, all official orders, reports and documents, and the latest and fullest Washington news, European news, with graphic letters from our correspondents in London and Paris, giving the tone of public feeling abroad, is made a special and permanent feature. In addition to Editorials on all the current topics of the day, the SEMI-WEEKLY TIMES has a page of carefully prepared commercial matter, giving the latest financial news and market reports: items of agricultural and domestic interest, complied from sources many of which are otherwise inaccessible to the American reader: and marriages and deaths of the week.

abstract: How he Stands the Test; his Popularity
snippet: How he Stands the Test; his Popularity
lead_paragraph: We envy not the feelings of any of the maligners of Mr. LINCOLN, whose eyes fell upon that noble passage concerning the President, in the speech of EDWARD EVERETT, published by us yesterday. It may be safely said that no person in the country is better qualified to pronounce an intelligent and impartial judgment upon our public men than this retired statesman. His long and varied official life in other days, brought him into immediate personal contact with all the leading public characters both of this country and of England during the last generation. He has long since thoroughly learned the stuff of which public men are made. When such experience is associated with a philosophic judgment, a refined taste, a fidelity to truth, and a devoted patriotism, such as belong to Mr. EVERETT, surely his decided testimony to the intellectual capacity of the President, to his purity of purpose and magnanimity of spirit, ought to bring shame, if anything could, to all the little carpers and defamers.

lead_paragraph: A HORTICULTURAL CONVENTION. -- A Convention of Fruit Cultivators and others will be held at Iona Island, the residence of Dr. C.W. GRANT, the celebrated grape-grower, near Peeksvill, on the 22d and 23d inst. A number of distinguished speakers and well-known horticulturists have accepted invitations to be present and address the Convention, such as the Rev. Henry Ward Beecher, Donald G. Mitchel, Horace Greeley, Dr. Loring, Dr. Noyes, P. Barry, Dr. Ward, Prof. Huntsman, Dr. Trimble, R.G. Pardee, P.B. Mead, and others. Win. C. Bryant, Esq., is expected to preside. There will be present on the occasion some of our most eminent ??? who will take part in the discussions and thus give them a great practical value. A committee has been appointed to make all needful arrangements. The proceedings will occupy the afternoon and evening of the 22d, and part of the 23d, lona Island is nearly opposite Peekskill, on the Hudson River. The principal trains arrive at Peekskill at 9 A.M. and 12 M., at which time boats will be at the dock to convey passengers to and from the Island, without charge.

lead_paragraph: We have been in possession, for some time past, of highly interesting and important information derived from Havana, in regard to a proposed rebel plan for capturing American passenger steamers upon the Pacific ocean. Hitherto we have retrained from giving the facts publicity, lest a premature announcement should tend to defeat measures that had been taken to frustrate the plot, and arrest the parties thereto. Now that any danger of that sort is over, we are at liberty to show how narrowly we have escaped the necessity of recording another Roanoke affair, only on a larger scale, upon the waters of the Pacific.

abstract: Mysterious Georgia Campaign
snippet: Mysterious Georgia Campaign
lead_paragraph: The spectacle which is now presented to the imaginations of the Northern people, of Gen. SHERMAN's legions plunging off into the darkness of an enemy's territory, burning their shelter behind them, as CORTEZ his ships, never to be heard of more till the enemy reports to us victory or disaster, is certainly something dramatic and exciting. To march a body of from 50,000 to 75,000 men, as a "flying column," for 300 miles, without connection to its base, and living, in great part, on the country, would, it successful, be the most remarkable military achievement of the war. In fact, we do not recall a march which can be compared with it, in modern military history. Rumor has it, that ten days' provision are to be carried on the back, and twenty days' in a compact wagon-train, and that construction trains and pontoon trains are to accompany the army, with a heavy mass of artillery.

abstract: Submission of Minority Opposed to Rebel Spirit; Historian, on Submission of Minorities
snippet: Submission of Minority Opposed to Rebel Spirit; Historian, on Submission of Minorities
lead_paragraph: A great deal has been said about the sublimity of an orderly popular election in the midst of such a terrible civil strife as is now raging. It truly was a grand exemplification of the vigor of the republican principle. But what is grander yet, is the cheerful submission universally manifested in the result of that election. It might be said by the enemies of our institutions, that the peaceful course of the canvass was owing to the expectation of each party that the result would be in its favor -- that so long as there was a belief by each that success would come to it without disorder, there could be no object in disorder. But no such pretext can be used to detract from the moral worth of this universal acquiescence in the result actually consummated and settled. This acquiescence stands out before the world in unimpeachable majesty. For two months before the election, political excitement raged almost like a tempest. Issues of the most tremendous magnitude were opposed, which the great body of both parties honestly believed involved the very fate of the country. Every motive and passion that can rouse human nature to intensity of action, were in full play. A spectator from abroad would have imagined that all this fierce stir must end in some dreadful convulsion. And yet here we all are as tranquil as if it all passed a hundred years ago. Not the slightest ruffle of opposition is anywhere visible.

abstract: In the Matter of the Habeas Corpus on Application of William Martin for the Custody of his Children. -- This was an application to obtain the custody of three young children, pending the result of a divorce suit instituted by Mary Martin against William Martin. On return to the writ, Mrs. Martin set forth that her husband was not the proper party to have charge of such young children, all of them being under five years of age. William Martin traversed this return by alleging that his wife was not the person to take care of them; that she had no means of supporting them, and that she was dependent on others. The Court ordered testimony to be taken in the case, with a view of ascertaining who were the fittest to have the children.

lead_paragraph: Some time since Mr. JAMES O'MALLEY, an artist of this city, completed a large and very excellent portrait of the late Archbishop HUGHES, which he valued at $1,000; the price being rather high, no purchases could be found, and as the artist could not afford to keep the picture, he was placed in a very embarrassing position. This coming to the knowledge of Mr. PHILLIV LYON, an old resident of this city and a friend of the late Archbishop, he determined the picture should be disposed of, and the artist relieved. He accordingly prepared a subscription paper, which provided that when it was filled, the subscribers should meet and draw lots for the picture. On Tuesday evening last, the chances being all subscribed for, the subscribers met at Room No. 24 Cooper Institute. The numbers were all placed in a wheel and drawn forth, one by one, by a young lad. When about two-thirds of them had been drawn, the lucky number came forth, and gave the picture to Rev. Father FARRELL, Pastor of St. Joseph's Church, of this city. The drawing was conducted in a very fair and open manner, and gave entire satisfaction to all. After the drawing was completed, the party adjourned to the Maison Doree, where a very bountiful supper had been prepared, and to which the gentlemen did full justice. After the dinner was finished, and the finest wines had been discussed, the real old-fashioned Irish whisky punch was produced, speeches were made, some very excellent songs sung, and a good time had generally, and which lasted until a late hour.

abstract: The movement to give a real old-fashioned Thanksgiving dinner to the gallant soldiers and sailers of the Union, has met with the most liberal and hearty response from the people. It is but little more than three weeks once the project was made...
lead_paragraph: The movement to give a real old-fashioned Thanksgiving dinner to the gallant soldiers and sailers of the Union, has met with the most liberal and hearty response from the people. It is but little more than three weeks once the project was made known through the papers; no extraordinary means were taken to bring it before the people; yet subscriptions have poured in so rapidly, from all parts of the country, that up to last night over forty thousand dollars had been received by the treasurer, Mr. THEODORE ROOSEVELT, and it is expected that at least ten thousand more will be received in season to be appropriated. The subscriptions are generally small, a large proportion of them ranging from fifty cents to five dollars; but every gift, large or small, was an offering of love, and often a sacrifice. No solicitation has been used to swell the amount. No one has been urged to give. Every one was left to give according to his inclination or his means.

abstract: Dinner for Soldiers and Sailors
snippet: Dinner for Soldiers and Sailors
lead_paragraph: -The movement to furnish a Thanksgiving dinner to our soldiers and sailors, of which a full account is given in another column, has proved a great success. No extraordinary measures have been taken to give publicity to the project. There have been no appeals to contribute to the dinner fund. And yet, within less than three weeks, the sum of nearly fifty thousand dollars has been sent to the committee in this city having the matter in charge, to be appropriated to the purchase of turkeys for the army and navy. This free-will offering is all the more gratifying and touching from the fact that, while our men of wealth have subscribed liberally, a very large proportion of the dinner fund has been contributed in small sums by persons whose hearts were far more liberal than their purses could afford to be -- wives, mothers, children of soldiers now in the field, or who have given their lives for their country, -- returned veterans who know how gratefully such a practical remembrance will be received by their old comrades -- old men, who remember the first war for liberty in America, and hope to see the present one end as happily. The heart of the people is with the soldiers; and thousands of families will next Thursday eat their Thanksgiving turkey with a double relish, as they think of the gallant fellows who sent EARLY "whirling through Winchester," and who keep LEE pent up in Richmond, enjoying a real old-fashioned Thanksgiving dinner in their camps.

abstract: Counterfeiting and Fractional Currency; Resumes the Practice of Law
snippet: Counterfeiting and Fractional Currency; Resumes the Practice of Law
lead_paragraph: The last issue of the postal currency has proved most unsatisfactory in a variety of ways. The different denominations were far from being easily distinguishable from the notes being of one size. The gilding on the notes was tawdry, and conceived in execrable taste. The engraving was good; but except to a keen and practiced eye it presented few points not easily susceptible of imitation. The vast herd of untutored manipulators could readily be deceived by a scurvy counterfeit of it. In short it has served its turn, and only served it indifferently well. It should be called in without delay, and we should have something better in its stead. The fifty-cent notes are counterfeited to an extent which it is impossible to estimate. The city is at this moment flooded by them. Scores of groggeries and policy shops act as distributing agencies for them. They are found fresh from the printer, circulating all round town; and it seems that the police and the detectives are utterly powerless to stop their increase. If nothing better can be devised, a return to the first issue would be vastly preferable to what now chiefly circulates. The issuing Department should at least see to it that the various denominations are distinguishable by the size as well as the color of the notes; that good substantial paper, with no guilding to it, is used, and that there is altogether less facility for counterfeiting the thing than exists at present.

abstract: Fullerton Contempt Case
snippet: Fullerton Contempt Case
lead_paragraph: William Fullerton vs. Gideon J. Tucket. -- This is a case growing out of the "Fullerton contempt case." Mr. Fullerton, having been nominally committed to the County Jail by the Surrogate for an alleged contempt of court, brings an action to recover damages for false imprisonment. The complaint recited the circumstances of the case, and set forth the process of the Surrogate's Court, under which the committal was made. To this the defendant demurred, and the demurrer was argued yesterday. The grounds of the demurrer were that an officer who acts judicially, having jurisdiction of the subject matter, cannot be held liable for damages, even for a wrongful act, the remedy being by certiorari appeal or a criminal proceeding.

abstract: Saturday morning. Sergt. DANIEL MURPHY, Nineteenth Massachusetts Volunteers, and Sergt. ALOKZO SMITH, Seventh Michigen Volunteers, (both of which regiments are attached to the Second Corps. Army of the Potomac,) appeared at the War Department, and presented to the Secretary of War battle-flags of the Forty-seventh and Twenty-sixth North Carolina Regiments, captured by them at Hatcher's Run Oct. 27, 1864. Sergts. MURPHY and SMITH were cordially taken by the hand by the Secretary of War. who. in suitable terms, thanked them for their gallantry and courage, which had produced such gratifying results. A medal of honor was awarded to each of them, and their names are now added to the list of those soldiers who, as evidence of their gallantry, have presented to the country colors captured, in many Instances. In hand-to-hand conflicts with the toe. -- Washington star.

abstract: Escape of from Old Capitol
snippet: Escape of from Old Capitol
lead_paragraph: ESCAPE OF PETERSON, THE REBEL SPY AND MAIL-CARRIER. -- GEORGE PETERSON, who was tracked from Canada to Alexandria, Va., by detectives, and arrested there on the llth inst., as a rebel spy and mail-carrier, made his escape from the old Capitol Prison last night, under the following circumstances: The sentinels on posts Nos. 12 and 7 permitted PETERSON, under some excuse which he offered, to go into a yard by a way and in violation of the rules of the prison. PETERSON, having disguised himself, and having succeeded in passing the sentinels on the posts above-named between 6 and 7 o'clock, made his way into the employe's mess-room. Here he is supposed to have found an iron chisel, left in the room by the gas-fiters, with which he broke open the door of the mess-room, which enabled him to cross the passage to the female department. In the passage-way he picked the lock and forced off the wooden braces (which were deemed sufficient to prevent escape). This enabled PETERSON to enter the store-room of the prison. When in this room he again succeeded in picking the lock and breaking the bolt of the door, by which means he entered the front office (second room, first floor, in the southern portion of the building). From this office PETERSON made his way into the street.

lead_paragraph: The latest and most explicit information about Gen. SHERMAN is from the Cincinnati Gazette, of Friday, which says SHERMAN's army left Atlanta in two columns, one on the 9th and the other on the 12th, moving eastward, the former via Macon, and the other directly toward Augusta, The Gazette adds that the first column was heard from on the 14th, and had then advanced seventy miles on the road toward Macon, driving everything before it, and destroying everything as it went. This would seem to indicate that SHERMAN is moving eastward, and furthermore that his army is making good progress.

abstract: Our cosmopolitan correspondent, DON RU  FINO M. DE ALFARRERO Y CAMPEON, asks once  more to be heard on what he considers to be the broad philosophy of the rebellion; the prime causes which led to it, the silent changes in the future structure of the Government to which it is leading, and the permanent influences it will leave behind it. There is very much in our correspondent's philosophy ...
lead_paragraph: Our cosmopolitan correspondent, DON RU FINO M. DE ALFARRERO Y CAMPEON, asks once more to be heard on what he considers to be the broad philosophy of the rebellion; the prime causes which led to it, the silent changes in the future structure of the Government to which it is leading, and the permanent influences it will leave behind it. There is very much in our correspondent's philosophy to which those who have been educated from their youth up to understand the workings of a free constitutional system will refuse to subscribe to. The dangers inherent in what DON RUFINO M.DE ALFARRERO Y CAMPEON calls diffused sovereignty, are naturally magnified to an inordinate extent in the eyes of those brought up under a quasi-military form of government -- we care not how wide may have been his range of subsequent observations and experience in other countries. Strong, concentrated Government, at whatever expense of individual liberty is the prime theory even with cosmopolites of our correspondent's broad philosophy. And this is by no means to be wondered at. The world has yet to learn that the "Latin race" in either hemisphere, understands what is the real basis of constitutional freedom. Outside of the Anglo-Saxon States municipal self-government is practically unknown. And yet it is on the municipal system of England that the present constitutional monarchy of that country is established and maintained. It was on the same system that a free Republic was built up here. And that system, with all due respect for DON RUFINO M. DE ALFERRERO Y CAMPEON, is the very essence and ideal of this "diffused sovereignty" of which our correspondent has so holy a horror, and against which he deals such trenchant blows.

abstract: Vote, the; and Organization After Election; The German Vote
snippet: Vote, the; and Organization After Election; The German Vote
lead_paragraph: After every previous election, the great fault of the Union and Republican party in our City, has been the entire giving up of its organization. Whether we gained a victory or suffered a defeat, as soon as the day of battle was over, we broke ranks, lost our organization and trusted to the effect of "ideas and principles," till a few months before the next great question was put before the people. Then again, we spasmodically awoke, chose officers, re-formed companies, began our drill anew, and attempted to make up for organization and discipline by immense activity and enthusiasm during a short time.

abstract: Sala, G A; Departure of; No Loss; London Telegraph; Its Character
snippet: Sala, G A; Departure of; No Loss; London Telegraph; Its Character
lead_paragraph: Mr. SALA, of the London Telegraph, publishes a card in a weekly paper to notify the public that he has been obliged to set sail for home without being able to bid adieu to his many friends in New-York. We regret that domestic affliction is the cause of the correspondent's leaving. But we doubt whether his countrymen either here or in England have much to lose, if his retirement from the post of correspondent should even prove to be permanent. No doubt, he has amused a large class in England, who relish wit, even if it is coarse, and who revel in caricatures of foreign communities, however broad and base may be their character. But when this is said, all that can honestly be claimed for Mr. SALA has been uttered. So far from his having contributed in any degree to the spread of correct intelligence among his countrymen respecting the causes, the progress, or the scope of this rebellion, he has from the first maliciously distorted whatever facts were put within his reach to serve a partisan purpose, or to gratify his overpowering appetite for travesty. His journal, the Telegraph, is a ???gnized mouthpiece of the rebel clique in London. It is a cheap, piquant, unscrupulous print, deriving its prime sustenance from the demimonde of Cockneydom. Fancy portraits of fast women, juicy reports of indecent trials before the Courts, and correspondence in the style of Sala, together with a free allowance of loud and vituperative editorial comment, have made the paper great in circulation. But in influence we should judge that Reynolds' Weekly far surpasses it.

abstract: Bank of Commerce, Investigation Concluded; Richmond Whig on Death of
snippet: Bank of Commerce, Investigation Concluded; Richmond Whig on Death of
lead_paragraph: The investigation in the case of MICHAEL O'BRIEN, WALTER PATTERSON and IRA GARADIER, alias GARSIDE, charged with swindling the Bank of Commerce out of upward of $25,000 by means of a forged check, and also with having been concerned in numerous other forgeries in this and other cities, was concluded yesterday at the Tombs Police Court, before Justice DOWLING -- i.e., concluded so far as that magistrate is concerned. At 10 o'clock, the hour to which the hearing had been adjourned, the court-room was crowded to suffecation with bankers, merchants, police-officers and citizens, all of whom, with mucn interest, bad watched the progress of the case. The prisoners were brought from their ceils by the officers of the court, and pplaced in the criminals' box. They appeared as all deep-dyed rogues usually appear, and, during the proceedings which took place in court relative to them, they looked on with that calm and stolid indifference peculiar to men long used to crime, and who are far gone down the road of infamy and ruin.

abstract: THE FOURTEENTH REGIMENT MILITIA. When this regiment left Brooklyn for Washington in the Spring of 1861, and entered the United States service for three years, the State military authorities acted upon the assumption that it had abandoned its State organization, and numbered it as the Sixty-second...
lead_paragraph: THE FOURTEENTH REGIMENT MILITIA. -- When this regiment left Brooklyn for Washington in the Spring of 1861, and entered the United States service for three years, the State military authorities acted upon the assumption that it had abandoned its State organization, and numbered it as the Sixty-second Regiment New-York State Volunteers. The officers and members always contended that they never had abandoned their State organization as militia, and did not acknowledge the new number by which they were designated on the volunteer rolls. Since their return the matter was presented to the present State authorities, and the former action in transferring them from the militia to the volunteers was virtually set aside by Gov. SEYMOUR, who recently transmitted to Col. E.B. FOWLER duplicate militia commissions for every officer in the Fourteenth Resiment, with the same rank as obtained while in the volunteer service. The commissions were received yesterday. and the regiment will again take its line in the Fifth Brigade N.Y.S.N.G., as before the war.

abstract: Examiner on Headache after Election
snippet: Examiner on Headache after Election
lead_paragraph: The Richmond Examiner thinks the Confederates "ought to derive sincere pleasure from the wild election excitement in the enemy's country because after excitement follow collapse and reaction; in the morning after a debauch comes the dismal deboire, with headache and nausea and weariness of life." The Examiner's drunken figure of speech may be all smart enough in its way; but it is all wrong as an illustration. The North has had its election, and instead of collapse, reaction, dismal deboire, headache, nausea and weariness of life, there is now a greater public vigor and strength, a greater confidence and a livelier pulse than there ever has been before since the opening of the war.

abstract: Report Ordered on Help by the Gods to Government of
snippet: Report Ordered on Help by the Gods to Government of
lead_paragraph: -- Capt. BEECHER has compiled within the last ten years the following curious voyages of bottles thrown into the sea by unfortunate navigators. A good many bottles cast into the sea next to the African coast, found their way to Europe. One bottle seems to have anticipated the Panama route, having traveled from the Panama Isthmus to the Irish coast. Another crossed the Atlantic from the Canaries to Nova-Scotia. Three or four bottles thrown into the sea by Greenland mariners off Davis' Straits, landed on the northwest coast of Ireland. Another made a curious trip -- swam from the South Atlantic Ocean to the west coast of Africa, passing Gibraltar, went along the Portuguese coast of France, and was finally picked up on Jersey Island. One bottle was found after sixteen years' swimming, one after fourteen years, and two after ten years. A few only traveled more than one year, and one only five days. This was sent off by the Captain of the Racehorse, on the 17th of April, in the Carribean Sea, and was found on the 228, after having gone through three degrees of longitude (210 miles,) western direction. Captain M'CLURE. of the Investigato, threw a bottle into the sea in 1850, on his voyage to Behring's Straits. It swam 3,500 miles in 200 days, and was picked up on the Honduras coast.

abstract: Greece and Its King
snippet: Greece and Its King
lead_paragraph: The admirers of strong government are in raptures because of the recent spirit and firmness displayed by the new King of Greece toward the National Assembly. That body, though specially elected to frame a new Constitution for the Kingdom, seemed in no haste to terminate their labors, and lay down their authority. The Hellenic Senate indeed was abolished under pretence that its existence was unnecessary, but the edifice of the Constitution was still very far from being complete. For nearly twelve months the young King GEORGE contemplated the dilatory proceedings of the assembly with Christian resignation. At length, however, even his patience gave way, and he addressed to the popular representatives a message in which, after censuring their past conduct, and expressing his determination to submit to it no longer, he coolly informs them that he has transmitted to the Chamber a draft of so much of the Constitution as they had neglected to prepare, to which he requires their assent within a period of ten days.

abstract: Horsfall's,Miss,Notorious Adventuress
snippet: Horsfall's,Miss,Notorious Adventuress
lead_paragraph: The Sheffield Independent gives a curious history of an engagement for marriage entered into by a young gentleman with the notorious "Miss HORSFALL," a smart young lady who pretended to be the niece of Mr. HORSFALL, M.P., and who managed in that character to swindle numerous tradespeople, who have obtained her committal to the next sessions of the Central Criminal Court on three distinct charges of embezzlement. "Shortly before this accomplished swindler commenced practising on the too susceptible shopkeepers in the neighborhood of Greenwich," says the Independent," she had been honoring Birmingham with a visit. As Miss HORSFALL, the reputed niece of the rich member for Liverpool, she found no difficulty in obtaining jewels, dresses, and other costly articles, such as a young heiress with expensive tastes might be supposed to require; and by dealings with her 'uncle' -- not the one whose name she bore but an accommodating relation with a hooked nose, who sports the sign of the Three Balls -- she raised enough money to carry on her game, and keep up a lady like appearance. This was the state of things when a young gentleman from Birmingham arrived on a periodical visit to Leeds, and took up temporary quarters at the same hotel in which Miss HORSFALL was residing. This young gentleman (whom we shall call FRANK, for the sufficient reason that FRANK is not his name) was traveling on a business tour for his father, who is one of the most respectable of our local manufacturers, following a line of business and residing in a suburb of Birmingham, FRANK saw and admired the charming MARY, who seemed to occupy a position in the hotel between that of a friend and a guest, and whose profuse liberality and condescending manners, added to her reputation of great wealthiness, made her an object of no little regard. FRANK found her affable, genial, and communicative; he had frequent opportunities of meeting her. and, to make a long story short, he fell in love with her. Nor was he doomed to despair, for the fair one confessed her preference for the ardent youth, and the upshot was that they were engaged to be married. By telling a story made up of the most flagrant untruths, this woman imposed upon a family who bear a high reputation for strictest integrity and whose natural love or truth may have disinclined them to distrust; while by simultaneously pursuing a secret course of swindling she was able to maintain her position in the eyes of those whom she had so impudently imposed, upon. Miss HORSFALL came to Birmingham as the affianced wife of FRANK, and was received by his family in that capacity. Her conduct was not in every respect satisfactory, but the minds of those disposed to believe the best are easily satisfied, and as Miss HORSFALL added hypocrisy in religious affairs to her other fatal accomplishments, she managed to avoid detection for a time The period for the wedding was fixed, and a house near the town was taken for the young couple to reside in. This house Miss HORSFALL undertook to furnish from her own private resources; and she proceeded to carry out that undertaking in a style which showed that her "resources" were as large as her tastes were extravagant. Tradesmen in London sent down furniture worth hundreds of pounds to order. There were four or five piano-fortes from different makers; chairs worth ten or twelve pounds each, much too good to sit upon; cushions to cover them, also too, valuable for ordinary use; carpets, tables and household "fixings" of all kinds, in all the same grand style. The stable had to be enlarged to make room for the splendid carriage horses sent down from London, and special provision had to be made for the smart groom who came to tend them. While all these preparations were in progress Miss HORSFALL was the guest of the family of which, according to the pro-programme, she was soon to be a cherished member; and she endeavored to show her gratitude for the kindness of her new found friends by loading them with costly presents. She was lavish with her wealth, and even tried to mix herself up with the business affairs of her dear papa that was to be. She offered FRANK's father the use of certain loose thousands belonging to her if he chose to accept them: but the offer was declined, or "dear papa" might have been wheedled out of promissory notes in advance, and have found them converted into hard cash, for which he would have been liable. The mechanism of Miss HORSFALL's daring scheme appeared to work admirably. As the wife of an honest and respectable man, whose name she might legally bear in any contingency, she would better face the exposure that was bound to come some day, even if her new connections could have been prevailed upon to avoid public scandal by settling with her dupes, or perhaps the bold adventuress really loved this young man, and was impelled by resistless passion, regardles or reckless of consequences. Whatever her motives or expectations, she was anxious to get married as quickly as possible, anxious to spend as much time as possible in the society of her intended husband, and anxious to stand well with his relatives. But though, as we have said, the mechanism appeared to work well. there was a screw loose somewhere. FRANK was not altogether satisfied with his bargain, and the evasion of his inquiries made him more determined to have all mystery cleared up with respect to the woman whom he was about to mary. The required explanations were not forthcoming, the plot thickened; the doubts in the young man's mind deepened into certainty -- and the match was broken off. The resolve once made, it was firmly adhered to. All the arts of a passionate and desperate woman were exercised in vain. The heart that had proved so soft and pliant at Leeds was hard and film as adamant at Birmingham; and the adventuress even though she urged that she could not survive the separation for three hours, was rejected by the man who had loved her. That the shock did not prove fatal, is established by the fact that Miss HORSFALL now lies in fall, awaring her trial now three charges of embozzlement. We believe that the family who have suffered so much annoyance by her perfidy have acted most honorably all through the matter, even to the assumption of liabilities they were not bound to undertake. Even since her imprisonment. Miss HORSFALL has written to the family of her intended husband, imploring a continuation of their friendship in her trouble, and making violent professions of religious sentiment, which we hope, rather than believe, to be the result of sincere repentance."

abstract: Our special correspondent at Nashville sends us a full and very interesting account of the initial movements of Gen. SHERMAN'S grand campaign in a region of the rebel Confederacy which has hitherto remained untouched by the Union armies.
lead_paragraph: Our special correspondent at Nashville sends us a full and very interesting account of the initial movements of Gen. SHERMAN'S grand campaign in a region of the rebel Confederacy which has hitherto remained untouched by the Union armies. For full details we refer the reader to our correspondent's letter. In brief, an expedition composed of the Fourteenth, Fifteenth, Sixteenth, Seventeenth, and Twentieth Army Corps, and KILPATRICK's Cavalry left Atlanta on the 12th inst., and proceeded in the direction of Macon. This force comprises about 50,000 men, including 9,000 picked cavalry. Thirty days' rations for man and beast were taken, and the expedition is finely equipped in every particular. Gen. SHERMAN's scout system is so complete as to render failure almost an impossibility.

abstract: New-Haven R R Disaster and Mr Gould
snippet: New-Haven R R Disaster and Mr Gould
lead_paragraph: -At an inquest into the New-Haven Railroad disaster on Saturday afternoon, JOHN GOULD, who is described as "late a Railroad Commissioner of the State of Connecticut," testified, that he examined the road after the accident occurred, and found no defectiveties or rails. Mr. GOULD does well to put his testimony in this negative form. There were intelligent witnesses present when the accident occurred who saw very defectiveties; ties, in fact, all but completely rotten. We doubt, moreover, whether Mr. GOULD's notions of safe traveling will be generally accepted, when he sells us that he thinks forty miles an hour a safe rate on such a piece of road. Those who desire to exculpate the Company and its sevants in this matter, would do well to speak with caution.

lead_paragraph: FIRE IN BROADWAY. -- Soon after 12 o'clock on Saturday night, a fire broke out in the mattress manufactory of F.R. HOUSEN, on the second floor of premises No. 1,360 Broadway, near Thirty-seventhstreet. The building is owned by Mr. CHARLES BEARDSLEY, aad was occupied for manufacturing purposes. The first floor was used by Mr. NORWOOD, trank-maker. His loss is about $1,500; the insurance could not be ascertained. The damage to the stock and machinery of Mr. HOUSEN is about $2,000. The third floor was occupied by M.J. DOOLKY, brush manufacturer. His loss is about $1,000; fulls insured in the Grocers' Insurance Company The building, which was damaged to the amount of from $3,000 to $4,000, is insured in the Indemnity Insurance Company. The flames extended to the adjoining building No. 1,358, also owned by Mr. BEARDSLEY, and occupied by ABRAHAM LEE & Co. It was damaged to the extent of $3,000. The cause of the fire is at present unknown.

abstract: Lyons, Lord; Recovered from Illness
snippet: Lyons, Lord; Recovered from Illness
lead_paragraph: -- It is reported from Washington that Lord LYONS has almost recovered from his recent illness. We feel sure that the whole community will receive this intelligence with sincere satisfaction. It will be left [???] story to record how much the United States owed to our own Minister at the Court of St. James, and to the British Minister at Washington, in maintaining a fair understanding between the two Governments, during a crisis which threatened on so many occasions to bring them into actual collision. Combined with a large and varied experience of the world, the Ministers who have been the mediums of official communication between the two countries since the opening of the war, have shown that they possessed the still rarer qualifications of even and genial temper. Both Lord RUSSELL and Lord DERBY have borne voluntary testimony to the uniform and perfect courtesy of Mr. ADAMS in all his communications with the Government of Her Britannic Majesty, and we are sure that the same testimony would be borne in the case of Lord LYONS by those who have had to conduct official intercourse with him on this side. We can only express a cordial wish that his mission may be prolonged, and, as satisfactory to both Governments in the future as it has been in the past.
