abstract: A GAMBLING CONSIDERATION VOID. -- The Supreme Court of the District of Columbia, in banc, has decided the suit brought to recover three promissory notes, of one thousand dollars each, made by Ex-Congressman THOMAS F. BOWIE, of Maryland, in 1857, payable to the or[???]er of one FRANKLIN STEERS, from whom the plaintiff purchased the notes. The defence was, that these notes were given for a gambling consideration, and, therefore, void in the hands of a bona fide holder for value. Chief-Justice CARTER delivered thu opinion of the Court, in which he said the proofs were that BOWIE, being intoxicated, was irrational. In the case of insanity it would be perfectly competent to prove the idiosyncracies of the insane person when in that condition. Why not th[???]n, when reduced to the condition of temporary inebriety? The notes were condemned by the law, and had no virtue in the hands of the gamblers. Therefore the Court decided in favor of the defendant. The plaintiff, one THOMPSON gave notice of appeal to the United States Supreme Court.

abstract: Election; What makes the Triumph Complete
snippet: Election; What makes the Triumph Complete
lead_paragraph: Men call the reelection of President LINCOLN a triumph of the Union cause. This don't tell the story. The reelection might have occurred, and have exposed the Union cause to greater danger than ever. A bare electoral majority would have surely had that effect. It would have encouraged the opposition to the Government to make its organization yet more complete, and keep itself ready for the first new opportunity to seize power. The second term of Mr. LINCOLN would have seen all the faction and sedition of the first, with ten-fold greater activity. In all earthly probability we should have had flagrant insubordination here in the North long before that second term had expired.

abstract: SHERMAN has been chiefly occupying his time in laying in a full supply of hard bread and beef cattle; and he has with him of the former sixty days full rations, and several thousand bead of the cattle. For all things else he will depend on the country over which he is to pass. His animals can subsist well. Corn and sweet potatoes are abundant. During the week ending on the 5th inst. he gathered inl, 760 wagon loads of corn, 436 loads of sweet potatoes, and a few horses, without sending his foraging parties more than thirty miles from Atlanta. He could manage to live for six months without communication once with the North. In reference to his cavalry, he feels certain of his ability to obtain horses enough to keep good his original stock; and perhaps he may be enabled to mount some more men.

lead_paragraph: It is estimated by those who are perfectly competent to judge, that there is a population of 20,000 on this Island that pay neither rent for the dwellings they occupy, nor municipal taxes as holders of real estate. They comprise that portion of the population known as "squatters." In one ward, which we need not name, they combined a year or two ago, in sufficient numbers, to control the elections for Aldermen and Councilmen. abstract: BOUNTIES TO VOLUNTEERS IN KINGS COUNTY.  The money heretofore raised for paying bounties to volunteers being exhausted, the Board of Supervisors held a special meeting on Saturday last for the purpose of taking measures to supply more funds with the view of keeping up recruiting.
lead_paragraph: BOUNTIES TO VOLUNTEERS IN KINGS COUNTY. -- The money heretofore raised for paying bounties to volunteers being exhausted, the Board of Supervisors held a special meeting on Saturday last for the purpose of taking measures to supply more funds with the view of keeping up recruiting. In connection with the subject a statement of the amounts heretofore raised for volunteering was submitted by the County Treasurer, showing that from Nov. 11, 1863, to July 29, 1864, the amount of bonds authorized to be raised was $3,000,000. Amount borrowed and paid to Bounty Committee, less $10,000 reserved for veterans, $2,664,000, leaving a balance of $336,000. Bonds disposed of by sale and exchanged for certificates, $1,154,000; outstanding certificates; $1,510,000, making a total of $2,664,000. Bonds on hand, $846,000. A resolution was adopted to the effect that in the opinion of the Board of Supervisors the best interests of the county will be promoted by continuing the enlistment of volunteers for the United States service. A resolution was also adopted directing the County Treasurer to advertise that coupon bonds in sums of $1,000, bearing 6 per cent. Interest, will be sold at his office on demand. A committee of three was appointed to assist the County Treasurer in the matter.

abstract: of New-York
snippet: of New-York
lead_paragraph: Lieut.-Col. JAMES A.P. HOPKINS, of the One Hundred and Thirty-third Regiment N.Y. Vols., (Second Metropolitan,) died on Saturday last of pneumonia, at the residence of Mr. Inspector DILES, No. 118 Maccougal-street. Col. HOPKINS had been quite Ill for several months, and to his numerous friends and acquaintances his death was therefore not unexpected. The regiment to which Col. HOPKINS was attached, left this city for. New-Orleans in the early part of the rebellion. After arriving at the latter place his force was ordered up the Mississippi and there took a noble part in the seige of Port Hudson. It was there that the lamented Lieut. BENJAMIN F. DENTON, of the Metropolitan Police force, met a glorious death while leading on a column of his brave men. Col. HOPKINS also fought with great bravery and skill in other important engagements in the Department of Gen. BANKS. During the latter part of his career at the South, he was appointed Chief of Police in the City of New-Orleans, and finally he received a commission as Chief of the United States Detective Force of that city. He was for many years previous to the breaking out of the war, well and favorably known as a member of the police of this city, and had held the position of Captain in the Third and Sixteenth Precincts. His funeral will take place from the residence of Mr. Inspector DILKS, at 1 o'clock this afternoon.

abstract: The larger portion of his (SHERMAN's) force, it is reported, is already moving toward Selma, Ala., and if this be true, Mobile must be his destination. Apropos to this conjecture, we learn that an immense fleet of transports, laden with stores, hasarrived in Mobile Bay, which looks as if a movement was contemplated at an early day in that quarter. We have, upon the above hypothesis, the most singular ferture of the war, that is, of two large armies passing each other by a sort ot flank movement and moving in an opposite direction. SHERMAN may be a shrewd banker, a stubborn fighter, and a prospective candidate for Presidential honors, but we venture the prediction that he has been woefully outgeneraled this time. We shall soon see. The situation is certainly increasing in interest in North Georgia.

lead_paragraph: TRIAL TRIP OF THE TORPEDO BOAT STROMBOLI. -- On Saturday afternoon the new torpedo vessel Stromboli made her first official trial trip, with a view of testing her engines and torpedo machinery. Her inventor, Chief-Engineer W.W.W. WOOD, Capts. WORDEN and BOGGS, and the engine builders, were the only persons present, as it is desired that the invention shall be kept a secret for a time at least. She left the Batrery yard of Messrs. SECOR & Co., at Jersey City, and proceeded up the North River, in company with Picket-boat No. 6, which also was making her first trial trip. Both vessels steamed along easily, attracting much attention from passing vessels and the passengers on the ferry-boats. Experiments were made in detaching torpedoes and in manoeuvering the vessels in a variety of ways, but with the severest tests the vessels worked to the satisfaction of all concerned. The speed of the Stromboli under easy steam, and while submerged, as if in action, was about eight knots, and with the power she can develop, could have been run up to ten knots. Picket-boat No. 6 made nine knots easily. As we have described in detail the construction of the vessels within the past few days, we do not deem it necessary to repeat it at this time. The following is a list of the officers of the Stromboli: First-Assistant JOHN L. LAY, Commanding; Second-Assistant-Engineers, CHAS. H. STONE, J.B. CHADWICK, JOHN SMITH; Third Assistant-Engineer BYRON S. HEATH. The Stromboli will sail in a few hours for very important service. The officers of this vessel have received their appointments to thi vessel, with the understanding that if it should become a military necessity to destroy the vessel to prevent her falling into the hands of the enemy, they perish with her.

abstract: -It is evident, as our Quebeo correspondent has always pointed out, that the British Government are eager to push the Provincial Union scheme through with as little delay as possible. Mr. GEORGE BROWN, the President of the Canadian Executive Council, has been deputied by his colleagues to go to England and explain the scheme agreed upon before the meeting of the Imperial Parliament. Early in January, the Provincial Legislatures are to be convened, to give the new Constitution whatever legal sanction they have the power to give it. And unless there should be a hitch in the House of Commons, the Union will probably be consummated before the close of next year. This hasty-pudding style of thing seems to us to cheat the Provincial voters out of their right of saying whether their rulers have done right or wrong in the Quebec Conference. We should have thought that the colonists might with advantage have been asked to say whether the new Constitution has their approval.

abstract: Thanksgiving and Families at Home
snippet: Thanksgiving and Families at Home
lead_paragraph: The country has just sent a substantial Thanksgiving dinner to its soldiers and sailors, and doubtless feel the better for it. It will be fully appreciated in the army and navy. Those who fight our battles by land and sea, are not the fellows to despise good cheer. Their long diet of hard tack and salt pork has not, we may be sure, made them indifferent to roast turkey and fresh vegetables. It was a small thing for our people to raise a few thousand dollars for this object. A million would have been a cheap price to pay for the fresh courage and hearty cheer with which this pleasant and timely gift will inspire the hearts of our brave soldiers. We have seen enough of camp and field life to know that nothing makes a soldier more cheerful than the feeling that the people at home sympathize with him in his struggles, privations and sufferings, and appreciate his services at their true value. And as the Thanksgiving festival is the day of al days for thinking of home and the old household gatherings, the bountiful dinner that will be distributed through the camps and the fleets, will save many a brave heart from sadness and depression.

abstract: His Great March
snippet: His Great March
lead_paragraph: We are enabled to-day to publish highly interesting details concerning SHERMAN's new and grand campaign through Georgia. The news is confirmatory of the dispatch announcing the inauguration and character of this remarkable march, which was published exclusively in the TIMES of the 10th inst. The campaign sustains all the characteristics of greatness originally attributed to it. The magnitude of the force, the distance of the march, and the importance of the purpose and the work, are not at all diminished; while the collateral objects assume immense magnitude, and the possible ultimate results loom up in the imagination.

lead_paragraph: Brig.-Gen. BARRY, Chief of Artillery of Maj.Gen. SHERMAN's army, arrived at Buffalo on Sunday, seriously ill from an attack of erysipelas. Gen. BARRY left Gen. SHERMAN at 9 o'clock on the morning of the 12th inst., at Kingston, Ga. Gen. BARRY says that Gen. SHERMAN has every cavalry, infantry and artillery soldier that he wants, and is certain of complete success. The men are all in the highest spirits. They have all received eight months' pay. Their outfit has been especially adapted to a hard and rapid campaign. The morale of the entire army is unequaled, and the vigor and determination of Gen. SHERMAN will push it triumphantly through the glorious work it has to do. We print this morning liberal extracts from Richmond papers of Friday last, which, though furnishing no later information as to SHERMAN's whereabouts, show plainly the fear and trepidation with which the rebels regard his movement. They exhort the Georgia militia to exhibit a miraculous degree of bravery, which is rather inconsistent, coming from a batch of Richmond editors, who are howling against JEFF's wholesale conscription of the fraternity.

abstract: Rebel Plot to Seize
snippet: Rebel Plot to Seize
lead_paragraph: -- The details which were given, in last Friday's TIMES, of the rebel scheme to seize the California steamships, revealed a plot at once very daring in character and very extensive in its scope. The plot, though concocted in the Southern Confederacy, and having its base at Havana, was addressed only to the Pacific. With good luck, HOGG might have captured three or four of the Pacific Mail Steamship Company's vessels, before discovery, beside two of the Panama Railroad Company's ships plying to Central American ports, and then running over toward the Sandwich Islands, might have inflicted serious damage on sailing commercial vessels; and thence proceeded to the north coast of California and the west of Oregon, and destroyed one or two ships of Charlady's line. The plan was as nicely concocted as it was extensive; and had it seceded, would have furnished a more respectable navy for the Southern Confederacy than it has ever been possessed of.

abstract: Basis of its Being
snippet: Basis of its Being
lead_paragraph: It appears that a party in Canada are in favor of having the new scheme of Confederation adopted by the Parliaments of the var ious Colonies, without submitting it to the people, and the proposal to take a popular vote upon the question has been denounced by a leading provincial organ as "a dreadful American heresy." The right of the Parliaments to do as they please in the matter, is defended on the ground of their "omnipotence," and it is declared that any formal acknowledgment that there was any appeal from their decision on a point of this kind, would be a long stride toward democracy.

abstract: On Confederacy a mere Shell
snippet: On Confederacy a mere Shell
lead_paragraph: Lieut.-Gen. GRANT arrived in this city from the front on Saturday afternoon, and took rooms at the Astor House, where he was joined by Mrs. GRANT and his two sons. His business in New-York was entirely of a private nature, and he therefore sent a personal request to the City Press that no mention, either editorially or otherwise, should then be made of his presence here. In compliance with his wishes the papers universally refrained from any allusion to his movements, and even the ovation he received, at the Fenton reception on Saturday evening, was passed by in silence. At 2 o'clock yesterday afternoon the General left the Astor House, and took the cars for Baltimore, en route to City Point, where he will doubtless be found at his headquarters to-night. When the Veteran Union Club complimented the Governor elect with a serenade, they little thought what a distinguished guest would grace the occasion with his presence. It was only after much solicitation that Gen. GRANT consented to come down to the receptio-room, and occupy a seat by the side of Gov. FENTON. His entrance was greeted with a shout of applause, bursting out from the heart of every man there present, the homage of the people to their great victorious leader. No words can express the wild enthusiasm of the moment when cheers for GRANT rang from floor to ceiling, and the audience looked upon that modest, unassuming man, whom half the continent fears and the other half adores. He positively refused to speak although repeatedly called upon. Voices in the crowd called out "Rise up, General, we want to see you." The General rose, bowed and sat down amid cries from all parts of the room, of "God bless you, General, God bless you." To Gen. SICKLES, he delegated the honor of returning his thanks for his flattering reception. His reticence on this occasion, his resistance to the inducement to say at least a few words, was but an illustration of the obstinate firmness of his character, which, having once determined to do or not to do a thing, will not allow him to deviate from his purpose. The General received very few visitors during his stay in the city. On Sunday evening he called on Lieut.-Gen. SCOTT, at the Hoffman House, but it is believed to have been nothing more than an unofficial visit of courtesy. To those whom he honored by receiving them at his rooms, his manner was cheerful, his conversation hopeful, and his views of the situation most assuring. No one can hear him talk without being profoundly impressed with the force of a character combining immense power with the most unassuming modesty. His presence fascinates, his eye magnetizes you, and you cannot look in his face, listen to his few calm, quiet words, and go away doubling that GRANT is master of the situation, and knows it. To a gentleman of this city he said, on Sunday afternoon: "The Southern Confederacy is a mere shell. I know it. I am sure of it. It is a hollow shell, and SHERMAN will prove it to you." The calm, modest consciousness of power with which this was said, more than the words themselves, conveyed to his visitor an unqualified conviction of the truth of the General's remarks. In answer to a question whether, in his opinion, ninety days would bring the end, he said, with a grim smile: "I am not a ninety-day man, but we shall see what will happen in six months." The significance of these words from the Commander-in-Chief of our armies, with the sense of his knowledge of and power over the whole subject, which his manner imports, cannot be underrated. Gen. GRANT knows and believes what he says, and he is not accustomed to express his views without due consideration. From the movement of Gen. SHERMAN it is evident he expects great results, and in the success of his operations he has the most perfect confidence. Although few had the pleasure of seeing him, yet he so impressed those few with his own hopefulness that they cannot help reiterating the cry of the Veteran Union Club and the prayer of all loyal men, "God bless you. General; God bless you!"

abstract: -Gen. PRICE has ended his campaign in Missouri, or, rather, has been driven out of the State, and away down south of the Arkansas River. We think it is a misfortune that he and his "twenty or thirty thousand half-starved bushwhackers and half-starved vagabonds," as Gen. CURTIS calls them, were allowed to leave Missouri. But, on the whole, it is decidedly better to have them out of the State than in it -- better to have them south of the Arkansas River than north of it.

abstract: Rebel Gen, Thoughts for; The News about
snippet: Rebel Gen, Thoughts for; The News about
lead_paragraph: The new facts which we were yesterday enabled to give about the character and progress of the heretofore inscrutable campaign of Gen. SHERMAN, furnished abundant material to the public for thought, speculation and excitement. And we may remark here, for the advantage of those who are troubled lest the revelations we have made should be of service to the enemy, that the publication of the facts did not trouble in the slightest the military soul of Lieut.-Gen. GRANT, who was present in this City on Saturday, Sunday and Monday, but who is by this hour pretty near to the front. And if it did in no wise perturb him, we do not see why it should any one else, unless it be our journalistic cotemporaries who have been so signally behind-hand in the publication of intelligence concerning this most remarkable of all the campaigns of the war.

abstract: There no longer remains any doubt that SHERMAN has torn up the Atlanta and Chattanooga Railroad, boldly cut himself off from all connection with his base, and plunged headlong into the heart of Georgia, depending entirely upon the force he has with him, and the weakness of the country through which he designs to pass.
lead_paragraph: There no longer remains any doubt that SHERMAN has torn up the Atlanta and Chattanooga Railroad, boldly cut himself off from all connection with his base, and plunged headlong into the heart of Georgia, depending entirely upon the force he has with him, and the weakness of the country through which he designs to pass. His aim is, beyond all question, to secure a position upon the seaboard, where he may receive reinforcements and supplies at leisure, and having there established his base, to prosecute further operations next Spring or during the Winter. It is not known for what point his course is directed -- whether he has selected Savannah or Charleston as his base, or whether he aims first at Selma and afterward at Mobile.

abstract: -A young woman named Mary BROWN was brought up before Recorder MARTINDALE, of Jersey City, yesterday, charged with having stolen $11 from Mrs. MALERNY, of No. 359 South Seventh-street. It appears that the accused called at the house of the complainant, and while there abstracted a $10 and $1 greenback bill from a wallet which was lying on a bureau. Immediately after leaving the robbery was detected, and the accused was followed into a grocery, and the money demanded back. Mrs. BROWN denied any knowledge of it, but was detected in adroitly slipping the $10 bill in her mouth. Mrs. MALERNY seized her by the throat, and in attempting to obtain the money had her finger badly bitten, and the woman finally succeeded in swallowing it. The prisoner was committed to the County Jail for trial.

abstract: The rebels might not be able to send any portion of their army from Virginia in time to impede or harass the march of Gen. SHERMAN through Georgia. But from such points as Wilmington, Charleston and Savannah, from the rebel garrisons all along the seaboard of North and South Carolina, a force of perhaps twenty thousand men might quickly be gathered on the line of the Savannah before SHERMAN could reach it. Add to these the militia of Georgia, who are already in the field under COBB, and the militia of the adjoining States -- constituting a force certainly twenty thousand in number. These forty thousand men might hope to obstruct SHERMAN's advance, in his long march, for days, if not for weeks, during which time they might suppose HOOD would be able to get round into the western part of Georgia, in SHERMAN's rear.

abstract: Seven-thirty Loan and Customs; Perry vs Draper; Perry vs Draper; Seven-Thirty Notes for Duties Case
snippet: Seven-thirty Loan and Customs; Perry vs Draper; Perry vs Draper; Seven-Thirty Notes for Duties Case
lead_paragraph: After reading two opinions in cases recently decided, this morning, the Judge inquired if there was anything ready for the jury. Mr. A.F. Smith stated that the case of Perry vs. Draper, involving the question whether the seven-thirty notes were receivable for duties, was ready. District-Attorney Smith rose and said that, on behalf of the Government, he must request a postponement of this cause. He stated that the case was commenced on the 7th of the present month; that an appearance was pu in by the Collector, not through the District-Attorney, but through a Deputy-Collector, Mr. Runkle; and that the plea was put in at once and by consent of the parties, the defendant's attorney acting, as he supposed, under the approval of the Treasury Department, but not with that approval, the case was put on the calendar for the present term, as it could not have been if it had taken the regular course; that he heard nothing of the case, except by rumor, until a few days since; that he had communicated with the Secretary of the Treasury at once in reference to employing counsel, desiring to have Mr. Evarts as counsel, and that Mr. Evarts only returned yesterday from Washington; that the Secretary of the Treasury was also very much occupied with the preparation of his Annual Report, and that it was very important, therefore, that the case which involved some twenty-five millions of dollars should go over, that proper time for preparation and consultation might be given.

abstract: Florida Crew Find Their Home in England
snippet: Florida Crew Find Their Home in England
lead_paragraph: A copy of the London Times of the 7th, received yesterday, by the Borussia, announces the safe arrival at Southampton of Capt. MORRIS, of the Florida, from Bahia, along with a portion of his officers and men. The Times takes pleasure in adding that the remainder of the Florida's crew, not captured by the Wachusett, will reach England by a schooner which had sailed from Bahia. We note the item of news simply to remark, how singular it is that the first thought of these piratical adventurers, when they find themselves in a tight place at sea, is how to reach England. SEMMES provided for this retreat when he got a pleasure yacht to act as tender for him before accepting Capt. WINSLOW's challenge. All that escaped of his crew instantly took passage for Southampton. And in fact, in the crisis of danger, the whole band of roving Confederate cut-throats seem to seek their island home, as it were by instinct, no matter in what part of the globe they run, or be cast ashore. France, Italy, Brazil, Holland, Spain, and Russia have no attractions for them whatever. They are bound to get home as quick as possible for a new outfit, and the means of prosecuting new adventures.

abstract: Mott-st. Saloon
snippet: Mott-st. Saloon
lead_paragraph: About 2 o'clock yesterday morning a quarrel took place in a drinking saloon, kept by JOHN CODY, at No. 297 Mott-street, during which the proprietor CODY was so dangerously stabbed in the abdomen with a knife in the hands of a hackman named WM. CARTER, that no hopes are entertained of his recovery. During the affray, and immediately after CARTER had inflicted the wounds above named, THOMAS CODY, a brother of the wounded man, entered the house, when he was assailed by CARTER and severely stabbed in the left shoulder. His wound, though severe, is not considered so serious as that of the other. The Police were at once notified of the state of things, Officer REGAN, of the Fourteenth Precinct, came in and took CARTER into custody. The latter stoutly resisted the officer with his knife, and but for the timely and vlgorous use of the club, the officer would no doubt have shared the fate of the two CODYS. The wounded men were both properly cared for by Police Surgeon GIBSON. CARTER has been committed by Justice DOWLING to await the result of the Injuries inflicted by him.... A man named JAMES HENNESSEY was also arrested on the charge of interfering with Officer REGAN while in the discnarge of his duty. He was locked up for examination.

abstract: A responsible citizen has put forward a proposition, and backed it with an offer of ten thousand dollars from his own purse, to set up an associated enterprise for the supply of coal and other articles of household necessity at different stations within the city, at something, like cost price. He invites others to join him, and pledges on behalf of liberal and wealthy citizens a capital of a quarter of a million as a beginning, provided thoroughly energetic and honest trustees can be got to see to the proper employment of the fund. The proposition has much in it to recommend it to the public generally. It would be a practical and immediately available means of giving aid to the industrious poor, at no great sacrifice -- if any -- to the enterprisers, and of giving aid to the industrious poor without putting on them the indignity of being the recipients of charity. We believe it would reach an end even greater than this. It would ultimately lead, under a wise and prudent trusteeship, to the institution of such cooperative societies among workmen themselves as have been so successfully carried on in Great Britain; and the whole community of consumers, rich and poor, would be benefited by the overthrow of those petty trading conspiracies, which are the curse, probably, of every large city on this side of the Atlantic, but which are the especial bane of the City of New-York to-day.

abstract: The trial of Lacky Maning for the murder of his wife was concluded yesterday afternoon. The charge against the prisoner was that on the 31st of July last he and his wife, being both grossly intoxicated, quarreled, and the accused beat his wife. Jane Maning about the head with a broomstick, inflicting injuries from which she died. No one saw Maning strike his wife. Her body was found by a sister of the deceased in the room occupied by the couple several days after death. A post-mortem examination disclosed the cause of her decease to be a fracture of the skull. abstract: Mercantile Marine, Our
snippet: Mercantile Marine, Our
lead_paragraph: Owing to a variety of causes, but chiefly to the demand made upon the officers of our merchant service for naval duties, the mercantile marine of this country is now far below the standard of four years ago, in its personnel. At that time we could, as a nation, boast of, perhaps, the finest body of shipmasters and officers in the world; men of education, of practical ability and of great value to our merchants. The best ships afloat were commanded by these gentlemen, a majority of whom combined the qualities of excellent navigators with commercial business talents. Many of them have been connected with our navy since the first blockade was established, up to the present time; and by their signal bravery, good judgment and officer-like qualifications, have risen in rank to the full limit of the existing laws of the Navy Department, while in the estimation of their brother officers, and the country at large, they have won for themselves an honorable and enduring fame. Our merchant ships, in the hands of men like these, called forth the respect and admiration of the world, and the captain of one of our fine clipper ships commanded that attention which was given to an officer of the same rank in the navy. In fact, our mercantile community looked upon them with far more consideration than they did upon the naval officer; and it was not strange that this should be the case, for at that time there was no demand for the services of fighting men, save to display and protect our flag and pennant.

HARRIS and HENRY BLACKMAN, were arraigned yesterday, before Justice DODGE, at the Jefferson Market Police Court, on the charge of having swindled Mr. MATHEW CLARK, of ...
lead_paragraph: BROADWAY GAMBLERS ARRESTED -- AN ONEIDA COUNTRYMAN SWINDLED OUT OF ABOUT $1,000, Two notorious gamblers named RICHARD H. HARRIS and HENRY BLACKMAN, were arraigned yesterday, before Justice DODGE, at the Jefferson Market Police Court, on the charge of having swindled Mr. MATHEW CLARK, of Oneida County, this State, but now temporarily stopping at the Girard House, in this oity, out of the sum of $845 at a game of "faro." From Clare's testimony, taken in court, it appears that on Monday night last he was walking up Broadway in pursuit of some of the attractions which this great city affords, when be came across a policeman whom he asked if he could direct him to a gamb ling-house where they played the game of" faro." The policeman said there were quite a number of that class of houses in that vicinity on Broadway, and that he could point bim to one which he thought would just suit Mr. Clark. He accord ingly pointed out to him the premises No. 663 Broad way, and told him to go up on the second floor and he would find a " laro" table and some one to play with him. Clark went there and found four or five men engaged in the above game around a table, Harris it seems was dealer, a man whose name is given as Richard ROE was game-keeper, Samuel Jones was looker out, Henry Blackman, above-named, was th man to receive the guests. He received Clark very politely, and cordially offered Clark his seat at the table. Clark took the seat, and in a very short time he was $845 poorer than when he entered. Officer GAFFNEY of the Fifteenth Precinct, succeeded yesterday in securing Harris and Blackman. The former was held for trial by Justice DODGE in the sum of $500 bail, and the latter was required to give bail to appear as a witness. Whether or not the others will be arrested, or the gambling-house broken up, does not at present appear.

abstract: DANIEL WESTERVELT, of this city, is building for the Pacific Steam Navigation Company, of Liverpool, England, a beautiful side-wheel steamer, to be called the Favorita, and from present appearances she will be probably the fastest steamer of her length in the world; she is intended to be so at least.
lead_paragraph: DANIEL WESTERVELT, of this city, is building for the Pacific Steam Navigation Company, of Liverpool, England, a beautiful side-wheel steamer, to be called the Favorita, and from present appearances she will be probably the fastest steamer of her length in the world; she is intended to be so at least. The Favorita is intended for the route of this comPany on the west coast of South America, extending to the Isthmus down to the lower parts of Chill. As the route is cut up into divisions, it is not known at present what division she will be attached to. Capt. James Hall, one of the company's officers, is here superintending the construction of the vessel.

abstract: BREWERY. -- The lady managers of this noble institution have made ample arrangements for the observance of Thanksgiving Day. The public exercises by the children in the chapel commence at 2 o'clock P.M. The dinner hours are from 4 to 8; gifts to the children immediately after dinner. Among the generous contributions to the dinner is a single frosted cake twelve feet long, beautifully ornamented, costing over two hundred dollars. Some idea of its magnitude may be formed by the fact that a portion of its ingredients consist of one barrel of sugar, one hundred pounds of butter, and two thousand eggs. Such as wish to enjoy the day and do good, would do well to attend. We hope our friends will not forget their contributions to aid the institution in successfully prosecuting its great work.

abstract: THE VERMONT. -- The United States receiving-ship Vermont, lying at the navy-vard, Brooklyn, has received since Aug. 16, 4,252 recruits, as follows: Seamen, 1,065; ordinary seamen, 447; landsmen, 1,703; firemen, 515; coal heavers, 356; boys, 166: total, 4,252. To whom has been paid money, viz: Government bounty, $92,627 39; advance pay. $78,-095 86; clothing, amounting to $104,843 60; small stores, $2,786 86; making a total expenditure of $278,353 71. There is at this date remaining on board 906 men available for draft, and the average number daity received is 30, the majority of whom are substitutes. One most excellent arrangement has been made on board this ship, which it would be well for other captains in our navy to imitate. It is this: In order to obviate the great difficulty heretofore existing on board receiving-ships, and which has caused so much suffering to the families of persons joining the navy -- the want of a reliable party to receive and forward moneys, and the want of which has caused so mamy complaints of thieving, gambling and other frauds -- all recruits have been afforded the opportunity of sending their money to their friends, through Westcott's Express, and as an evidence of the very general appreciation of this arrangement, It may be weil to state that upwards of $350,00U has been received and promptly delivered by the agent of the Express Company, whose office has become one of the institutions of this ship. The officers attached to this ship are Capt. N.G. SCOTT, commanding; W M. MOSLANDER, Acting Master and ex. officer: C.W. HASSLER, Paymaster; GEORGE L. MEAD Acting Assistant Paymaster.

abstract: Thompson, Dr R H, Ex-Health Officer
snippet: Thompson, Dr R H, Ex-Health Officer
lead_paragraph: Dr. R.H. THOMPSON, formerly Health Officer at this port, died recently at his residence in Brooklyn, after a short illness. His age was 47 years. He was a native of Rennselaer County, in this State; practiced medicine in Albany for ten years, and removed to Staten Island in 1855, having received the appointment of Health Officer. He held that position for four years, and it was in the last year of his term that the Quarantine riots occurred, in which he was a sufferer -- his house having been burned by the rioters, with all its contents, and his family narrowly escaping with their lives. In 1858 Dr. THOMPSON removed to Brooklyn, and interested himself in various measures of public improvement; becoming President of the Brooklyn Central and Jamaica Railroad and Park Commissioner, and finally was appointed Quarantine Commissioner in 1863, to protect and represent the interests of the City of Brooklyn. To his skill as a physician and his executive talent, the port of New-York is largely indebted for its present immunity from the epidemics incident to emigration and foreign commerce. His codification of the health laws, adopted by the Legislature of this State, is now in force.

abstract: Feast in the Army
snippet: Feast in the Army
lead_paragraph: -- People who eat their turkeys and fixings to-day will enjoy them all the more when they think of the two hundred thousand soldiers in front of Petersburgh, in the Shenandoah Valley, around Washington and elsewhere, and the tens of thousands of sailors in big ships, little ships, wooden ships and iron-clads, at sea, in port, on blockade duty or on shore, who will be enjoying like good cheer through their thoughtful beneficence. Turkeys will be thankfully and joyously eaten in the camps, in the trenches, in bomb-proofs, on the advance picket line, and under fire -- by pale men in the hospitals and by lean convalescents -- by those in navy-blue on deck, in the hold, and, perhaps, in some cases, in the rigging. Legs and wings will be picked clean by brave fellows with their muskets in their hands, and to the music of the rifle and the cannon. The white meat, the brown meat, the neck, the other parts, and the stuffing, will all be ably discussed in the tents, by the campfires, and on shipboard. Privates and officers, the drummer-boy and the Major-General, Jack and the Admiral, will all for one day enjoy equality -- as regards their dinner.

abstract: Capt. PETTY, of the Fifth Precinct, yesterday made the following report to Mr. Inspector CARPENTER, at Police Headquarters: "A gang of rowdies, composed of thieves, gamblers, pimps, bounty jumpers, fighters and rumsellers, headed by MIKE NORTON, alias Crowe, JOE COBURN, "Rockey" MOORE, and others, principally from the Eighth and Fourteenth Wards, came down to the Fifth Ward Democratic primary election, held at Laird's Hotel, for the purpose of intimidating the voters, overawing the inspectors, and seizing the box containing the ballots. Their designs were frustrated by the presence of a sufficient force of police to protect the citizens and prevent a breach of the peace. N.B. -- MIKE is a candidate for Alderman of the Fifth District."

abstract: Farmers Should Sell Direct to Consumers; Monopolies and the Industrious Poor
snippet: Farmers Should Sell Direct to Consumers; Monopolies and the Industrious Poor
lead_paragraph: A cotemporary mistakes the reference we made to the Coal monopolists when it classes us as advocates of charitable subsidies for cooperative Unions. But we are satisfied that the villainous combinations between forestallers and petty tradesmen in NewYork to-day could be broken down to the tune of at least fifty per cent on all their sales, if the intelligent portion of the great consuming population of New-York chose to say the word. We are not "bound up" in trading cooperative associations. They have often failed. Individual character in the enterprisers must always affect the results promised from associated enterprise. And we are not bound to any specific remedy for the evils which unquestionably do exist in the relations of the consumer of our large cities toward the actual producer.

abstract: To-day there will be a general wind-up of the out-door games at cricket, base ball, and other sports of the field. The cricketers of the New-York and St. George's Clubs will play a wind-up match among the members and friends of the separate associations. The base ball clubs will end the season also in friendly encounters. Most of the leading associations will be on their respective grounds at 12 o'clock A.M. The famous champion nine of the Atlantic Club will play the original nine at baseball on the Capitoline grounds Brooklyn. Should the day be fine there will, undoubtedly, be some of the best sport of the season exhibited to-day, on the different ball grounds, as well as the Long Island trotting tracks. Good day, good sport.

abstract: Thanksgiving Proclamation; Thanksgiving Proclamation; Thanksgiving Proclamation
snippet: Thanksgiving Proclamation; Thanksgiving Proclamation; Thanksgiving Proclamation
lead_paragraph: It has pleased Almighty God to prolong our national life another year, defending us with his guardian care against unfriendly designs from abroad, and vouchsafing to us in His mercy many and signal victories over the enemy who is of our own household. It has also pleased our Heavenly Father to favor as well our citizens in their homes as our soldiers in their camps and our sailors on the seas, with unusual health. He has largely augmented our free population by emancipation and immigration; while He has opened to us new sources of wealth, and has crowned the labor of our workingmen in every department of industry with abundant reward. Moreover He has been pleased to animate and inspire our minds and hearts with fortitude, courage and resolution sufficient for the great trial of civil war into which we have been brought by our adherence as a nation to the cause of freedom and humanity, and to afford to us reasonable hopes of an ultimate and happy deliverance from all our dangers and afflictions.

abstract: Arrest of part of Georgia Legislature
snippet: Arrest of part of Georgia Legislature
lead_paragraph: The first positive news of Gen. SHERMAN'S progress comes, as we expected, through rebel sources. Richmond papers of the 21st and 22d insts., contain telegrams from Macon, Ga., announcing SHERMAN'S rapid approach, and that on Sunday, the 20th, his advance was within eighteen miles of Macon. That city, the rebels report as only defended by Georgia militia, under HOWELL COBB, and they had no hope of being able to keep the place from falling into SHERMAN's hands. As SHERMAN advanced he cut a swath with his army forty miles wide, drying up the country of its subsistence and means for sustaining a rebel army. At Griffin he captured a portion of the Georgia Legislature. The cavalry force, under KILPATRICK, was reported as dashing over the country unresisted, in the direction of Milledgeville and Augusta. The Richmond papers evidently have other news, but, they say, as we are entirely dependent upon them for news from SHERMAN, they will not gratify us by giving it. Of course such news cannot be unfavorable to our side.

abstract: The brig Lady of the Lake, of Bermuda, HILL, Jacmel, sixteen days, with logwood, &c., to CHARLES THACKER & CO., arrived this morning. Left schooners Indus. for New-York, loading, to sail on the 8th; Kast Wind and Martha Washington, from Boston, discharging. On the 10th inst., Fortune Island bearing northeast, about four miles, spoke a pilot-boat and look from her Capt. NICKERSON, of the brig Vivid, of Halifax, N.S., whose vessel sunk three miles from Bird Rock, on the 14th inst. She was from Aux Gayes, for Glasgow. Capt. NICKERSON states that a few hours after his vessel sunk, he spoke the brig Express, Capt. HOWARD, of Halifax, and requested him to take himself and crew on board, which he refused to do. Night coming on, and every prospect of a northwest gale, and being some six or seven miles from shore, and the men worn out, he requested Capt. HOWARD to tow the boat in toward the land that he might save himself and crew, but was refused; and they were obliged to make for the land, which they succeded in reaching during the early part of the gale, which had then broken upon them.

lead_paragraph: The fifth annual exhibition of the Artists' Fund Society is now open at the Derby Gallery, Broadway. There are 331 pieces, 267 of which are loaned for the exhibition, and 64 are contributions to the fund. These last are to be sold for the benefit of the society on the 30th of December, at auction. Until that time they will remain upon exhibition in the present well-arranged and pleasant rooms. But one thing mars the pleasure of the visitor. The hanging of the pictures seems to have fallen into incompetent hands.

lead_paragraph: It has frequently been asserted by the enemies of the Union that even the breaking up of the large armies of the rebels would leave a population in the South exceedingly embittered against the Government, who could not be subdued for many years. We believe there is much less force in this objection to our military plans than appears on the surface.

abstract: Attack on Prince Nagato's Forts
snippet: Attack on Prince Nagato's Forts
lead_paragraph: -- We have some additional particulars of the opening up of the Sea of Japan to the commerce of Europe and America. The Western entrance to the Sea of Japan is guarded by the Straits of Simonosaki, and on the 5th of September the allied fleet, consisting of English, French, and Dutch men-of-war, and one American vessel, specially chartered for the occasion -- consisting in all of thirteen vessels -- made an attack on what are called Prince NAGATO's forts. Shots were exchanged, but no decisive results were reached until the following day, (the 6th of September,) when the guns of the Japanese forts were silenced, shortly after daybreak. The attack was accompanied with considerable loss to the allied fleet, one hundred being reported killed and wounded.

abstract: Speech at Lincoln and Johnson Club, New-York; and Johnson Club, N. Y., Banquet; Speech at Lincoln and Johnson Club, New-York
snippet: Speech at Lincoln and Johnson Club, New-York; and Johnson Club, N. Y., Banquet; Speech at Lincoln and Johnson Club, New-York
lead_paragraph: This Club, last evening, held Thanksgiving at the Metropolitan Hotel, giving a grand banquet in celebration of the late triumph in the reelection of LINCOLN and the election of JOHNSON, and the triumph in this State. The large dining room of the Metropolitan was handsomely draped with flags. The tables did not groan with good things, simply because they had no tongues to express their sense of the load of good things spread out before the numerous guests assembled. To say that the LELANDS spread the tables in their best style, is perhaps all that could be said. Hon. CHARLES SPENCER, Esq., presided at the table, surrounded by many distinguished guests.

abstract: A large audience assembled last evening at the Cooper Institute to hear a lecture from Dr. IVES in aid of the Catholic Reformatory of New-York, which was organized for the purpose of protecting and providing for the destitute children of that Church. abstract: Day
snippet: Day
lead_paragraph: In every loyal State, from the Atlantic to the Pacific, this day will be observed as an occasion for special recognition of the national and individual mercies vouchsafed by Providence during the year soon to close. The propriety for the observance will be questioned by no man who believes in a Superintending Power -- that is to say, by no man who does not rank himself with the brutes that perish. The year, certainly, has been full of blessings, that should excite gratitude in every rational nature.

abstract: ALLEGED VIOLATION OF THE ENLISTMENT ACT. -- C.D. LE BRUN, who keeps an office at No. 6 Wall-street, was, yesterday, arrested by officer O'BYSNE. of the Essex Market Police Court, charged, on the complaint of Mr. JOHN DEMPSKY, OF No. 163 West Houston-street, with having violated the Enlistment Act. In his affidavit before Justice MANSFIELD, DEMPSEY alleges, that on the 15th inst. he accompanied three men, named JAMES MCAVOY, JAMES and JOHN F. LAUGHTON, to the prisoner's office, for the purpose of enlisting them. After they made known their wishes to Mr. LE BRUN, the latter told them that the enlisting business in this city was very dull at present, but that if they would go to Jersey City he would guarantee them $450 each. Quite reluctantly the men went to Jersey City, the accused accompanying them thither. The three men there enlisted, and entered into the military service. DEMPSEY therefore charges that LE BRUN has violated the Enlistment Act. The accused was required to find bail in the sum of $2,000 to appear for trial.

abstract: Gov of Wisconsin; The Rebel News from
snippet: Gov of Wisconsin; The Rebel News from
lead_paragraph: We are to-day indebted to the rebels for the first credible account of the progress of Gen. SHERMAN's army through the State of Georgia. On Saturday last, one of SHERMAN's columns was rapidly approaching Macon, and his advance is reported as having reached the outskirts of the city; while the other column is moving upon Augusta, but we are not informed how far it has got on its way. It seems that there is other Georgia news beside this at Richmond, but the rebels say they do not mean to gratify us by telling it. We are grateful to them for even this unkind remark, however, as we are able to infer from it that the news which they are holding back is such news as would afford us gratification. Who can tell what it may be.? Perhaps SHERMAN has overwhelmed the immense COBB, and his doughty militia, that marched boldly forth to confront the Union hosts. Perhaps he has had peace propositions for the stiffnecked GOV. BROWN. Perhaps he has compelled the Georgia legislators whom he captured to hold a special session, take the oath of allegiance and repeal the ordinance of Secession. Perhaps he finds the coast clear for a march upon Augusta and Savannah. But we might conjecture many things, and not get at the right one after all.

abstract: -- There was buried at Mechanicville, Saratoga county, last week, CHARLES FELLOWS, color-bearer of the One Hundred and Fifteenth Regiment, as gallant a soldier as ever gave up his life to save that of his country. His death was due entirely to rebel fiendishness. Wounded in one of the recent battles in front of Petersburgh, he fell into the enemy's hands. With a refinement of cruelty they amputated his limb, which was shattered below the knee, and cut it off so close to the body, that his recovery was impossible. Had he been properly attended to, he would have no doubt lived. While he was lying on the field a rebel came up to him and asked who he was going to vote for as President. He replied, "For Lincoln, if my life is spared so that I can reach home." The "secesh"called him a "d_____d Abolitionist," took his hat and passed on. FELLOWS had been a color-bearer of the regiment for two years. He was exchanged, but came home to die. -- Troy Times, Nov. 23.

abstract: Influence of the War World-wide
snippet: Influence of the War World-wide
lead_paragraph: We are apt, in this great war, to lose sight sometimes of its world-wide bearings, and its influence upon the permanent history of man. It touches so closely our present feelings and interests, and our whole daily life, that we are apt to view it only in these relations. Friendly and intelligent observers in other countries, viewing the strife at a distance, see its great and permanent significance more clearly than we do. This has appeared in many of the utterances of such men as GASPARIN, GOLDWIN SMITH and GARIBALDI. The last named friend of liberty has written a brief note from Caprera, correcting certain statements to the effect that he had become antagonistic to the cause of the Union. He says he considers the American [???] to be one "affecting all mankind," and exclaims: "Woe to the world if the North do not come out victorious from this struggle." It is thus that our cause appears abroad, and thus that it will appear to the generations who shall come after us in this country. The words that ROBERT HALL used to the English people during the Napoleonic wars may well be applied to the people of this nation now: "As far as the interests of freedom are concerned," said he, "the most important by far, of sublunary interests you, my countrymen, stand in the capacity of the federal representatives of the human race; for with you it is to determine (under God) in what condition the latest posterity shall be born; their fortunes are intrusted to your care, and on your conduct at this moment depends the color and complexion of their destiny. If liberty, after being extinguished on the continent of Europe, is suffered to expire here, whence is it ever to emerge in the midst of that thick night that will invest it?"

abstract: -It is now settled that this gallant officer and accomplished gentleman is elected to Congress from the First (Milwaukee) District of Wisconsin. He will succeed the present Peace Democratic member. The people of that district, aided by the gallant soldiers in the field, have highly honored themselves by electing Gen. PAINE. The next Congress will not contain a truer patriot, a more incorruptible man, nor a more genial, popular gentleman. He will be certain to win respect and love from every quarter, and his severe wounds, received in the service of his country, will entitle him to the prominent position we are certain he deserves.

abstract: Roanoke; The Capture of and Capt Drew
snippet: Roanoke; The Capture of and Capt Drew
lead_paragraph: -- It is due to the master of the Roanoke, Capt. DREW, and to the public as well, that we should draw special attention to the fact that Capt. DREW is charged, in the Havana letter which we publish this morning, with knowledge of the piratical scheme for the capture of his vessel. We were the first to point out that the circumstances under which BRAINE and his associates got on board the Roanoke in Havana harbor were exceedingly suspicious. We threw no imputation upon Capt. DREW, but it has now become imperative that he should have an opportunity of proving his innocence, by a judicial trial in some form. It has also become apparent that the Government will be compelled to adopt new and rigid measures of precaution in such cases. This Roanoke affair, as described in our Havana correspondence, is altogether atrocious.

abstract: System of Free Labor, La. Lady on
snippet: System of Free Labor, La. Lady on
lead_paragraph: A letter has been published, purporting to come from a lady in Louisiana, on Gen. BANKS' system of free labor, and attempting to prove it a failure, by setting forth the insubordination of the negro servants, the small result of their labor as compared with that of whites, their inability to comprehend the nature of contracts, and so on. The letter, in short, is precisely such a one as an Irish landlord of the old school will write at this day about Irish servants and peasantry; as the French aristocracy were in the habit of writing about their tenantry; and as Russian nobles write about their serfs. Every vice which the ex-slaveholder of Louisiana charges against the negroes, as something peculiar to people of their race, may be found ascribed to any white race which has been long in a condition of servitude or degradation, in any modern work which treats of their character. Lying, stealing, carelessness, indolence, are the vices of the slave everywhere, and not alone in America; and they disappear as his condition improves. No man who has never seen his rights respected by others, will ever respect theirs. No man will ever tell the truth who has no means of protecting himself from violence but falsehood and fraud. No man will ever respect property who has never had any, and has lived long with the knowledge that he never can acquire any. No man will ever feel a strong respect for the family tie who has never had a home, and has been bred in the belief that he can never have any better claim to wife or children than if he were an ox or an ass. No man ever yet retained or acquired a sense of honor with the marks of a whip on his back. How can they respect themselves whom nobody else respects? These things are true of all races. It must never be forgotten that the Helots belonged to the foremost race of the world.

abstract: Sermons, >amp;c.
snippet: Sermons, >amp;c.
lead_paragraph: Yesterday was more generally observed as a national holiday than any preceding Thanksgiving day we remember. Stores were universally closed. The churches were opened and filled with devout worshipers. The charity of the citizens of New-York provided for the unfortunate poor a bountiful supply of those comforts which make the day a joyful one to them. The people of this city felt that it was a day of thankfulness and gratitude, not merely for the fatness of the annual turkey which graced the family table, but for comparative prosperity in all things. An exciting political contest has passed away and not left in its track the devastating effects of bloody strile, as many feared and a few hoped.

abstract: Squatter Population of; Squatter Population of New-York City
snippet: Squatter Population of; Squatter Population of New-York City
lead_paragraph: We are assured, by those whose official position has brought them into immediate contact, for many years, with the "exempt" population of this city, that the picture of squatter sovereignty which was given in a recent issue of this journal, only told half the truth. Out of every seven squatter tenements, it can be shown that five are unlicensed groggeries; that on Sundays and other holidays they are the resorts of the vilest and lowest character, of both sexes, and that they serve the purpose of repositories for petty thievings from one end of the island to the other, besides being nurseries for juvenile criminals of a more dangerous class than those bred in the crowded haunts down town.

snippet: Sympathisers at the North; H S Foote on; says We have Sympathizers in the North
lead_paragraph: in the rebel Congress, on the 19th, it will be seen that Mr. FOOTE was gracious enough to proclaim the indebtedness of the Confederacy to its friends at the North. FOOTE, moreover, is as candid as he is gracious. He says: -- "We have friends, good, true, valiant friends in the North. * * * We have more sympathizers in the North than in all the rest of the world." We presume FOOTE spoke thus with some knowledge of the facts. It will be interesting to see how his gushing friendship is reciprocated here, among those for whom he certifies after this whole-souled fashion.

abstract: States Rights in the Rebel Congress
snippet: States Rights in the Rebel Congress
lead_paragraph: The report of the debate on State exemptions from military service, which took place in the rebel Congress on Saturday last, is singularly suggestive. We publish it in an abridged form, that our readers may see by what easy steps the rebel Legislature is descending from the high ground of absolute State Sovereignty to that of concentrated military despotism. A Committee has reported in favor of dictating to the separate States of the Confederacy how many State officers it shall be lawful for each Commonwealth to keep in its employ, and to hold exempt from Confederate military service. It seems that some of these independent sovereignties claim the privilege of keeping a larger retinue of State servants than Confederate interests will warrant.

lead_paragraph: Here is nothing further from Gen. SHERMAN substantially later than we published yesterday, but we print fuller details of his progress and the manner of his march. The army moves through the country in four columns, by four parallel roads, and is divided into two wings, the right commanded by Maj.-Gen. SLOCUM and the left by Maj.-Gen. HOWARD. The columns concentrate at a point yet to be decided upon. Foraging and impressment of stock and stores is regulated by strict military discipline. Any destruction of property rendered recessary, either by its value to the rebel army or by the hostility of the people, is to be regulated by army Corps Commanders. All trespassing upon private dwellings is strictly forbidden; horses, mules, &c., are to be taken, and able-bodied negroes also, when they will not encumber the column. The rate of marching is fifteen miles per day. The Richmond papers of the 21st and 22d, though orofessing not to be alarmed at SHERMAN'S movement, yet betray a degree of startling nervousness and anxiety, and express great fear that the people of Georgia will not be found equal to the occasion.

abstract: ACADEMY OF MUSIC. -- To-night DONIZETTI's opera of "Don Sebastiano" will be produced for the first time in America. It is an Importsnt work, and, we have reason to know, has been placed upon the stage in a most liberal manner by Mr. MARETZEK. The rehearsals which have lately taken place justify the expectation of a success of no ordinary kind. The libretto is by SCRIBE. It is in five acts, and contains several situations of unusual Ingenuity and interest. No opera of equal importance has been produced for many years. The orchestra and chorus have been strengthened for the occasion; new scenery and costumes have been prepared, and the cast introduces the best members of Mr. MARETEEK's company. Upward of two hundred additional per sons are employed in the representation of this splendid work.

abstract: Enrollment Lists and Gen Fry's Circular; Fry's, Provost-Marshal, Circular on
snippet: Enrollment Lists and Gen Fry's Circular; Fry's, Provost-Marshal, Circular on
lead_paragraph: It is a singular perversion in the Opposition press to assign to General FRY'S circular, which we published yesterday, the character of a military edict, or to distort it into a forewarning of an immediate conscription. Any one who cares to get at its true intent, will see, without any special study, that it is merely a suggestive commentary upon the errors and irregularities which have hereto-tofore prevailed in making a correct enrollment of citizens liable to military duty. It points out the way, therefore, to remedy the evil from which such large communities as New-York have been the special sufferers -- excessive quotas. The larger the number of enrolled not liable to military service -- such as aliens, non-residents and persons over age, -- the larger the quota. To correct this unfair enrollment, is thus at once the interest of the whole community, as it is the special interest of each individual citizen.

abstract: We publish this morning, from our special correspondent, Mr. H. J. WINSER, who accompanies Col. MULFORD'S Exchange Fleet in the Savannah River, a thrilling and deeply interesting account of the exchange of prisoners now taking place, one thousand two hundred and fifty of whom arrived at Fortress Monroe on Thursday. The
lead_paragraph: We publish this morning, from our special correspondent, Mr. H.J. WINSER, who accompanies Col. MULFORD's Exchange Fleet in the Savannah River, a thrilling and deeply interesting account of the exchange of prisoners now taking place, one thousand two hundred and fifty of whom arrived at Fortress Monroe on Thursday. The letter of our correspondent gives the most convincing proof of the sufferings and present condition of these men. The official correspondence which accompanies his description will be read with feelings of mingled pity and horror. Out of their own mouths are the rebels convicted of barbarities to helpless captives that would make the blood of a cannibal run cold. We print largely from the correspondence thus furnished. But there is more of a similar character yet to come.

abstract: Gen. Granger's Order of Thanks to
snippet: Gen. Granger's Order of Thanks to
lead_paragraph: We see that Gen. ASBOTH has been compelled by the severity of his wounds to retire for the pressent from active service and go to New-Orleans for medical attendance. He is succeeded by Gen. BAILEY. Gen. ASBOTH is one of the oldest and most meritorious of the foreign officers who entered our service when the rebellion broke out. He is a man of high character and of very marked ability. He bore a prominent and most honorable part in the active scenes of the Hungarian Revolution, being one of the few in that contest who brought practical military knowledge and experience to the aid of the cause. During his residence in this country he has won the respect and friendship of all who knew him by the sterling qualities of his character, and by the modest manliness of his demeanor.

abstract: Kimbro vs Colgate, >amp;c; Gold Contract
snippet: Kimbro vs Colgate, >amp;c; Gold Contract
lead_paragraph: Rolly P.S. Kimbro vs. James B. Colgate and Charles Burrall Hoffman. -- This case came up on a demurrer to the declaration. The declaration set up that on Oct. 26,1863, the defendants, who are citizens or New-York, contracted with the plaintiff, a citizen of Tennessee, to sell him gold or silver bullion, and likewise to buy from him gold or silver bullion, which contract was, by its own terms, not to be performed till after three days from the making of the contract; that the contract was not in writing and not stamped, as required by the Internal Revenue Act of July 1, 1862, and was in violation of sections 4 and 5 of the act amending that act passed March 3, 1863; that under the contract the plaintiff paid the defendant, on various days. $22,537 36, and that by virtue of the said 4th and 5th sections of the act of March 3, 1863, there accrued to the plaintiff a right of action to recover back the sums paid by him under the contract, which the defendants refuse to pay.

lead_paragraph: ACADEMY OF MUSIC -- PRODUCTION OF DON SEBASTIAN. -- The first of Mr. MARETZEK's promised novelties -- "Don Sebastian" -- was produced at the Academy last evening, after many weeks of elaborate and conscientious preparation. The opera is entirely new to our public -- a fact which is the more remarkable, in as much as it is the latest and best work of a composer whose other productions are held in high esteem with us. Nearly twenty years have elapsed since SCRIBE's excellent story of the unfortunate King of Portugal was set to music by DONIZETTI. It was intended for Parisians, and was produced in the gay metropolis with great splendor. At first it did not enjoy a Very extended popularity. The Court was in mourning for the Duke of ORLEANS, who had been thrown from his carriage and killed. Fashionable pleasures were, for a time, forgotten in a grief that was almost universal. Subsequently, "Don Sebastian" was revived with eclat, and has ever since been regarded as the masterpiece of its composer. A very short inquiry will explain why it has not been produced here. The work is long, and constructed on the largest plan of the French stage. There are five acts and as many situations. A very heavy expenditure has to be encountered before it can be submitted to the public at all, and no one has felt disposed to run the risk of such a venture, even if any have had the ability to make it. A combination of happy circumstances has induced Mr. MARETZEK to undertake the task, and "Don Sebastian" must now be added to that long list of operas which he has been the first to introduce to our public, and which, with one or two exceptions, constitutes the entire repertoire of our opera-house.

abstract: at Andersonville; Horrible Treatment
snippet: at Andersonville; Horrible Treatment
lead_paragraph: Our special correspondent who accompanied the fleet that went to Savannah to bring back ten thousand of our exchanged prisoners who have been confined by the rebels at Andersonville, sends us a letter that will be read with terrible interest. He had already sent us an account of the devilish treatment that these captives had undergone, as narrated by themselves, and as proven by their appearance, and by the records of mortality. It appears that the worst had not been told. It seems that the rebels had actually been attempting to realize hell upon earth, with Union soldiers for their victims. Fearful testimony is that furnished by the rebels themselves. The documents given are transcripts from original rebel documents obtained from Andersonville.

abstract: Rev. Dr. THOMPSON took for his text Third Ecclesiastes, verse three: "There is a time to break down, and a time to build up." He proposed to con  sider whether it is not possible to build a nation so that it shall stand. Lord BACON marks the degrees of ...
lead_paragraph: Rev. Dr. THOMPSON took for his text Third Ecclesiastes, verse three: "There is a time to break down, and a time to build up." He proposed to con sider whether it is not possible to build a nation so that it shall stand. Lord BACON marks the degrees of honor in a State, viz: Founders, saviors and defenders, and in the last place fathers of their country. Founders of States are sometimes unconscious in their work. They settle in a new soil, and then grow in to great cities, & c., and the founders do not know how. The Plymouth children joined to build a Stale before they built houses, When they landed at Andover they declared a State. Man is distinguished from the animal, Inasmuch as he is a moral and political being. He is social. These forty-one Pilgrims created a State and founded a State lasting as time. He recited the preamble of the foundation of the colony of Massachusetts. That simple declaration is the great charter of freedom for all on this continent. There the nation began; coining to America planted a colony under a patent, they founded a nation on principle. These were the first founders whom BACON described. It was then given for the second founders to propagate what had been done by the first founders. It was given thorn to harmonize this gift of independence with order. It is next given to us as restorers and fathers, who, by ruling justly, making the times great. We may a scribe to us another distinction, those who fight for the country. And when faction and treason has built up in the land, and when it said it is time to break down this temple of liberty, it is given us to rebuild this great and grand edifice. It is ordered that this temple shall not be be broke down, but it is the time to break down this Confederacy of treason and conspirators. The speaker said that society is founded on family. All society had its origin there. A true society is not an artificial compact. He then referred to PLATO's several definitions of man, and showed their application. The said society is not merely a conglomeration of individuals who form a Government to rule over them. Man has not alone rights, but, du[???]es. Wherever one has rights, he has duties, slavery cuts at the root of society, and by severing the family He of the nation, slavery strips the man of wife and children, and thus society, which is founded on family, becomes destroyed. Equally destructive is the monopoly of land by the aristocracy. In the South, there is a concentration of large acres of land in the hands of few proprietors. In New-York, each farm averages a little over a hundred; in Virginia the average farm is over three hundred acres; in South Carolina five hundred and ninety-nine; and so on through the South. Thus the body of the laboring population are precluded from an ownerse[???]p in the soil, Hence that pestiferous designation of "poor whites." England is falling into this evil. The tenants are there worse off than the people were under the feudal system. Society is thus made up of two extremes -- the owning and the owned. No nation can land permanently which is builded on a landed aristocracy. The grand hope of this nation lies in the Homestead Act. This, with the confiscation of the estates of the rebels of the South, will cause the nation to take deep root and fill the land. The patriotic poet of the nation will yet live to see his prophetic vision fulfilled when free homes take the place of slave plantations. The history of land is the history of races. Every where do we find in a nation that has rooted itself in history a race. The nation must grow by assimilation. The natural structure must be strong enough to bear the weight of foreign elements.

lead_paragraph: The diabolical plot to burn the City of NewYork, published yesterday morning, proves to be far more extensive than was at first supposed. It is already proved to the entire satisfaction of the authorities, that the affair was planned by the rebels and has been in preparation for a long time past, the men selected to perform the work were sent to this City at various times and under various pretexts, and arriving here they formed themselves into a regularly organized band, had their various officers, including a treasurer, whom they could always find, and who was always ready to supply them with the money necessary to carry out their infernal work, and they proceeded deliberately to mature their plans for one of the most fie[???] dish and inhuman acts known in modern times.

abstract: The Board of County Canvassers finished the canvass yesterday of the returns of the late election, and will make the declaration of results tomorrow. The missing returns of the vote in the Third District of the Twenty-first Ward, having been obtained by the County Clerk, the canvass ...
lead_paragraph: The Board of County Canvassers finished the canvass yesterday of the returns of the late election, and will make the declaration of results tomorrow. The missing returns of the vote in the Third District of the Twenty-first Ward, having been obtained by the County Clerk, the canvass of the Eighth Congressional District was concluded without further discussion. Mr. BROOKS' plurality is 146. The total electoral vote of the city toots up: Democratic, 73,709; Union, 36,686, Total, 110,395; Democratic majority, 37,023. The vote for Coroner, between WM. SCHIRMER, Democrat, who has been supposed to be elected by a small majority, and EDWARD A. COLLIN, Union, is so close as to be almost a tie, and which is elected is a question that will require the most carefully computed footings to prove.

abstract: If the vote polled at the late Presidential election in Philadelphia be any criterion of the population, our city has increased materially during the progress of the war. In 1860 we polled here some 82,000 votes, and the census of that year showed our population to be 565,000, which would be in the ratio of about one voter to every 6,88 of the population. At the Presidential election this year we polled 99,800 votes, and at the ratio as in 1860 ought therefore to have 686,404 inhabitants. Another test is afforded by the total number of regular and extra, which this year foot up about 129,000. Calculating the taxables to be in the usual average of one in every five and a half of the population, this would give us now about 709,500 inhabitants. It is therefore evident we have In Philadelphia somewhere about 700,000 inhabitants. This is confirmed by the water statistics. In 1860 the waterworks of this city supplied 7,465,740,277 gallons to a population of 565,000 persons, or about 13,212 gallons to each person. In 1863 the total supply was 9.498,775,141 gallons, which in the same ratio would give about 718,000 inhabitants. -- Philadelphia N. American.

abstract: The Richmond papers of the 24th contain no news from Georgia, except a single item that SHERMAN, on the 22d, was east of Macon, where he had been previously reported. There is no news yet of the capture of Macon, and from the ...
lead_paragraph: The Richmond papers of the 24th contain no news from Georgia, except a single item that SHERMAN, on the 22d, was east of Macon, where he had been previously reported. There is no news yet of the capture of Macon, and from the direction of Gen. SHERMAN's march, it would seem that he had passed that city, leaving it on his right and Tear, and destroying the railroad both north and south of it. The redoubtable HOWELL COBB and his militia had taken refuge behind the fortifications of the place, and every person capable of bearing arms had been ordered out under penalty of arrest. But SHERMAN, declining the risk of a delay of one or two days, and the necessary expenditure of ammunition for the capture of a city he would not hold, has deliberately moved by, leaving COBB in his rear to scratch his head and thank his stars for having escaped demolition. The Richmond Dispatch of the 24th says one column of troops followed the line of the Georgia Railroad sixty-seven miles east of Atlanta, and then struck off due South for Milledgeville. This column had already reached Eatonton, the terminus of the railroad running off from the Georgia Central through Milledgeville, and only 25 miles north-west from the latter city. The other column, headed by SHERMAN in person, followed down the line of the railroad leading to Macon as far as Gr[???], sixty-eight miles from Atlanta and forty-three from Macon, and then struck off southeast to Gordon, located twenty miles east of Macon on the Georgia Central Road, at the point where it is intersected by the Milledgeville Road. Thus Macon was cut off from communication eastward, and the announcement of its capture could not reach Richmond even if made. At Gordon SHERMAN was attacked by WHEELER's cavalry, but without success. From Gordon below and Eatonton above the Federal columns were moving on Milledgeville in conjunction, leaving no avenue of escape for the citizens and others except on foot eastward. The Legislature and Methodist Conference, both in session there, had hastily absconded.
