abstract: Rochdale (Eng) Cooperative Union; Cooperative Societies and Trade Monopolies
snippet: Rochdale (Eng) Cooperative Union; Cooperative Societies and Trade Monopolies
lead_paragraph: We have negative evidence that sharp and biting want has never yet overtaken any large portion of our industrious poor for a long continuous period, in the fact that cooperative trading societies, such as have been in existence in England and Scotland for over a quarter of a century, have never yet become, as it were, an established institution among us. There are one or two in operation in the manufacturing districts of New-England. But these were put in operation quite as much from the taste which the operatives had acquired for experiments in social science, as from any immediate pressure of need on the part of the associates. The Rochdale Cooperative Union, which was, we believe, the pioneer institution in England was, on the other hand, the offspring mainly of a stern necessity. The workers in the mills -- especially those who had young families to support -- found that no industrious effort, no frugality in household outlay, and no self-denial in the way of luxuries, could guarantee them against the sharp pinchings of poverty, during even a short season of sickness, unless they could devise some method of preventing the absorption of their earnings by greedy and unscrupulous traders, who, in the best of times, charged exorbitant profits on what they sold, and in the dull seasons succeeded in mortgaging every item of their customer's personal effects for two or three weeks' credit. Many of the very poorest mill-workers of Rochdale were intelligent as well as sober, and their desperate circumstances, during a long crisis in the cotton manufacture, brought them inspiration. They determined (the best of a body of operatives mainly belonging to one mill) to club together. Their joint capital made up a sum of fifteen odd pounds sterling. With this they opened a store, getting credit for the rent of the building. At the beginning there was no profit, and very little satisfaction. But the acting manager, himself a workman, was persevering; the directors, in the main, were men of firm purpose, and all of them were true to each other. Energy, steadiness of effort, courage and honest dealing ultimately gained the day. That fifteen pounds' stock of goods -- mainly groceries -- has grown steadily and surely, till to-day it approaches close to half a million sterling. It has had, as all great enterprises necessarily have, a varying fortune. But those who have stuck to it -- and they form nineteen-twentieths of the class that first instituted the business -- have improved their fortunes in a variety of ways. They bear testimony in their latest reports, that the combination to purchase articles of daily and necessary consumption -- after paying liberally for the management of their stores -- has been, on an average, a saving of fifteen per cent, in household expenditures, besides leaving considerable dividends of accumulated profits. They show what is still more important, that the Cooperative Union tends to create and to foster provident habits, and that among the workmen, who are members of the association, independence and self-reliance have fructified to an extent which it is difficult to estimate or describe.

abstract: Ladies' Views of the Rebellion; on NEW-YORK TIMES on Confederate Pirates
snippet: Ladies' Views of the Rebellion; on NEW-YORK TIMES on Confederate Pirates
lead_paragraph: We give place in another column to a somewhat doleful communication from a lady on the subject of her political sympathies. Domestic ties compel her to endure in silence the reproaches cast upon her Southern compatriots by those she is bound to honor and obey. Her love for those most closely related to her obliges her to smother her rebellious yearnings. In short, she has to endure the irrepressible agony -- that agony which a true woman probably best understands -- of being dumb, and opening not her mouth. There is much to commend in the steadfastness and resolution with which our correspondent maintains her reserve. It shows that at heart she is loyal; that she has a sensible appreciation of domestic quiet; and that there is one union, at least, which she will not consent to see broken in twain.

abstract: ELLEN HANFORD was arraigned on Friday at the Jefferson Market Police Court, charged, on the complaint of JAMES T. ROWE, of West Fifty-eighth-street, with having stolen from him a gold watch and chain valued at $150 and $85 in greenbacks, she having first drugged a bottle of wine of which he partook, and in three minutes after, as he testified, he became insensible and did not recover until several hours after. The wine was drank, it seems, in a saloon in Le Rovplace, kept by one ADOLPH CHAVEY. The latter testified that ELLEN yesterday morning exhibited to him a watch and chain similar to the one lost by Rows. The accused was committed in default of $1,000 bail. The property has not been recovered.

abstract: Foreign Office and Board of Trade--New Regulations
snippet: Foreign Office and Board of Trade--New Regulations
lead_paragraph: It has been a grievance of long standing with British merchants at home and abroad that the Consular service, as heretofore regulated and controlled by the Foreign Office, is far less efficient than it might be made were the Consular agents put into more direct communication with the Board of Trade. The Foreign Minister, by long unquestioned usage, has been in the habit of consulting with the President of the Board of Trade when important questions of commercial interest had to be decided. But the arrangement has been altogether of a loose sort. Commercial men, having a grievance at some foreign part, have scarcely known how to apply for a remedy. At the Foreign Office there, was often no one to whom technical points of commercial law were so familiar as to enable the information to be readily given. Their, if the matter was referred to the Board of Trade, there were necessarily further vexatious delays interposed, and even the Board of Trade could not give a final decision without another consultation with the Foreign Office. One office could interpret the case, and report upon it to the satisfaction of the applicant. But the ultimate decision could only be reached through the other office. It was altogether a shuttlecock business, harassing and moat unsatisfactory.

abstract: Gen Dix's Order
snippet: Gen Dix's Order
lead_paragraph: We gave yesterday some startling facts, to which this morning we append others, concerning the concerted effort made on Friday night by persons supposed to be rebel sympathisers, to burn the hotels and other buildings of this city. It will be seen that Gen. DIX has promptly taken the matter in hand, and has issued two orders upon the subject, of great stringency, but absolutely necessary. "Order No. 92" mentions the nefarious attempt and its frightful perils -- states that the evidences of extensive combination and other facts disclosed yesterday, show it to have been the work of rebel emissaries; and then adds that "all such persons engaged in secret acts of hostility can only be regarded as spies subject to martial law, and to the penalty of death. On conviction before a court-martial" says Gen. DIX, "they will be executed without the delay of a single day."

abstract: "Don Sebastian" will be given to-night for the second time In America. We have already spoken of the remarkable splendor of the production, of the merit of the music, and of the excellence of the singers. A work of such importance is seldom heard to advantage on the first night. It improves as the artists become familiar with their parts, and the audience displays its preference for particular morceaux. We anticipate a perfect rendering of the work to-night, and a success even more marked and emphatic than that of Friday. No opera has ever been given at the Academy of Music that contains so much for the eye and the ear.

abstract: and Hood's Advance; Rebel Press have no News; Exchange of, Stopped by Sherman's Advance
snippet: and Hood's Advance; Rebel Press have no News; Exchange of, Stopped by Sherman's Advance
lead_paragraph: We have never during the course of the war had anything analogous to the military situation as it is at present in the Southwest. The two great armies which so long confronted one another, and which fought each other from Nashville to Atlanta, have parted company, and each has started off in a direction opposite to the other -- one striking southward through Georgia for the Atlantic coast, and the other striking northward of the great central mountain range for Middle Tennessee. One of the Richmond papers remarked the other day how strangely ignorant both sides were concerning the movements of these great forces. The rebels have known but little about the operations of HOOD's army, and now that SHERMAN has cut their telegraph lines in Georgia, they will know little more about HOOD than we know about SHERMAN; and it is likely that, what information they do obtain will be got through Union mediums, just as our information about SHERMAN is got through rebel mediums.

abstract: Incendiary Plot; Gen Dix's Orders
snippet: Incendiary Plot; Gen Dix's Orders
lead_paragraph: The seasonable orders issued by Gen. DIX on Saturday, did much to allay public excitement in regard to the possible scope of the plot from which the city had so narrow an escape. It was felt on all hands that, however prompt and effective the joint action of the authorities of the Police and Fire Departments proved to be, when the first alarm was given, it was an act of wisdom to let it be known that the criminals would be summarily tried before a military tribunal, treated as rebel spies if found guilty, and thereupon hanged with dispatch. Equally reassuring to the public is Gen. DIX's supplementary order, requiring that persons arriving here from the insurgent States, shall promptly register their names at Gen. PECK's headquarters, in order to avoid being regarded as spies and treated accordingly. A wholesome application of military law will do an uncommon amount of good at this particular juncture. The city is literally swarming with rebel adventurers, of an irresponsible and dangerous class. And their case can only be promptly reached by the strong authority of which Gen. DIX is the immedidiate representative.

lead_paragraph: Savannah papers of the 23d contain dispatches from Augusta, to the effect that Milledgeville and Gordon were captured by Gen. SHERMAN on the 21st. The State-house, Governor's mansion and the penitentiary were committed to the flames. The Augusta Constitutional, of the 21st, reports that the Oconee bridge, five miles above Gordon, was burned at noon of that day, by a small party of our cavalry, who retired after performing their work. This is, no doubt, the "repulse" of our cavalry, reported by the Richmond press with so much satisfaction.

abstract: New-York; Incendiary Plot; Gen. Dix's Order
snippet: New-York; Incendiary Plot; Gen. Dix's Order
lead_paragraph: Since the full account published in the TIMES yesterday of the diabolical attempt to burn this city, nothing of special importance has transpired. It is settled, however, beyond a doubt, that the infernal plot was the deliberate work of Southern traitors, who had for their object the complete destruction of the city. Several arrests have been made, and the prospects are fair for the securing of a majority of the criminals, who, according to the order of Gen. Dix, published below, will, on conviction, be "executed without the delay of a single day." The police are in possession of important evidence, which it is not proper to give to the public now, but which promises the most satisfactory results. The principal hotels fired -- the Astor St. Nicholas, Fifth-avenue. Lafarge, St. James, Metropolitan. Howard, United States, Lovejoy's, Tammany, Belmont and Hanford, are secure against any further incendiary attempts.

snippet: Surgeon's Report on our Prisoners; at Andersonville, >amp;c; Rebel Surgeons' Report on
lead_paragraph: Before the rebel authorities were compelled, by reason of the fearful pestilence that raged within it, to break open the prison pen at Andersonville, the bodies of eleven thousand loyal soldiers had been thrown, uncoffined, into the shallow trenches surrounding the stockade. The names of three thousand of those who thus miserably perished under the inhuman treatment of their captors, we publish in other columns this morning. It is a saddening record, and yet, its publication will doubtloss relieve many of the friends and relatives of our poor martyred soldiers from the horrors of despairing hope and suspense, in regard to the fate of those they love.

abstract: Jersey City--Infant by Drunken Father
snippet: Jersey City--Infant by Drunken Father
lead_paragraph: AN INFANT'S BRAINS KNOCKED OUT BY ITS FATHER. -- On Saturday afternoon, a man named BERNARD FITZPATRICK residing at No. 113 Morganstreet, Jersey City, in a building known as " Marine Terrace," while under the influence of liquor, threw a stove lid at his wife, which struck her infant daughter, 18 months of age, in her arms, and dashed its brains out. The child died in halt an hour afterward. FITZPATRICK, upon realizing what he had done, left the house, threatening to destroy his own life, but was taken in custody shortly afterward at the corner of Provost and South Eighth streets, by Officers J. NUGENT and COTTRELL. An inquest was held by Coroner FARREL yesterday afternoon. MARGARET FITZPATRICK, wife of the prisoner, testified that her husband had been on a spree all last week, and when under the influence of liquor acted in a crazy manner and was quarrelsome; on Saturday he drank liquor, and in the afternoon slept about an hour on the floor, when he woke up and told his wife to send the boy out for more liquor; she refused, and told him that he was a drunken loafer. and then went down stairs with her infant; when nearly at the foot of the stairs, she saw the blood flowing from her child's head, and heard something drop on the floor, which she did not see, but believed it was a piece of the stove; she called for help and then returned to the room, when her husband exclaimed, "My God, have I done that to my child?" and then went out; the child died shortly after. Dr. WALTER J. HADDAN, who was called in, testified that when he arrived at the house the child was dying; he examined the wound and found a compound fracture of the skull, and a portion of the brains were protruding; the injury seemed to have been done by some blunt instrument; the wound was about three inches in length, and in an oblique direction, as though something had been thrown. The jury rendered a verdict that they believed that ELIZABETH FITZPATRICK came to her death by a blow from a piece of stove at the hands of her father. Upon the rendition of the verdict, Coroner FARREL committed the prisoner to the County Jail for trial.

lead_paragraph: We publish, to-day, two partially conflicting accounts respecting the exchange of prisoners at Savannah. In the Richmond Dispatch of Friday, it is stated that the exchange goes on well; that thirty-two hundred Confederates have been delivered by our agent, and that Capt. HATCH (the rebel agent) is engaged in making an equal return of our prisoners at the South. The news which we get by way of Annapolis and Baltimore is doubtless later, and presents a more correct view of the situation. By vessels which arrived yesterday at Annapolis with twelve hundred and forty six of OUT men, comes the report that with the reception of this batch of prisoners in Savannah River on the 25th, the announcement was made by the rebel agent that the exchange had ceased. The reason assigned for this was that SHERMAN had cut off the railroads leading from Savannah, and had, as it was thought, reached the place where the remainder of OUT prisoners in the State ate confined. SHERMAN, by this report, is made to appear as having been within six hours' march of the Stockade at Millen, at the latest report on Friday last. To this is appended the conjectural statement that the rebels would make an effort to remove our prisoners to Florida before SHERMAN should reach them. Millen, where the bulk of our prisoners are kept, is directly in SHERMAN's road toward Savannah, after leaving ???lledgeville, And if he was within six hours' march of the place on Friday last, he has made, ere now, two-thirds of his journey from Atlanta to the coast, supposing Savannah to be his main objective point.

abstract: Carriage Way Wanted
snippet: Carriage Way Wanted
lead_paragraph: -- We very cordially second the demand of a morning cotemporary for some safe way of traversing the city lengthwise, by carriages. Broadway, and the Fifth-avenue, which is substantially its continuation, ought to be reserved permanently for this purpose. The present pavements, moreover, have proved wholly unsuitable and unsafe, and ought to be superseded by something better adapted to the purpose. The suggestion that they should be macadamized or supplied with a road-bed of gravel and asphaltum, is a good one. In Paris these roads have been found dryer, more durable, and in every way better than the ordinary stone pavements; and the experience afforded by the Central Park is very greatly in their favor.

abstract: Slow Progress; a Slight Rebel Mistake
snippet: Slow Progress; a Slight Rebel Mistake
lead_paragraph: -- The Richmond papers of the 25th attempt to draw comfort from what they are pleased to term "SHERMAN's slow progress." They state that up to the 25th he had advanced but seventy-five miles, and had been out fifteen days. The rebels are mistaken. SHERMAN did not leave Atlanta until Nov. 14, and part of his force even not until the 15th. So that, at the outside, he had not been out more than eleven days, up to the 25th. Now, according to rebel reports, SHERMAN's forces captured Milledgeville and Gordon on the twenty-first, only seven days after he set out from Atlanta; and on the 23d our cavalry occupied Toomsboro, on the Georgia Central Railroad, fifteen miles east of Gordon. The distance from Atlanta to Savannah, via Macon, is 284 miles; the distance from Atlanta to Gordon is 124 miles, but Gen. SHERMAN shortened this distance about fifteen miles by avoiding Macon. Nevertheless, the rebels own reports prove that he had actually moved one hundred and ten miles in seven days, more than fulfilling his marching order, which was that the army should average fifteen miles per day. It has been done, and more too. The rebels will possibly find that SHERMAN's march is quite rapid enough to suit his purposes and their most ardent wishes.

abstract: Probabilities of
snippet: Probabilities of
lead_paragraph: There seems to be a temporary lull in the newspaper speculation about changes in the Cabinet. Ten days ago it was announced, with the utmost positiveness, that Mr. STANTON was at once to give place to Gen. BUTLER, Mr. FESSENDEN to R.J. WALKER, and Mr. SEWARD to C.F. Adams. Not a single one of these changes had been proposed or even talked about by the President, or by any of the parties concerned; but this made not the slightest difference. The outside public knew all about it, and the newspapers told all about it -- with just as much confidence and assurance as if it had all been true.

abstract: Emancipation in Maryland Celebration at Cooper Institute
snippet: Emancipation in Maryland Celebration at Cooper Institute
lead_paragraph: A large and highly respectable meeting of our colored citizens was held last evening in the hall of the Cooper Institute, for the purpose of celebrating the passing of emancipation in Maryland. On the platform were seated many of the sons and daughters of Maryland, whose presence gave an additional interest to the evening's proceedings. A circle of young ladies attired in white emblematical of the States that endured and re-instated Mr. LINCOLN, supporting the Goddess of Liberty, were also seated on the platform presenting an annuated scene.

abstract: Rose, John, of Montreal, and San Juan Difficulty
snippet: Rose, John, of Montreal, and San Juan Difficulty
lead_paragraph: One Mr. JOHN ROSE, of Montreal, we observe, has been appointed a commissioner to settle certain disputes (imaginary, we trust) between the United States and Great Britain Among other disputes Mr. ROSE is to arrange the "San Juan difficulty!" There is something consoling in the assurance that all these difficulties -- whatever they may be -- are to be settled by so sweet an individual. The rose by any other name might possibly not smell as sweet. This estimable ROSE, it is said, was chief butler to the Prince of WALES during his Canada sojourn. The appointment may, therefore, be considered as having been made sub rosa. How the "San Juan difficulty" happens to loom up at this particular moment we do not precisely know. Less than a quarter of a century ago it was supposed to have been disposed of, when Gen. SCOTT went to the Pacific to take HARNEY's place as a diplomatist. But it seems to have cropped out again in some unexpected quarter, and it is not improbable that we shall have to exhaust the resources of statesmanship in holding our own against the biandishments of this new British Commissioner, redolent of the Royal Kitchen, and fragrant with the bouquet of the choice vintage. Swee Rose! All hail!

lead_paragraph: Richmond papers of the 26th are received, but, according to a previously expressed threat, preserve entire silence as to military movements in Georgia. They assert that any news of SHERMAN'S whereabouts would be of incalcutable value to us, and they therefore will not give it. Of course, it is not to be supposed for a moment that if the rebels had any news favorable to their side, but that they would out with it in a paroxysm of joy. SHERMAN is making himself felt in the very vitals of the rebellion, and all the sophistry of all the rebels in the Confederacy can't conceal it. SHERMAN will be heard from a great deal sooner than the rebels care for.

abstract: JOHN YOUNG, Chief of the Detective force, and Detectives BENRETT and McDOUGALL, are making very great exertions, and are sparing no pains or expanse to discover and bring to merited punishment the persons who last Friday night, attempted to destroy this ...
lead_paragraph: JOHN YOUNG, Chief of the Detective force, and Detectives BENRETT and McDOUGALL, are making very great exertions, and are sparing no pains or expanse to discover and bring to merited punishment the persons who last Friday night, attempted to destroy this by fire. In addition to the arrests previously reported, Chief YOUNG and his officers yesterday succeeded in apprehending two suspicious Southern refugees, who; since their arrival in the city some months ago, have been leading an idle and dissolated life. From motives of public policy, we are requested not to publish at present the names of the prisoners, nor disclose the evidence which the officers have in their possession connecting these men with the act of incendiarism in vuestion. It is understood that Mayor GUNTHER has offered a reward of $25,000 for the apprehension and conviction of the guilty persons.

lead_paragraph: A dispatch of Rear-Admiral PORTER to the Navy Department, dated on yesterday, at Fortress Monroe, announces the sinking nine fathoms deep of the rebel privateer Florida, which has been lying in Hampton Roads for a fortnight past, or since she was brought back by the Wachusett from Brazil. The rebel craft, it seems, was run into by one of the innumerable army steamers which are perpetually coursing through the waters in which she lay; but the particulars of her destruction had not been received by Admiral PORTER up to yesterday.

abstract: and the Incendiaries; Refusal to Celebrate Victories by a Tallow Candle
snippet: and the Incendiaries; Refusal to Celebrate Victories by a Tallow Candle
lead_paragraph: Mayor GUNTHER, it will be seen, recommends the Common Council to appropriate $25,000 for the conviction, according to due process of law, of the rebel incendiaries. His Honor maintains a consistent record. He finds that Gen. DIX'S orders might possibly conflict with the interests of those in whom His Honor has always shown an especial interest. He makes the proviso, therefore, in his message to the Common Council, that the reward shall be contingent upon a conviction according to ordinary process of law. If Gen. DIX, through his military detectives, succeeds in capturing any of the rebel spies engaged in the conspiracy of Friday night, and if these spies should be tried, convicted and hung according to military law, the Mayor's proposed reward shall be void.

abstract: Southerners in New-York, and their Spite; Rebel Attempt to Burn, and Southerners in
snippet: Southerners in New-York, and their Spite; Rebel Attempt to Burn, and Southerners in
lead_paragraph: The attempt of Southern desperadoes to lay our city in ashes raises, serious questions concerning the tens of thousands of Southern people we have been harboring. Hitherto this crowd has not excited much concern. The forbearance of our community toward them has been in the most marked contrast to the treatment received by Northern men resident in the South. Multitudes of these latter were prevented at the outbreak of the rebellion from coming North, and were forced into the rebel armies to serve a cause they abhorred. No small number of them, who would not turn against their old flag, were lynched to death; their property was all confiscated, and their families were left to starve. The amount of infernal wrong perpetrated upon the Northerners in the Southern States is incalculable.

abstract: CITIZENS' ASSOCIATION.--Last evening the council and various boards of the Citizens' Association met in their rooms, No. 813 Broadway, to hear an explanation of the operations of the Association, and an account of what had been done toward the improvement of the Municipal
lead_paragraph: CITIZENS' ASSOCIATION. -- Last evening the council and various boards of the Citizens' Association met in their rooms, No. 813 Broadway, to hear an explanation of the operations of the Association, and an account of what had been done toward the improvement of the Municipal Government. Among the distinguished gentlemen present there were Hon. D. STRONG, Rev. Dr. JERVIS, Chancellor of the University of New-York; Dr. W. NICAE, of Columbia College; NATHANIEL SANDS, Esq., J. STURGES, Esq., R.B. ROOSEVELT, Esq., CHARLES O'CONOR, Esq., and others. The meeting having been called to order, JONATHAN STURGES was chosen Chairman. R.B. ROOSEVELT acted as Secretary. An interesting and elaborate report was read by Mr. ROOSEVELT, which embraced the various proceedings of the association since its commencement, the establishment of a Sanitary Bureau, together with subjects for sanitary inquiry, all bearing on the health of the city. The meeting was then addressed by Dr. THOMPSON, Secretary of the Sanitary Bureau, who explained in a very lucid manner the several steps adopted in obtaining the sanitary reports of the present state of the city. In the course of his remarks, Dr. THOMPSON paid a just and well-merited compliment to the various medical gentlemen throughout the city, who had voluntarily engaged in the work of visiting the localities of the city where sickness most prevailed, and supplying the councils of the association with valuable information, particularly as to tenement houses, the number of families therein and space allotted to each, and other subjects for sanitary inquiry. In the course of his remarks, the Doctor exhibited to the meeting a carefully prepared sanitary map of the City, showing where sickness and mortality most prevailed. The Doctor concluded his interesting address amid great applause. Dr. SMITH in a few remarks pointed out to the meeting the great labors of the association, alluding to the fearful deathrate of the city, and the necessity of active measures being adopted in checking the ravages of the disease. Gen. VIELE, in a few remarks, explained what had been done in the Engineer Department of the association. After which, NATHANIEL SANDS, Esq., stated that a mass meeting of the association would be held at the Cooper Institute on Thursday evening, and called on all to support the nominations of the association. The meeting then adjourned.

lead_paragraph: The Swedish steam frigate Vanadis, Capt. MELANDER, arrived at this port late on Monday evening, and anchored, having been 35 days from Plymouth, England. She comes over here on a tour of inspection and to give her officers an opportunity to see some of the scenes of the present war. Sweden has taken much interest in our naval affairs, and has for a long time had a resident naval officer, Count ROSEN, in our midst, who has carefully noted all events as they transpired, and forwarded them to his Government at home. He visited all our navy-yards, arsenals, ship-yards, was present at the trial trips of iron-clads, and even made a passage in one of them from New-York to Fortress Monroe. The little corvette Gifte brought toe Count to our shores, and after a brief stay, returned home. We now have the Vanadis with us. Yesterday morning she hoisted the American flag at her fore and saluted it and Admiral PAULDING at about 9 o'clock, and immediately after the Vanadis ceased firing, the naval battery at the Navy-yard returned the salute gun for gun, the royal Swedish ensign being displayed from the fore truck of the North Carolina, Capt. J.P. MCKINSTRY. In due time the Swedish officers will pay an official visit to Admiral PAULDING, and be tendered the hospitalities of the station.

abstract: There is nothing later from Gen. SHERMAN, no rebel papers having been received within the past twenty-four hours. The very latest rebel intelligence from either column of Gen. SHERMAN'S army placed Gen. SLOCOUM'S column at Greensboro, on the Georgia State Railroad, ...
lead_paragraph: There is nothing later from Gen. SHERMAN, no rebel papers having been received within the past twenty-four hours. The very latest rebel intelligence from either column of Gen. SHERMAN's army placed Gen. SLOCUM's column at Greensboro, on the Georgia State Railroad, eighty-four miles west of Augusta, on the 20th; Gen. HOWARD's column at Toomsboro, on the Georgia Central Railroad, one hundred and forty-five miles from Savannah, on the 22d. Both columns had crossed the Ocomulgee and Oconee Rivers, the two principal streams on the route of the march, and both columns were, at the dates mentioned, fully half way to Savannah, and the announcement of the fall of Augusta may be expected at any hour. ROGER A. PRYOR, the ex-rebel General, who was captured on Sunflay while endeavoring to exchange newspapers on the picket line, admits that SHERMAN will, if he has not already, capture Augusta, and that he cannot meet any serious resistance in his march to the coast.

abstract: Hon. WILLIAM G. MOORHEAD, late President of the Philadelphia and Erie Railroad, will sail, accompanied by his family, in the steamer for Liverpool, to-day. While Mr. MOORHEAD's chief object is that rest and relaxation from business cares to be found in foreign travel, he has in view several important financial projects connected with the development of railroad and mining interests in this country, and the formation of such alliances with European skill and capital as will produce the highest results. Mr. MOORHEAD has been concerned in some of the largest and most important business interests in the United States.
